{"title_page": "Shrewsbury Castle", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox military structure\n|name=Shrewsbury Castle\n|partof=\n|location=[[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]]\n|map_type=Shropshire\n|map_alt=\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.7077|-2.7541|display=inline,title}}\n|image=Shrewsbury Schloss.JPG\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Shrewsbury Castle\n|condition=\n|ownership=[[Shropshire Council]]\n|built=1070\n{{Infobox historic site\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = UK Grade I\n| designation1_offname = \n| designation1_date = 10 January 1953\n| designation1_number = 1246877\n}}\n}}\n'''Shrewsbury Castle''' is a red [[sandstone]] [[castle]] in [[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]], [[England]]. It stands on a hill in the neck of the meander of the [[River Severn]] on which the town originally developed. The castle, directly above [[Shrewsbury railway station]], is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref name=listed>{{National Heritage List for England |num=1246877 |access-date=8 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shrewsbury Castle 01943.jpg|thumb|left|Shrewsbury Castle, c.1778]]\n[[File:Shrewsbury Castle 2.jpg|thumb|left|Shrewsbury Castle viewed from Laura's Tower]]\nA castle was ordered on the site by William I c. 1067 - a very early date - but it was greatly extended under [[Roger de Montgomery]] circa 1070 as a base for operations into Wales, an administrative centre and as a defensive [[fortification]] for the town, which was otherwise protected by the loop of the river.<ref name=listed/> [[Town wall]]s, of which little now remains, were later added to the defences, as a response to Welsh raids and radiated out from the castle and surrounded the town; the area known as Town Walls still has a small section of them and a single tower, known as [[Town Walls Tower]], which is in the care of the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]]). In 1138, [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]] successfully besieged the castle held by William FitzAlan for the [[Empress Maud]] during the period known as [[The Anarchy]].<ref name=wales>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlewales.com/shrwsbry.html |title=Shrewsbury Castle|publisher=Castle Wales|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe castle was briefly held by [[Llywelyn the Great]], [[Prince of Wales]], in 1215.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://originalshrewsbury.co.uk/shrewsbury-historic-timeline|title=Historic Timeline|publisher=Original Shrewsbury|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Parts of the original medieval structure remain largely incorporating the inner bailey of the castle; the outer bailey, which extended into the town, has long ago vanished under the encroachment of later shops and buildings.<ref name=wales/> Having fallen into decay after c. 1300 (at the end of the Welsh wars) the castle became a domestic residence during the reign of Elizabeth I and passed to the ownership of the town council c.1600. The castle was extensively repaired in 1643 during the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] and was briefly besieged by Parliamentary forces from Wem before its surrender. It was acquired by [[Francis Newport, 1st Earl of Bradford|Sir Francis Newport]] in 1663.<ref name=wales/> Further repairs were carried out by [[Thomas Telford]] on behalf of [[Sir William Pulteney, 5th Baronet|Sir William Pulteney]], M.P. for Shrewsbury, after 1780.<ref name=listed/> It remained as a private residence until after WW1.\n\nThe Shropshire Horticultural Society purchased the castle from a private owner and gave it to the town in 1924.<ref name=listed/> and it became the location of Shrewsbury Town Council chambers for over 50 years. The castle was internally restructured to become the home of the '''Shropshire Regimental Museum''' when it moved from [[Copthorne Barracks]] and othe rlocal sites in 1985.<ref name=listed/> The museum was [[Chronology of Provisional Irish Republican Army actions (1990\u201399)|attacked]] by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] on 25 August 1992 and extensive damage to the collection and to some of the Castle resulted.<ref name=inde>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/firebomb-attack-at-army-museum-linked-to-ira-1542518.html|title=Firebomb attack at army museum linked to IRA|date=26 August 1992|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> The museum was officially re-opened by [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] on 2 May 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.military-history.org/articles/shropshire-regimental-museum.htm|title=Shropshire Regimental Museum|publisher=Military History Monthly|date=10 November 2010|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Shropshire Star |date=3 May 1995 |page=8 |edition=Midday|title=Royal praise for rebuilt museum}}</ref>\n\n==Collection==\nThe museum combines the collections of the [[King's Shropshire Light Infantry]] and the [[Shropshire Yeomanry]].<ref name=inde/> Laura's Tower overlooks the surrounding townscape and countryside and is often used as a backdrop for functions and [[marriage|weddings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truereflections.co.uk/shrewsbury-castle-wedding-photography-helen-and-ian/|title=Shrewsbury Castle Wedding Photography|publisher=True Reflections|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Shrewsbury]]\n*[[Listed buildings in Shrewsbury (southeast central area)]]\n*[[King's Shropshire Light Infantry]]\n*[[Ludlow Castle]], another English [[Welsh Marches|Marches]] stronghold\n*''[[One Corpse Too Many]]'' - historical fiction based on 1138 battle between King Stephen and supporters of the Empress Maud\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.shrewsburymuseum.org.uk/visit-shrewsbury/shrewsbury-castle/ Shrewsbury Castle] - official site with visiting information and Shropshire Regimental Museum\n*[http://www.shropshireregimentalmuseum.co.uk/ Shropshire Regimental Museum collections]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLK_uHVQZB__CV5ZdK4AtzxaezAs_dD1tX Dig diaries from the 2019 excavations]\n\n{{Shrewsbury architecture}}\n\n[[Category:Castles in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Shrewsbury]]\n[[Category:Museums in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in Shropshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox military structure\n|name=Shrewsbury Castle\n|partof=\n|location=[[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]]\n|map_type=Shropshire\n|map_alt=\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.7077|-2.7541|display=inline,title}}\n|image=Shrewsbury Schloss.JPG\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=Shrewsbury Castle\n|condition=\n|ownership=[[Shropshire Council]]\n|built=1070\n{{Infobox historic site\n| embed = yes\n| designation1 = UK Grade I\n| designation1_offname = \n| designation1_date = 10 January 1953\n| designation1_number = 1246877\n}}\n}}\n'''Shrewsbury Castle''' is a red [[sandstone]] [[castle]] in [[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]], [[England]]. It stands on a hill in the neck of the meander of the [[River Severn]] on which the town originally developed. The castle, directly above [[Shrewsbury railway station]], is a Grade I [[listed building]].<ref name=listed>{{National Heritage List for England |num=1246877 |access-date=8 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shrewsbury Castle 01943.jpg|thumb|left|Shrewsbury Castle, c.1778]]\n[[File:Shrewsbury Castle 2.jpg|thumb|left|Shrewsbury Castle viewed from Laura's Tower]]\nA castle was ordered on the site by William I c. 1067 - a very early date - but it was greatly extended under [[Roger de Montgomery]] circa 1070 as a base for operations into Wales, an administrative centre and as a defensive [[fortification]] for the town, which was otherwise protected by the loop of the river.<ref name=listed/> [[Town wall]]s, of which little now remains, were later added to the defences, as a response to Welsh raids and radiated out from the castle and surrounded the town; the area known as Town Walls still has a small section of them and a single tower, known as [[Town Walls Tower]], which is in the care of the [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]]). In 1138, [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]] successfully besieged the castle held by William FitzAlan for the [[Empress Maud]] during the period known as [[The Anarchy]].<ref name=wales>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlewales.com/shrwsbry.html |title=Shrewsbury Castle|publisher=Castle Wales|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe castle was briefly held by [[Llywelyn the Great]], [[Prince of Wales]], in 1215.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://originalshrewsbury.co.uk/shrewsbury-historic-timeline|title=Historic Timeline|publisher=Original Shrewsbury|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> Parts of the original medieval physical structure remain largely incorporsating the inner bailey of the castle; the outer bailey, which extended into the town, has long ago vanished under the encroachment of later shops and buildings.<ref name=wales/> Having fallen into decay after c. 1300 (at the end of the Welsh wars) the castle became a domestic residence during the reign of Elizabeth I and passed to the ownership of the town council c.1600. The castle was extensively repaired in 1643 during the [[English Civil War|Civil War]] and was briefly besieged by Parliamentary forces from Wem before its surrender. It was acquired by [[Francis Newport, 1st Earl of Bradford|Sir Francis Newport]] in 1663.<ref name=wales/> Further repairs were carried out by [[Thomas Telford]] on behalf of [[Sir William Pulteney, 5th Baronet|Sir William Pulteney]], M.P. for Shrewsbury, after 1780.<ref name=listed/> It remained as a private residence until after WW1.\n\nThe Shropshire Horticultural Society purchased the castle from a private owner and gave it to the town in 1924.<ref name=listed/> and it became the location of Shrewsbury Town Council chambers for over 50 years. The castle was internally restructured to become the home of the '''Shropshire Regimental Museum''' when it moved from [[Copthorne Barracks]] and othe rlocal sites in 1985.<ref name=listed/> The museum was [[Chronology of Provisional Irish Republican Army actions (1990\u201399)|attacked]] by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] on 25 August 1992 and extensive damage to the collection and to some of the Castle resulted.<ref name=inde>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/firebomb-attack-at-army-museum-linked-to-ira-1542518.html|title=Firebomb attack at army museum linked to IRA|date=26 August 1992|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref> The museum was officially re-opened by [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] on 2 May 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.military-history.org/articles/shropshire-regimental-museum.htm|title=Shropshire Regimental Museum|publisher=Military History Monthly|date=10 November 2010|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |work=Shropshire Star |date=3 May 1995 |page=8 |edition=Midday|title=Royal praise for rebuilt museum}}</ref>\n\n==Collection==\nThe museum combines the collections of the [[King's Shropshire Light Infantry]] and the [[Shropshire Yeomanry]].<ref name=inde/> Laura's Tower overlooks the surrounding townscape and countryside and is often used as a backdrop for functions and [[marriage|weddings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.truereflections.co.uk/shrewsbury-castle-wedding-photography-helen-and-ian/|title=Shrewsbury Castle Wedding Photography|publisher=True Reflections|accessdate=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Shrewsbury]]\n*[[Listed buildings in Shrewsbury (southeast central area)]]\n*[[King's Shropshire Light Infantry]]\n*[[Ludlow Castle]], another English [[Welsh Marches|Marches]] stronghold\n*''[[One Corpse Too Many]]'' - historical fiction based on 1138 battle between King Stephen and supporters of the Empress Maud\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.shrewsburymuseum.org.uk/visit-shrewsbury/shrewsbury-castle/ Shrewsbury Castle] - official site with visiting information and Shropshire Regimental Museum\n*[http://www.shropshireregimentalmuseum.co.uk/ Shropshire Regimental Museum collections]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLK_uHVQZB__CV5ZdK4AtzxaezAs_dD1tX Dig diaries from the 2019 excavations]\n\n{{Shrewsbury architecture}}\n\n[[Category:Castles in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Shrewsbury]]\n[[Category:Museums in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in Shropshire]]\n", "name_user": "Tofrek1885", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shrewsbury_Castle"}
{"title_page": "Francis Jayne", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|RRevd}}\n| name             = Francis Jayne\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|}}\n| image            = Bp Francis Jayne by Bassano.jpg\n| caption          = \n| title            = [[Bishop of Chester]]\n| diocese          = [[Diocese of Chester]]\n| term             = 1889\u20131919\n| predecessor      = [[William Stubbs]]\n| successor        = [[Luke Paget]]\n| other_post       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1845|01|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = Pant-y-beiliau, [[Llanelli]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1921|08|23|1845|01|01|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Oswestry]], [[Shropshire]]\n| buried           = [[Bowdon, Greater Manchester|Bowdon]], [[Cheshire]]\n| nationality      = [[British people|British]]\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = Emily Garland\n| children         = \n| profession       = \n| education        = [[Rugby School]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Wadham College, Oxford]]\n}}\n'''Francis John Jayne''' (1 January 1845 &ndash; 23 August 1921) was a British [[bishop]] and [[academic]].\n\nBorn in Pant-y-beiliau, [[Llanelli]], Jayne was the eldest son of John Jayne, a colliery owner and his second wife, Elisabeth Haines<ref name=\"ODNB\" />. He was educated at [[Rugby School]] and [[Wadham College, Oxford]]. He took his B.A. in 1868 and M.A. in 1870. He was elected Fellow of [[Jesus College, Oxford]] in 1868 and tutor of [[Keble College, Oxford|Keble College]] in 1871.<ref name=ODNB>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/34162|title=Jayne, Francis John (1845&ndash;1921)|first=D. T. W |last= Price|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] (online edition, subscription access)|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=January 2007|accessdate=2008-02-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-JAYN-JOH-1845|title=JAYNE, FRANCIS JOHN (1845 - 1921), bishop {{!}} Dictionary of Welsh Biography|website=biography.wales|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He was ordained deacon and priest in 1870.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFrom 1879 to 1886, Jayne was Principal of [[University of Wales, Lampeter|St David's College]], a university institution in the small Welsh town of [[Lampeter]]. During his time there, he steered the institution through the difficult years following the 1880 [[Aberdare report]] on intermediate and higher education in [[Wales]]. The report recommended that the Colleges at [[Aberystwyth]] and Lampeter be united to form one institution, but Jayne fought the plan and retained St. David's College's independence.  Jayne reformed the college in many ways; new statutes were issued and affiliation to Oxford and Cambridge was achieved.  A new hall of residence was constructed and the college chapel was rebuilt.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />  The number of students doubled.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Death of Bishop Jayne|date=25 August 1921|work=Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The college school opened in 1884, with the aim of providing a sound education for future entrants to the college.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />  Jayne is remembered as the 'second founder' of the college.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nA devoutly religious man, Jayne left Lampeter to become an [[Anglican]] [[vicar]] in [[Leeds]]. He became [[Bishop of Chester]] in 1889, a position he held for the next thirty years. At the time of his appointment, he was the youngest English bishop<ref name=\":1\" />. Under his rule, his diocese was said to be 'perhaps the most peaceful and orderly in England.'<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Bishop Jayne|date=25 August 1921|work=Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He resigned his bishopric in April 1919 owing to ill health.  He died at his home at The Quarry, [[Oswestry]], and was buried at [[Bowdon, Greater Manchester|Bowdon]], [[Cheshire]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000576/19210825/121/0006|work=Aberdeen Journal|title=The Right Rev. Francis John Jayne|date=25 August 1921|publisher=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nJayne was concerned about excessive drinking and the misuse of alcohol. He published an article called ''Successful Public-House Reform''<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/25103324 Francis John Jayne, 'Successful Public-House Reform' in ''The North American Review'' 158, no. 450 (1894): 520-28]\n</ref> discussing the virtues of the Scandinavian [[Gothenburg system]] for managing pubs etc. He also founded the People's Refreshment House Association Limited which at its peak owned 130 inns and hotels.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\nHe and his wife Emily (n\u00e9e Garland) had six sons and three daughters,<ref name=ODNB/> one of whom was the Norwegian-to-English translator Edith M. G. Jayne.<ref>'The Late Miss Jayne' in the ''Chester Chronicle'', 20 January 1945, p8</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Francis John Jayne}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Llewelyn Lewellin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice-Chancellor of the University of Wales, Lampeter|Principal of St David's College]]|years=1879\u20131886}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Herbert Ryle]]}}\n{{s-rel|en}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Stubbs]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Chester]]|years=1889\u20131919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Luke Paget]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Bishops of Chester since 1908}}\n{{Principals of St David's College}}\n]\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jayne, Francis John}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1921 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Chester]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Wales, Lampeter]]\n[[Category:People from Llanelli]]\n[[Category:Principals of St David's College]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox Christian leader\n| honorific-prefix = {{pre-nominal styles|RRevd}}\n| name             = Francis Jayne\n| honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|}}\n| image            = Bp Francis Jayne by Bassano.jpg\n| caption          = \n| title            = [[Bishop of Chester]]\n| diocese          = [[Diocese of Chester]]\n| term             = 1889\u20131919\n| predecessor      = [[William Stubbs]]\n| successor        = [[Luke Paget]]\n| other_post       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1845|01|01|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = Pant-y-beiliau, [[Llanelli]]\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1921|08|23|1845|01|01|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[Oswestry]], [[Shropshire]]\n| buried           = [[Bowdon, Greater Manchester|Bowdon]], [[Cheshire]]\n| nationality      = [[British people|British]]\n| religion         = [[Anglicanism|Anglican]]\n| residence        = \n| parents          = \n| spouse           = Emily Garland\n| children         = \n| profession       = \n| education        = [[Rugby School]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Wadham College, Oxford]]\n}}\n'''Francis John Jayne''' (1 January 1845 &ndash; 23 August 1921) was a British [[bishop]] and [[academic]].\n\nBorn in Pant-y-beiliau, [[Llanelli]], Jayne was the eldest son of John Jayne, a colliery owner and his second wife, Elisabeth Haines<ref name=\"ODNB\" />. He was educated at [[Rugby School]] and [[Wadham College, Oxford]]. He took his B.A. in 1868 and M.A. in 1870. He was elected Fellow of [[Jesus College, Oxford]] in 1868 and tutor of [[Keble College, Oxford|Keble College]] in 1871.<ref name=ODNB>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/34162|title=Jayne, Francis John (1845&ndash;1921)|first=D. T. W |last= Price|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] (online edition, subscription access)|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|date=January 2007|accessdate=2008-02-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-JAYN-JOH-1845|title=JAYNE, FRANCIS JOHN (1845 - 1921), bishop {{!}} Dictionary of Welsh Biography|website=biography.wales|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He was ordained deacon and priest in 1870.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFrom 1879 to 1886, Jayne was Principal of [[University of Wales, Lampeter|St David's College]], a university institution in the small Welsh town of [[Lampeter]]. During his time there, he steered the institution through the difficult years following the 1880 [[Aberdare report]] on intermediate and higher education in [[Wales]]. The report recommended that the Colleges at [[Aberystwyth]] and Lampeter be united to form one institution, but Jayne fought the plan and retained St. David's College's independence.  Jayne reformed the college in many ways; new statutes were issued and affiliation to Oxford and Cambridge was achieved.  A new hall of residence was constructed and the college chapel was rebuilt.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />  The number of students doubled.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Death of Bishop Jayne|date=25 August 1921|work=Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The college school opened in 1884, with the aim of providing a sound education for future entrants to the college.<ref name=\"ODNB\" />\n\nA devoutly religious man, Jayne left Lampeter to become an [[Anglican]] [[vicar]] in [[Leeds]]. He became [[Bishop of Chester]] in 1889, a position he held for the next thirty years. Under his rule, his diocese was said to be 'perhaps the most peaceful and orderly in England.'<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Bishop Jayne|date=25 August 1921|work=Telegraph|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He resigned his bishopric in April 1919 owing to ill health.  He died at his home at The Quarry, [[Oswestry]], and was buried at [[Bowdon, Greater Manchester|Bowdon]], [[Cheshire]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000576/19210825/121/0006|work=Aberdeen Journal|title=The Right Rev. Francis John Jayne|date=25 August 1921|publisher=[[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nJayne was concerned about excessive drinking and the misuse of alcohol. He published an article called ''Successful Public-House Reform''<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/25103324 Francis John Jayne, 'Successful Public-House Reform' in ''The North American Review'' 158, no. 450 (1894): 520-28]\n</ref> discussing the virtues of the Scandinavian [[Gothenburg system]] for managing pubs etc. He also founded the People's Refreshment House Association Limited which at its peak owned 130 inns and hotels.<ref name=ODNB/>\n\nHe and his wife Emily (n\u00e9e Garland) had six sons and three daughters,<ref name=ODNB/> one of whom was the Norwegian-to-English translator Edith M. G. Jayne.<ref>'The Late Miss Jayne' in the ''Chester Chronicle'', 20 January 1945, p8</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Francis John Jayne}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Llewelyn Lewellin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Vice-Chancellor of the University of Wales, Lampeter|Principal of St David's College]]|years=1879\u20131886}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Herbert Ryle]]}}\n{{s-rel|en}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William Stubbs]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Bishop of Chester]]|years=1889\u20131919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Luke Paget]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Bishops of Chester since 1908}}\n{{Principals of St David's College}}\n]\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jayne, Francis John}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1921 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Rugby School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wadham College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Jesus College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Bishops of Chester]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Wales, Lampeter]]\n[[Category:People from Llanelli]]\n[[Category:Principals of St David's College]]\n", "name_user": "R