ve.org/web/20110830150538/http://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox/half-life-2 |archivedate=August 30, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.valvesoftware.com/games/hl2.html}}\n\n{{Half-Life}}\n{{Valve}}\n{{DICE GOTY}}\n{{BAFTA Games BG}}\n{{GDCA GOTY}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Video games}}\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-Half-Life 2.ogg|2006-12-22}}\n{{Wikiquote|Half-Life#Half-Life 2 (2004)|''Half-Life 2 (2004)''}}\n\n[[Category:2004 video games]]\n[[Category:AIAS Game of the Year winners]]\n[[Category:Alien invasions in video games]]\n[[Category:Amputees in fiction]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Dystopian video games]]\n[[Category:First-person shooters]]\n[[Category:Half-Life (series)]]\n[[Category:Interactive Achievement Award winners]]\n[[Category:Laboratories in fiction]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Oculus Rift games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Post-apocalyptic video games]]\n[[Category:Propaganda in fiction]]\n[[Category:Rebellions in fiction]]\n[[Category:Science fiction video games]]\n[[Category:Single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Source (game engine) games]]\n[[Category:Sterilization in fiction]]\n[[Category:Teleportation in fiction]]\n[[Category:Trains in fiction]]\n[[Category:Valve Corporation games]]\n[[Category:Video game sequels]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Europe]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Video games using Havok]]\n[[Category:Video games with variable translation control]]\n[[Category:Wars in fiction]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox games]]\n", "name_user": "2602:304:ab8a:b8f9:8537:de65:883c:4589", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half-Life_2"}
{"title_page": "Environmental impact of fishing", "text_new": "[[File:Fishing down the food web.jpg|thumb|350px|{{center|[[Fishing down the foodweb]]}}]]\n\nThe '''environmental impact of fishing''' includes issues such as the availability of [[fish]], [[overfishing]], [[fisheries]], and [[fisheries management]]; as well as the impact of [[industrial fishing]] on other elements of the environment, such as [[by-catch]]. These issues are part of [[marine conservation]], and are addressed in [[fisheries science]] programs. According to a 2019 [[FAO]] report, global production of fish, crustaceans, molluscs and other aquatic animals has continued to grow and reached 172.6 million tonnes in 2017, with an increase of 4.1 percent compared with 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/fishery/static/Yearbook/YB2017_USBcard/booklet/CA5495T_web.pdf|title=Fishery and Aquaculture Statistics 2017|last=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO)|date=2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026013049/http://www.fao.org/fishery/static/Yearbook/YB2017_USBcard/booklet/CA5495T_web.pdf|archive-date=2019-10-26|access-date=}}</ref> There is a growing gap between the supply of fish and demand, due in part to [[world population]] growth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sharkresearch.rsmas.miami.edu/conservation/global-population-growth-wild-fish-stocks-and-the-future-of-aquaculture|title=Global population growth, wild fish stocks, and the future of aquaculture {{!}} Shark Research & Conservation Program (SRC) {{!}} University of Miami|website=sharkresearch.rsmas.miami.edu|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref>\n\nThe journal ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' published a four-year study in November 2006, which predicted that, at prevailing trends, the world would run out of wild-caught [[seafood]] in 2048. The scientists stated that the decline was a result of [[overfishing]], [[pollution]] and other environmental factors that were reducing the population of fisheries at the same time as their ecosystems were being annihilated. Many countries, such as [[Tonga]], the [[United States]], [[Australia]] and [[Bahamas]], and international management bodies have taken steps to appropriately manage marine resources.<ref>{{cite journal\n | author = Worm, Boris\n | date = 2006-11-03\n | title = Impacts of Biodiversity Loss on Ocean Ecosystem Services\n | journal = Science\n | volume = 314\n | issue = 5800\n | pages = 787\u2013790\n | doi = 10.1126/science.1132294\n | pmid = 17082450\n |display-authors=etal| bibcode = 2006Sci...314..787W\n | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1a15e7ee67b3e34fc7277341a0574daaac60af27\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n |author=Juliet Eilperin \n |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/02/AR2006110200913.html\n |title=Seafood Population Depleted by 2048, Study Finds\n |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]]\n |date=2 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nReefs are also being destroyed by [[overfishing]] because of the huge nets that are dragged along the ocean floor while [[trawling]]. Many corals are being destroyed and as a consequence, the [[ecological niche]] of many species is at stake.\n\n{{Bar chart|title=Mean [[greenhouse gas emissions]] for different food types<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Michael Clark|last2=Tilman|first2=David|date=November 2014|title=Global diets link environmental sustainability and human health|journal=Nature|volume=515|issue=7528|pages=518\u2013522|doi=10.1038/nature13959|pmid=25383533|issn=1476-4687|bibcode=2014Natur.515..518T}}</ref>|float=right|label_type=Food Types|data_type=Greenhouse Gas Emissions (g CO<small>2</small>-C<small>eq</small> per g protein)|bar_width=20|width_units=em|data_max=62|label1=[[Ruminant|Ruminant Meat]]|data1=62|label2=[[Recirculating aquaculture system|Recirculating Aquaculture]]|data2=30|label3=[[Trawling|Trawling Fishery]]|data3=26|label4=[[Aquaculture|Non-recirculating Aquaculture]]|data4=12|label5=[[Pork]]|data5=10|label6=[[Poultry]]|data6=10|label7=[[Dairy]]|data7=9.1|label8=[[Fishery|Non-trawling Fishery]]|data8=8.6|label9=[[Egg as food|Eggs]]|data9=6.8|label10=[[List of root vegetables|Starchy Roots]]|data10=1.7|label11=[[Wheat]]|data11=1.2|label12=[[Maize]]|data12=1.2|label13=[[Legumes]]|data13=0.25}}\n\n==Effects on marine habitat==\n{{main|Blast fishing|Cyanide fishing|Bottom trawling|Ghost net}}\n[[File:Turtlekill1.jpg|thumb|A sea turtle killed by a boat propeller]]\nSome fishing techniques cause habitat destruction.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Erdmann, Pet-Soede, Cabanban|date=2000|title=Destructive Fishing Practices|url=https://rmportal.net/nriclib/0100-999/115/Section_6_Trade_&_Management/6-2_Fishing.pdf|journal=9th International Coral Reef Symposium}}</ref> [[Blast fishing]] and [[cyanide fishing]], which are illegal in many places, harm surrounding habitat.<ref name=\":11\" /> Blast fishing refers to the practice of using explosives to capture fish. Cyanide fishing refers to the practice of using cyanide to stun fish for collection. These two practices are commonly used for the aquarium trade and the live fish food trade.<ref name=\":11\" /> These practices are destructive because they impact the habitat that the reef fish live on after the fish have been removed. [[Bottom trawling]], the practice of pulling a [[fishing net]] along the sea bottom behind [[Commercial trawler|trawlers]], removes around 5 to 25% of an area's seabed life on a single run.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.deh.gov.au/soe/2001/coasts/coasts05-6.html#changestobenthic| title=Reports| date=2017-01-29| access-date=2008-02-04| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909080154/http://deh.gov.au/soe/2001/coasts/coasts05-6.html#changestobenthic| archive-date=2006-09-09| url-status=dead}}</ref> Most of the impacts are due to commercial fishing practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://slowfood.com/slowfish/pagine/eng/pagina.lasso?-id_pg=43|title=Destructive Fishing Practices and Bycatch - Ocean Threats {{!}} Slow Fish - Local Sustainable Fish|last=Blulab|website=slowfood.com|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> A 2005 report of the [[UN Millennium Project]], commissioned by UN Secretary-General [[Kofi Annan]], recommended the elimination of bottom trawling on the high seas by 2006 to protect seamounts and other ecologically sensitive habitats. This was not done.\n\nIn mid-October 2006, [[United States]] President [[George W. Bush]] joined other world leaders calling for a moratorium on deep-sea [[trawling]], a practice shown to often have harmful effects on sea habitat and, hence, on fish populations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15117680/ns/world_news-world_environment/t/us-vows-work-against-destructive-fishing/|title=U.S. vows to work against destructive fishing|date=2006-10-03|work=msnbc.com|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> No further action was taken (Divek). the sea animals aquatic ecosystem may also collapse due to the destruction in the food chain.\n\nAdditionally, ghost fishing is a major threat due to capture fisheries.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Jennings|first1=Simon|last2= Kaiser|first2=Michel J.|date=1998|title=The effects of fishing on marine ecosystems|url=https://fish.gov.au/Archived-Reports/2014/Documents/2014_refs/Jennings%20et%20al%201998.pdf|journal=Advances in Marine Biology|volume=34|pages=201\u2013352|doi=10.1016/S0065-2881(08)60212-6|isbn=9780120261345}}</ref> [[Ghost net|Ghost fishing]] occurs when a net, such as a gill net or trawl, is lost or discarded at sea and drifts within the oceans and can still act to capture marine organisms. According to the [[Food and Agriculture Organization|FAO]] Code of Conduct for Responsible Fisheries, States should act to minimize the amount of lost and abandoned gear, and work to minimize ghost fishing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/005/v9878e/v9878e00.htm|title=FAO. Code of Conduct for Responsible Fisheries|website=www.fao.org|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Overfishing==\n{{main|Overfishing}}\n[[Overfishing]] has also been widely reported due to increases in the volume of fishing hauls to feed a quickly growing number of consumers. This has led to the breakdown of some sea ecosystems and several fishing industries whose catch has been greatly diminished.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.seafoodwatch.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/sfw_of.asp |title=Monterey Bay Aquarium: Seafood Watch Program - Issues - Overfishing<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2008-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324213755/http://www.seafoodwatch.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/sfw_of.asp |archive-date=2008-03-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/international/campaigns/save-our-seas-2/don-t-waste-our-oceans Overfishing | Greenpeace International<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The extinction of many species has also been reported.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://seawifs.gsfc.nasa.gov/OCEAN_PLANET/HTML/peril_overfishing.html |title=Ocean Planet:perils-overfishing<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2008-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118161531/http://seawifs.gsfc.nasa.gov/OCEAN_PLANET/HTML/peril_overfishing.html |archive-date=2008-01-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to a [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] estimate, over 70% of the world\u2019s fish species are either fully exploited or depleted.<ref>https://www.un.org/events/tenstories/story.asp?storyID=800</ref> According to the Secretary General of the 2002 World Summit on Sustainable Development, \"Overfishing cannot continue, the depletion of fisheries poses a major threat to the food supply of millions of people.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.johannesburgsummit.org/html/whats_new/otherstories_fishing_2808.htm | title=Johannesburg Summit &#124; Realidad social y desarrollo | access-date=2008-02-04 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528130111/http://www.johannesburgsummit.org/html/whats_new/otherstories_fishing_2808.htm | archive-date=2006-05-28 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe cover story of the May 15, 2003 issue of the science journal [[Nature (journal)|''Nature'']] \u2013 with Dr. [[Ransom A. Myers]], an internationally prominent fisheries biologist (Dalhousie University, Halifax, Canada) as the lead author \u2013 was devoted to a summary of the scientific information. The story asserted that, as compared with 1950 levels, only a remnant (in some instances, as little as 10%) of all large ocean-fish stocks are left in the seas. These large ocean fish are the species at the top of the food chains (e.g., [[tuna]], [[cod]], among others). This article was subsequently criticized as being fundamentally flawed, although much debate still exists (Walters 2003; Hampton et al. 2005; Maunder et al. 2006; Polacheck 2006;Sibert et al. 2006) and the majority of fisheries scientists now consider the results irrelevant with respect to large [[pelagic]]s (the open seas).<ref>[http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/PFRP/large_pelagics/large_pelagic_predators.html ''Changes in the Biomass of Large Pelagic Predators''] \u2013 Pelagic Fisheries Research Program</ref>\n\nThe fishing down the food web is something that occurs when overfishing arises. Once all larger fish are caught, the fisherman will start to fish the smaller individuals, which would lead to more fish needing to be caught to keep up with demand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fisheries.org/2015/07/fishing-down-through-the-food-web/|title=Fishing Down through the Food Web|date=2015-07-18|work=American Fisheries Society|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> This decreases fish populations, as well as genetic diversity of the species, making them more susceptible to disease, and less likely to adapt to their stressors and the environment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sonsthagen|first=Sarah A.|last2=Wilson|first2=Robert E.|last3=Underwood|first3=Jared G.|date=2017-12-01|title=Genetic implications of bottleneck effects of differing severities on genetic diversity in naturally recovering populations: An example from Hawaiian coot and Hawaiian gallinule|journal=Ecology and Evolution|volume=7|issue=23|pages=9925\u20139934|doi=10.1002/ece3.3530|pmid=29238526|pmc=5723630|issn=2045-7758}}</ref> Additionally, catching smaller fish leads to breeding of smaller offspring, which can be problematic for fish. In many species, the smaller the female, the less fecund it is, impacting the fish population.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beldade|first=R.|last2=Holbrook|first2=S. J.|last3=Schmitt|first3=R. J.|last4=Planes|first4=S.|last5=Malone|first5=D.|last6=Bernardi|first6=G.|date=2012-06-07|title=Larger female fish contribute disproportionately more to self-replenishment |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|volume=279|issue=1736|pages=2116\u20132121|doi=10.1098/rspb.2011.2433 |pmc=3321707|pmid=22279163}}</ref>\n\n==Ecological disruption==\nOver-fishing can result in the over-exploitation of marine ecosystem services.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Daskalov|first=Georgi M.|last2=Grishin|first2=Alexander N.|last3=Rodionov|first3=Sergei|last4=Mihneva|first4=Vesselina|date=2007-06-19|title=Trophic cascades triggered by overfishing reveal possible mechanisms of ecosystem regime shifts|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=104|issue=25|pages=10518\u201310523|doi=10.1073/pnas.0701100104|pmid=17548831|pmc=1965545|bibcode=2007PNAS..10410518D}}</ref> Fishing can cause several negative physiological and psychological effects for fish populations including: increased stress levels and bodily injuries resulting from lodged fish hooks.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite journal|last=Cooke|first=Steven J.|last2=Suski|first2=Cory D.|date=2005-05-01|title=Do we need species-specific guidelines for catch-and-release recreational angling to effectively conserve diverse fishery resources?|journal=Biodiversity & Conservation|volume=14|issue=5|pages=1195\u20131209|doi=10.1007/s10531-004-7845-0|issn=0960-3115}}</ref> Often times, when this threshold is crossed, [[hysteresis]] may occur within the environment.<ref name=\":0\" /> More specifically, some ecological disturbances observed within the [[Black Sea]] marine ecosystem resulted from a combination of over-fishing and various other related human activities which adversely affected the marine environment and ecosystem.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Daskalov|first=Georgi M.|date=2002|title=Overfishing drives a trophic cascade in the Black Sea|journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series|volume=225|pages=53\u201363|doi=10.3354/meps225053|issn=0171-8630|bibcode=2002MEPS..225...53D|doi-access=free}}</ref> Ecological disruption can also occur due to the over-fishing of critical fish species such as the tilefish and grouper fish who can be referred to as [[Ecosystem engineer|ecosystem-engineers]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Coleman|first=Felicia C.|last2=Williams|first2=Susan L.|authorlink2=Susan L. Williams|title=Overexploiting marine ecosystem engineers: potential consequences for biodiversity|journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution|volume=17|issue=1|pages=40\u201344|doi=10.1016/s0169-5347(01)02330-8|year=2002}}</ref>\n\nFishing may disrupt [[food web]]s by targeting specific, in-demand species. There might be too much fishing of prey species such as [[sardine]]s and [[anchovies]], thus reducing the food supply for the predators. Disrupting these types of wasp-waist species may have effects throughout the ecosystem.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cury, Bakun, Crawford, Jarre, Quinones, Shannon, Verheye|date=2000|title=Small pelagics in upwelling systems: patterns of interaction and structural changes in ''wasp-waist'' ecosystems.|journal=ICES Journal of Marine Science|volume=57|issue=3|pages=603\u2013618|doi=10.1006/jmsc.2000.0712|doi-access=free}}</ref> It may also cause the increase of prey species when the target fishes are predator species, such as [[salmon]] and [[tuna]].\n\nOverfishing and pollution of the oceans also affect their carbon storage ability and thus contribute to the climate crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/04/tackling-ocean|title=Tackling degraded oceans could mitigate climate crisis - report|last=Harvey|first=Fiona|date=2019-12-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Bycatch==\n{{main|Bycatch}}\n[[Bycatch]] is the portion of the catch that is not the target species. These are either kept to be sold or discarded. In some instances the discarded portion is known as [[discards]]. Even sports fisherman discard a lot of non-target and target fish on the bank while fishing. For every 1 pound of the target species caught, up to 5 pounds of unintended marine species are caught and discarded as bycatch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/3/W6602E/w6602E09.htm|title=Discards and bycatch in Shrimp trawl fisheries.|website=www.fao.org|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref> As many as 40% (63 billion pounds) of fish caught globally every year are discarded, and as many as 650,000 whales, dolphins and seals were killed every year by fishing vessels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oceana.org/sites/default/files/reports/Bycatch_Report_FINAL.pdf|title=WASTED CATCH: UNSOLVED PROBLEMS IN U.S. FISHERIES|last=Keledjian|first=Amanda}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/20/americas-nine-most-wasteful-fisheries-named|title=America's nine most wasteful fisheries named|last=Goldenberg|first=Suzanne|date=2014-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-30|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Shark finning and culling==\n===Shark finning===\n{{main|Shark finning}}\n[[Shark finning]] is the act of removing fins from sharks and discarding the rest of the shark. The sharks are often still alive when discarded, but without their fins.<ref>Schindler, D.E., Essington, T.E., Kitchell, J.F., Boggs, C. and Hilborn, R. (2002) http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/wol1/doi/10.1890/1051-0761(2002)012%5B0735:SATFIO%5D2.0.CO;2/abstract \"Sharks and tunas: fisheries impacts on predators with contrasting life histories\". Ecological Applications, 12 (3): 735\u2013748. doi:10.1890/1051-0761(2002)012[0735:SATFIO]2.0.CO;2</ref><ref>Spiegel, J. (2000) http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/bcic24&div=22&id=&page= \"Even Jaws deserves to keep his fins: outlawing shark finning throughout global waters\". Boston College International and Comparative Law Review, 24 (2): 409\u2013438.</ref> Unable to swim effectively, they sink to the bottom of the ocean and die of suffocation or are eaten by other predators. Though studies suggest that 73 million sharks are finned each year,<ref name=\"sharkfinning\">https://www.livescience.com/1027-shark-slaughter-73-million-killed-year.html ''Shark Slaughter: 73 Million Killed Each Year.'' Ker Than. September 26, 2006. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> scientists have noted that the numbers may actually be higher, with roughly 100 million sharks being killed by finning each year.<ref>https://ocean.si.edu/ocean-life/sharks-rays/shark-finning-sharks-turned-prey Ocean.si.edu. ''Shark finning: Sharks turned prey\". Caty Fairclough. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> The deaths of millions of sharks has caused catastrophic damage to the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref name=\"sharkfinning\"/>\n\n===Shark culling===\n{{main|Shark culling}}\n[[Shark culling]] is the killing of sharks in government-run \"shark control\" programs.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/can-governments-protect-people-from-killer-sharks/5158880 \"Can governments protect people from killer sharks?\". ABC News. 2013-12-22. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> These programs exist to reduce the risk of [[shark attack]]s \u2014 however, environmentalists say that they do not reduce the risk of shark attacks; they also say that shark culling harms the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref>http://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/sharks-how-a-cull-could-ruin-an-ecosystem Schetzer, Alana. \"Sharks: How a cull could ruin an ecosystem\". puruit.unimelb.edu.au. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"sharkculling\">https://web.archive.org/web/20181002102324/https://www.marineconservation.org.au/pages/shark-culling.html \"Shark Culling\". marineconservation.org.au. Archived from the original on 2018-10-02. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> Shark culling currently occurs in [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]], [[KwaZulu-Natal]] and [[R\u00e9union]].<ref name=\"sharkculling\"/><ref name=\"sharkangels\">http://www.sharkangels.org/index.php/media/news/157-shark-nets \"Shark Nets\". sharkangels.org. Archived from the original on 2018-09-19. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref><ref>https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=11847758 \"Man Who Devoted Life To Sharks, Killed Off The Coast Of Reunion\". nzherald.co.nz. April 30, 2017. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> Queensland's \"shark control\" program killed roughly 50,000 sharks between 1962 and 2018 \u2014 Queensland's program uses lethal devices such as [[shark nets]] and [[drum line (shark control)|drum lines]].<ref>https://www.news.com.au/technology/science/animals/aussie-shark-population-is-staggering-decline/news-story/49e910c828b6e2b735d1c68e6b2c956e Aussie shark population in staggering decline. Rhian Deutrom. December 14, 2018. Retrieved January 1, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"sharkculling\"/> Thousands of other animals, such as [[turtle]]s and [[dolphin]]s, have been killed in Queensland as [[bycatch]].<ref>http://www.afd.org.au/news-articles/queenslands-shark-control-program-has-snagged-84000-animals Action for Dolphins. Queensland\u2019s Shark Control Program Has Snagged 84,000 Animals. Thom Mitchell. November 20, 2015. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> Queensland's shark culling program has been called \"outdated, cruel and ineffective\".<ref>https://www.ntd.tv/2018/09/04/video-endangered-hammerhead-sharks-dead-on-drum-line-in-great-barrier-reef/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919094449/https://www.ntd.tv/2018/09/04/video-endangered-hammerhead-sharks-dead-on-drum-line-in-great-barrier-reef/ |date=2018-09-19 }} Phillips, Jack (September 4, 2018). \"Video: Endangered Hammerhead Sharks Dead on Drum Line in Great Barrier Reef\". ntd.tv.  Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> The shark culling program in New South Wales (which uses nets) has killed thousands of sharks, turtles, dolphins, and [[whales]].<ref name=\"sharkculling\"/> KwaZulu-Natal's shark culling program killed more than 33,000 sharks in a 30-year period.<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/>\n\n==Marine debris==\n{{main|Marine debris}}\nRecent research has shown that, by mass, fishing debris, such as buoys, lines, and nets, accounts for more than two-thirds of large plastic debris found in the oceans;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eriksen|first=Marcus|last2=Lebreton|first2=Laurent C. M.|last3=Carson|first3=Henry S.|last4=Thiel|first4=Martin|last5=Moore|first5=Charles J.|last6=Borerro|first6=Jose C.|last7=Galgani|first7=Francois|last8=Ryan|first8=Peter G.|last9=Reisser|first9=Julia|date=2014-12-10|title=Plastic Pollution in the World's Oceans: More than 5 Trillion Plastic Pieces Weighing over 250,000 Tons Afloat at Sea|journal=[[PLOS ONE]]|volume=9|issue=12|pages=e111913|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0111913|pmc=4262196|pmid=25494041|bibcode=2014PLoSO...9k1913E}}</ref> in the [[Great Pacific Garbage Patch]], fishing nets alone comprise at least 46% of the debris.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lebreton|first=L.|last2=Slat|first2=B.|last3=Ferrari|first3=F.|last4=Sainte-Rose|first4=B.|last5=Aitken|first5=J.|last6=Marthouse|first6=R.|last7=Hajbane|first7=S.|last8=Cunsolo|first8=S.|last9=Schwarz|first9=A.|displayauthors=4|date=2018-03-22|title=Evidence that the Great Pacific Garbage Patch is rapidly accumulating plastic|journal=[[Scientific Reports]]|volume=8|issue=1|pages=4666|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-22939-w|pmid=29568057|pmc=5864935|first10=A.|first11=K.|first12=P.|first13=H.|last10=Levivier|last11=Noble|last12=Debeljak|last13=Maral|first14=R.|first15=R.|first16=J.|last14=Schoeneich-Argent|last15=Brambini|last16=Reisser|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.4666L}}</ref> Similarly, fishing debris has been shown to be a major source of plastic debris found on the shores of Korea.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jang|first=Yong Chang|last2=Lee|first2=Jongmyoung|last3=Hong|first3=Sunwook|last4=Lee|first4=Jong Su|last5=Shim|first5=Won Joon|last6=Song|first6=Young Kyoung|date=2014-07-06|title=Sources of plastic marine debris on beaches of Korea: More from the ocean than the land|url=|journal=Ocean Science Journal|volume=49|issue=2|pages=151\u2013162|bibcode=2014OSJ....49..151J|doi=10.1007/s12601-014-0015-8|issn=1738-5261}}</ref> [[Marine life]] interacts with debris in two ways: either through [[Plastic pollution#Entanglement|entanglement]] (where debris entangles or entraps animals), or ingestion of the debris (either intentionally or accidentally). Both are harmful to the animal.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Marine Debris|last=Laist|first=David W.|date=1997|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781461384885|editor-last=Coe|editor-first=James M.|series=Springer Series on Environmental Management|location=New York, NY|pages=99\u2013139|chapter=Impacts of Marine Debris: Entanglement of Marine Life in Marine Debris Including a Comprehensive List of Species with Entanglement and Ingestion Records|doi=10.1007/978-1-4613-8486-1_10|editor-last2=Rogers|editor-first2=Donald}}</ref> Marine debris consisting of old fishing nets or trawls can often be linked to phenomena such as ghost fishing, wherein the netting debris, referred to as [[ghost net]]s, continues to entangle and capture fish.<ref name=\":4\" /> A study performed in southern Japan on [[octopus]]es noted that there was an estimated mortality rate of 212,000\u2013505,000 octopuses per year within the area's fishing grounds, due in large part to ghost fishing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matsuoka|first=Tatsuro|last2=Nakashima|first2=Toshiko|last3=Nagasawa|first3=Naoki|date=2005-07-01|title=A review of ghost fishing: scientific approaches to evaluation and solutions|url=https://www.wpcouncil.org/documents/APECSeminar/Panel%201-%20Science%20and%20Policy/Presentation%20by%20Dr.%20Tatsuro%20Matsuoka.pdf|journal=Fisheries Science|volume=71|issue=4|pages=691|doi=10.1111/j.1444-2906.2005.01019.x|issn=0919-9268}}</ref> Tracking garbage and monitoring the logistics of human waste disposal, especially waste materials primarily associated with fishing, is one method to reduce marine debris.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Sigler|first=Michelle|date=2014-11-01|title=The Effects of Plastic Pollution on Aquatic Wildlife: Current Situations and Future Solutions|url=https://www.earthexpeditions.org/system/files/Sigler_Michelle_Water%20Air%20Soil%20Pollut_2014.pdf|journal=Water, Air, & Soil Pollution|volume=225|issue=11|pages=2184|doi=10.1007/s11270-014-2184-6|issn=0049-6979|bibcode=2014WASP..225.2184S}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Gregory|first=Murray R.|date=2009-07-27|title=Environmental implications of plastic debris in marine settings\u2014entanglement, ingestion, smothering, hangers-on, hitch-hiking and alien invasions|journal=[[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences]]|volume=364|issue=1526|pages=2013\u20132025|doi=10.1098/rstb.2008.0265|issn=0962-8436|pmc=2873013|pmid=19528053}}</ref> Using technological or mechanical innovations such as marine debris-clearing drones can further serve to reduce the amount of debris within oceans.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Importance of Recreational Fishing Impacts ==\n{{main|Recreational fishing}}\n\nRecreational fishing is fishing done for sport or competition, whereas commercial fishing is catching seafood, often in mass quantities, for profit. Both can have different environmental impacts when it comes to fishing.\n\nThough many assume recreational fishing does not have a large impact on fish, it actually accounts for almost a quarter of the fish caught in the United States, many of those being commercially valuable fish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2004/08/040827094111.htm|title=Study In Science Reveals Recreational Fishing Takes Big Bite Of Ocean Catch|work=ScienceDaily|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> Since recreational fishing is not nearly as regulated or monitored as commercial fishing, this is large section of environmental impact that needs to be taken into account.\n\nRecreational fishing has its biggest impact on marine debris, overfishing, and fish mortality. Release mortality in recreational fisheries is the same as the impacts of bycatch in commercial fisheries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=J.|first=Cooke, Steven|last2=G.|first2=Cowx, Ian|date=2004-09-01|title=The Role of Recreational Fishing in Global Fish Crises|journal=BioScience|volume=54|issue=9|pages=857|doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2004)054[0857:TRORFI]2.0.CO;2|issn=0006-3568|doi-access=free}}</ref> Studies have suggested that improving recreational fisheries management on a global scale could generate substantial social benefits of the same scale as reforming commercial fisheries.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Joshua K. Abbott |first1=Patrick Lloyd-Smith, Daniel Willard, and Wiktor Adamowicz |title=Status-quo management of marine recreational fisheries undermines angler welfare |journal=PNAS |volume=115 |date=September 4, 2018 |issue=36 |pages=8948\u20138953 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1809549115 |pmid=30127021 |pmc=6130401 }}</ref>\n\n==Countermeasures==\n\n=== Fisheries management and fish farming ===\n{{main|Fisheries management|Fish farming}}\nOne method to increase fish population numbers and reduce the severity of adverse environmental impacts and ecological disturbances is the utilization of traditional [[fisheries management]] systems within fisheries.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Hilborn|first=Ray|last2=Ovando|first2=Daniel|date=2014-08-01|title=Reflections on the success of traditional fisheries management|journal=ICES Journal of Marine Science|volume=71|issue=5|pages=1040\u20131046|doi=10.1093/icesjms/fsu034|issn=1054-3139|doi-access=free}}</ref> Essentially, traditional fisheries management incorporates the aspects of fisheries management; however, the conservation efforts take into account concepts that place restrictions on the type of gear used and the allotment of permitted angling.<ref name=\":6\" /> Traditional fisheries management also incorporates communities within its conservation efforts which often result in management scenarios where there is co-management conservation efforts led by communities.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n[[Ecosystem-based management]] of fisheries is another method used for fish conservation and impact remediation.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Pikitch|first=Ellen K.|date=2012-10-26|title=The Risks of Overfishing|journal=Science|volume=338|issue=6106|pages=474\u2013475|doi=10.1126/science.1229965|issn=0036-8075|pmid=23112316|bibcode=2012Sci...338..474P}}</ref> Instead of solely focusing conservation efforts on a single species of marine life, ecosystem-based management is used across various species of fish within an environment.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> To improve the adoption of these types of fisheries management, it is important to reduce barriers to entry for management scenarios in order to make these methods more accessible to fisheries globally.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nMany governments and intergovernmental bodies have implemented [[fisheries management]] policies designed to curb the environmental impact of fishing. Fishing conservation aims to control the human activities that may completely decrease a fish stock or washout an entire aquatic environment. These laws include the quotas on the total catch of particular species in a fishery, effort quotas (e.g., number of days at sea), the limits on the number of vessels allowed in specific areas, and the imposition of seasonal restrictions on fishing.\n\nIn 2008 a large scale study of fisheries that used [[individual transferable quota]]s and ones that didn't provided strong evidence that individual transferable quotas can help to prevent collapses and restore fisheries that appear to be in decline.<ref>Costello, Christopher; Gaines, Steven D and Lynham, John (2008) [http://fiesta.bren.ucsb.edu/~costello/research/CatchShares/ ''Can Catch Shares Prevent Fisheries Collapse?''] Science Vol 321, No 5896, pp 1678\u20131681.</ref><ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/channel/earth/dn14762-guaranteed-fish-quotas-halt-commercial-freeforall.html  New Scientist: Guaranteed fish quotas halt commercial free-for-all]</ref><ref>[http://www.economist.com/science/displayStory.cfm?source=hptextfeature&story_id=12253181 A Rising Tide: Scientists find proof that privatising fishing stocks can avert a disaster] The Economist, 18th Sept, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2008-09/s-nso091208.php New study offers solution to global fisheries collapse] Eureka alert.</ref>\n\n[[Fish farming]] has been proposed as a more sustainable alternative to traditional capture of [[Wild fisheries|wild fish]]. However, fish farming has been found to have negative impacts on nearby wild fish<ref>[http://biology.plosjournals.org/perlserv/?request=get-document&doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.0060046 PLoS Biology - Can Farmed and Wild Salmon Coexist?<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and farming of predatory fish [[Aquaculture of salmon#Impact on forage fish|like salmon]] can rely on fish feed that is based on [[fish meal]] and [[Fish oil|oil]] from [[Forage fish|wild fish]].<ref name=\"Alliance\">[[Seafood Choices Alliance]] (2005) [http://www.seafoodchoices.com/resources/afishianado_pdfs/Salmon_Spring05.pdf It's all about salmon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924095748/http://www.seafoodchoices.com/resources/afishianado_pdfs/Salmon_Spring05.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref>\n\n=== Marine reserves ===\n[[Marine reserve]]s serve to foster both environmental protection and marine wildlife safety.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Roberts|first=Callum M.|last2=Polunin|first2=Nicholas V. C.|date=1993|title=Marine Reserves: Simple Solutions to Managing Complex Fisheries?|jstor=4314106|journal=Ambio|volume=22|issue=6|pages=363\u2013368}}</ref> The reserves themselves are established via environmental protection plans or policies which designate a specific marine environment as protected.<ref name=\":7\" /> Coral reefs are one of the many examples which involve the application of marine reserves in establishing marine protected areas.<ref name=\":7\" /> There have also been marine reserve initiatives located in the United States, [[Caribbean]], [[Philippines]], and [[Egypt]].<ref name=\":7\" /> To mitigate the negative environmental impacts of fishing within marine environments, marine reserves are intended to create, enhance, and re-introduce biodiversity within the area.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Aburto-Oropeza|first=Octavio|last2=Erisman|first2=Brad|last3=Galland|first3=Grantly R.|last4=Mascare\u00f1as-Osorio|first4=Ismael|last5=Sala|first5=Enric|last6=Ezcurra|first6=Exequiel|date=2011-08-12|title=Large Recovery of Fish Biomass in a No-Take Marine Reserve|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=6|issue=8|pages=e23601|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0023601|pmid=21858183|pmc=3155316|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2011PLoSO...623601A}}</ref> As a result, the primary benefits arising from the implementation of this type of management effort include positive impacts towards habitat protection and species conservation.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Catch-and-release ===\nBased upon [[Catch and release|catch-and-release]] research, this method of mitigation involves several practices to reduce the negative environmental impacts of fishing that include: the duration, timing, and type of hook used during angling.<ref name=\":52\"/> To increase the effectiveness of catch and release fishing and mitigate its negative impacts, species-specific guidelines are required.<ref name=\":52\" /> These guidelines help tailor specific rules and regulations to specific species of fish in relation to their locations and mating and migration cycles.<ref name=\":52\" /> A metastudy in 2005 found that the average catch and release mortality rate was 18%, but varied greatly by species.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bartholomew|first=Aaron|last2=Bohnsack|first2=James A.|date=2005-02-01|title=A Review of Catch-and-Release Angling Mortality with Implications for No-take Reserves|journal=Reviews in Fish Biology and Fisheries|volume=15|issue=1|pages=129\u2013154|doi=10.1007/s11160-005-2175-1|issn=1573-5184}}</ref> While catch-and-release fishing has been wildly used in recreational fishing, it is also beneficial for maintaining fish populations at a stable level for commercial fisheries to receive social and economic benefits.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Donaldson|first=Michael R.|last2=Arlinghaus|first2=Robert|last3=Hanson|first3=Kyle C.|last4=Cooke|first4=Steven J.|date=2008-03-01|title=Enhancing catch-and-release science with biotelemetry|journal=Fish and Fisheries|volume=9|issue=1|pages=79\u2013105|doi=10.1111/j.1467-2979.2007.00265.x|issn=1467-2979|citeseerx=10.1.1.589.1499}}</ref> Combining catch-and-release fishing with [[biotelemetry]] data collection methods allows for researchers to study the biological effects of catch-and-release fishing on fish in order to better suit future conservation efforts and remedies.<ref name=\":10\" /> The environmental impact of recreational fishing may be alleviated to some extent by [[catch and release]] fishing.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Finless Foods]]\n*[[Population dynamics of fisheries]]\n* [[List of harvested aquatic animals by weight]]\n*[[Shark culling]]\n*[[Shark finning]]\n*[[Sustainable seafood]]\n*[[Marine debris]]\n*[[Destructive fishing practices]]\n\n'''Books:'''\n*''[[The End of the Line: How Overfishing Is Changing the World and What We Eat]]'' (book)\n*''[[One Fish, Two Fish, Crawfish, Bluefish]]'' (book)\n\n'''Related:'''\n*[[Environmental effects of meat production]]\n*[[Human impact on the environment]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Castro, P. and M. Huber. (2003). Marine Biology. 4thed. Boston: McGraw Hill.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Hampton | first1 = J. | last2 = Sibert | first2 = J. R. | last3 = Kleiber | first3 = P. | last4 = Maunder | first4 = M. N. | last5 = Harley | first5 = S. J. | year = 2005 | title = Changes in abundance of large pelagic predators in the Pacific Ocean | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 434 | issue = | pages = E2\u2013E3 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Maunder | first1 = M.N. | last2 = Sibert | first2 = J.R. | last3 = Fonteneau | first3 = A. | last4 = Hampton | first4 = J. | last5 = Kleiber | first5 = P. | last6 = Harley | first6 = S. | year = 2006 | title = Interpreting catch-per-unit-of-effort data to assess the status of individual stocks and communities | url = | journal = ICES Journal of Marine Science | volume = 63 | issue = 8| pages = 1373\u20131385 | doi=10.1016/j.icesjms.2006.05.008| doi-access = free }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Myers | first1 = Ransom | last2 = Worm | first2 = Boris | year = 2003 | title = Rapid worldwide depletion of predatory fish communities | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 423 | issue = 6937| pages = 280\u20133 | doi = 10.1038/nature01610 | pmid = 12748640 | bibcode = 2003Natur.423..280M }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Polacheck | first1 = T | year = 2006 | title = Tuna longline catch rates in the Indian Ocean: did industrial fishing result in a 90% rapid decline in the abundance of large predatory species? | url = | journal = Marine Policy | volume = 30 | issue = 5| pages = 470\u2013482 | doi=10.1016/j.marpol.2005.06.016}}\n*FAO Fisheries Department. (2002). The State of World Fisheries and Aquaculture. Rome: Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Sibert | display-authors = etal  | year = 2006 | title = Biomass, Size, and Trophic Status of Top Predators in the Pacific Ocean | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0a7dc0f67d244832137549192eedada7188e6563| journal = Science | volume = 314 | issue = 5806| pages =  1773\u20131776| doi=10.1126/science.1135347 | pmid=17170304| bibcode = 2006Sci...314.1773S }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Walters | first1 = C. J. | year = 2003 | title = Folly and fantasy in the analysis of spatial catch rate data | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b4a200754478530eadfee40d8f79a271f64ef3a3| journal = Canadian Journal of Fisheries and Aquatic Sciences | volume = 60 | issue = 12| pages = 1433\u20131436 | doi=10.1139/f03-152}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/PFRP/ Pelagic Fisheries Research Program]\n*[http://www.icsf.net International Collective in Support of Fishworkers website]\n*[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/N03201755.htm United Nations conference in criticism of deep-sea trawling]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080329072043/http://www.savethehighseas.org/display.cfm?ID=139 Bush backs international deep-sea trawling moratorium]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928074029/http://www.uwtv.org/programs/displayevent.aspx?rID=2515&fID=456 Re-interpreting the Fisheries Crisis seminar by Prof. Ray Hilborn]\n*[http://www.fishonline.org/ UK Database of commercially sold fish with stock status]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080515202354/http://seafoodwatch.org/cr/seafoodwatch.asp Database on stock status of US seafood]\n* [http://www.conservationinstitute.org/ Conservation Science Institute]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110714235353/http://www.olrac.com/knowledge-base The facts about the Commercial Fishing Environment]\n\n{{human impact on the environment|state=expanded}}\n{{fishery science topics|expanded=none}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Effects Of Fishing}}\n[[Category:Environmental impact of fishing| ]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Fishing down the food web.jpg|thumb|350px|{{center|[[Fishing down the foodweb]]}}]]\n\nThe '''environmental impact of fishing''' includes issues such as the availability of [[fish]], [[overfishing]], [[fisheries]], and [[fisheries management]]; as well as the impact of [[industrial fishing]] on other elements of the environment, such as [[by-catch]]. These issues are part of [[marine conservation]], and are addressed in [[fisheries science]] programs. According to a 2019 [[FAO]] report, global production of fish, crustaceans, molluscs and other aquatic animals has continued to grow and reached 172.6 million tonnes in 2017, with an increase of 4.1 percent compared with 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/fishery/static/Yearbook/YB2017_USBcard/booklet/CA5495T_web.pdf|title=Fishery and Aquaculture Statistics 2017|last=Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO)|date=2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026013049/http://www.fao.org/fishery/static/Yearbook/YB2017_USBcard/booklet/CA5495T_web.pdf|archive-date=2019-10-26|access-date=}}</ref> There is a growing gap between the supply of fish and demand, due in part to [[world population]] growth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sharkresearch.rsmas.miami.edu/conservation/global-population-growth-wild-fish-stocks-and-the-future-of-aquaculture|title=Global population growth, wild fish stocks, and the future of aquaculture {{!}} Shark Research & Conservation Program (SRC) {{!}} University of Miami|website=sharkresearch.rsmas.miami.edu|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref>\n\nThe journal ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'' published a four-year study in November 2006, which predicted that, at prevailing trends, the world would run out of wild-caught [[seafood]] in 2048. The scientists stated that the decline was a result of [[overfishing]], [[pollution]] and other environmental factors that were reducing the population of fisheries at the same time as their ecosystems were being annihilated. Many countries, such as [[Tonga]], the [[United States]], [[Australia]] and [[Bahamas]], and international management bodies have taken steps to appropriately manage marine resources.<ref>{{cite journal\n | author = Worm, Boris\n | date = 2006-11-03\n | title = Impacts of Biodiversity Loss on Ocean Ecosystem Services\n | journal = Science\n | volume = 314\n | issue = 5800\n | pages = 787\u2013790\n | doi = 10.1126/science.1132294\n | pmid = 17082450\n |display-authors=etal| bibcode = 2006Sci...314..787W\n | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1a15e7ee67b3e34fc7277341a0574daaac60af27\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news \n |author=Juliet Eilperin \n |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/02/AR2006110200913.html\n |title=Seafood Population Depleted by 2048, Study Finds\n |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]]\n |date=2 November 2006}}</ref>\n\nReefs are also being destroyed by [[overfishing]] because of the huge nets that are dragged along the ocean floor while [[trawling]]. Many corals are being destroyed and as a consequence, the [[ecological niche]] of many species is at stake.\n\n{{Bar chart|title=Mean [[greenhouse gas emissions]] for different food types<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Michael Clark|last2=Tilman|first2=David|date=November 2014|title=Global diets link environmental sustainability and human health|journal=Nature|volume=515|issue=7528|pages=518\u2013522|doi=10.1038/nature13959|pmid=25383533|issn=1476-4687|bibcode=2014Natur.515..518T}}</ref>|float=right|label_type=Food Types|data_type=Greenhouse Gas Emissions (g CO<small>2</small>-C<small>eq</small> per g protein)|bar_width=20|width_units=em|data_max=62|label1=[[Ruminant|Ruminant Meat]]|data1=62|label2=[[Recirculating aquaculture system|Recirculating Aquaculture]]|data2=30|label3=[[Trawling|Trawling Fishery]]|data3=26|label4=[[Aquaculture|Non-recirculating Aquaculture]]|data4=12|label5=[[Pork]]|data5=10|label6=[[Poultry]]|data6=10|label7=[[Dairy]]|data7=9.1|label8=[[Fishery|Non-trawling Fishery]]|data8=8.6|label9=[[Egg as food|Eggs]]|data9=6.8|label10=[[List of root vegetables|Starchy Roots]]|data10=1.7|label11=[[Wheat]]|data11=1.2|label12=[[Maize]]|data12=1.2|label13=[[Legumes]]|data13=0.25}}\n\n==Effects on Marine habitat==\n{{main|Blast fishing|Cyanide fishing|Bottom trawling|Ghost net}}\n[[File:Turtlekill1.jpg|thumb|A sea turtle killed by a boat propeller]]\nSome fishing techniques cause habitat destruction.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Erdmann, Pet-Soede, Cabanban|date=2000|title=Destructive Fishing Practices|url=https://rmportal.net/nriclib/0100-999/115/Section_6_Trade_&_Management/6-2_Fishing.pdf|journal=9th International Coral Reef Symposium}}</ref> [[Blast fishing]] and [[cyanide fishing]], which are illegal in many places, harm surrounding habitat.<ref name=\":11\" /> Blast fishing refers to the practice of using explosives to capture fish. Cyanide fishing refers to the practice of using cyanide to stun fish for collection. These two practices are commonly used for the aquarium trade and the live fish food trade.<ref name=\":11\" /> These practices are destructive because they impact the habitat that the reef fish live on after the fish have been removed. [[Bottom trawling]], the practice of pulling a [[fishing net]] along the sea bottom behind [[Commercial trawler|trawlers]], removes around 5 to 25% of an area's seabed life on a single run.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.deh.gov.au/soe/2001/coasts/coasts05-6.html#changestobenthic| title=Reports| date=2017-01-29| access-date=2008-02-04| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909080154/http://deh.gov.au/soe/2001/coasts/coasts05-6.html#changestobenthic| archive-date=2006-09-09| url-status=dead}}</ref> Most of the impacts are due to commercial fishing practices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://slowfood.com/slowfish/pagine/eng/pagina.lasso?-id_pg=43|title=Destructive Fishing Practices and Bycatch - Ocean Threats {{!}} Slow Fish - Local Sustainable Fish|last=Blulab|website=slowfood.com|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> A 2005 report of the [[UN Millennium Project]], commissioned by UN Secretary-General [[Kofi Annan]], recommended the elimination of bottom trawling on the high seas by 2006 to protect seamounts and other ecologically sensitive habitats. This was not done.\n\nIn mid-October 2006, [[United States]] President [[George W. Bush]] joined other world leaders calling for a moratorium on deep-sea [[trawling]], a practice shown to often have harmful effects on sea habitat and, hence, on fish populations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15117680/ns/world_news-world_environment/t/us-vows-work-against-destructive-fishing/|title=U.S. vows to work against destructive fishing|date=2006-10-03|work=msnbc.com|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> No further action was taken (Divek). the sea animals aquatic ecosystem may also collapse due to the destruction in the food chain.\n\nAdditionally, ghost fishing is a major threat due to capture fisheries.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Jennings|first1=Simon|last2= Kaiser|first2=Michel J.|date=1998|title=The effects of fishing on marine ecosystems|url=https://fish.gov.au/Archived-Reports/2014/Documents/2014_refs/Jennings%20et%20al%201998.pdf|journal=Advances in Marine Biology|volume=34|pages=201\u2013352|doi=10.1016/S0065-2881(08)60212-6|isbn=9780120261345}}</ref> [[Ghost net|Ghost fishing]] occurs when a net, such as a gill net or trawl, is lost or discarded at sea and drifts within the oceans and can still act to capture marine organisms. According to the [[Food and Agriculture Organization|FAO]] Code of Conduct for Responsible Fisheries, States should act to minimize the amount of lost and abandoned gear, and work to minimize ghost fishing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/005/v9878e/v9878e00.htm|title=FAO. Code of Conduct for Responsible Fisheries|website=www.fao.org|access-date=2018-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==Overfishing==\n{{main|Overfishing}}\n[[Overfishing]] has also been widely reported due to increases in the volume of fishing hauls to feed a quickly growing number of consumers. This has led to the breakdown of some sea ecosystems and several fishing industries whose catch has been greatly diminished.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.seafoodwatch.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/sfw_of.asp |title=Monterey Bay Aquarium: Seafood Watch Program - Issues - Overfishing<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2008-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324213755/http://www.seafoodwatch.org/cr/cr_seafoodwatch/sfw_of.asp |archive-date=2008-03-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.greenpeace.org/international/campaigns/save-our-seas-2/don-t-waste-our-oceans Overfishing | Greenpeace International<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The extinction of many species has also been reported.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://seawifs.gsfc.nasa.gov/OCEAN_PLANET/HTML/peril_overfishing.html |title=Ocean Planet:perils-overfishing<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2008-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080118161531/http://seawifs.gsfc.nasa.gov/OCEAN_PLANET/HTML/peril_overfishing.html |archive-date=2008-01-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> According to a [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] estimate, over 70% of the world\u2019s fish species are either fully exploited or depleted.<ref>https://www.un.org/events/tenstories/story.asp?storyID=800</ref> According to the Secretary General of the 2002 World Summit on Sustainable Development, \"Overfishing cannot continue, the depletion of fisheries poses a major threat to the food supply of millions of people.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.johannesburgsummit.org/html/whats_new/otherstories_fishing_2808.htm | title=Johannesburg Summit &#124; Realidad social y desarrollo | access-date=2008-02-04 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528130111/http://www.johannesburgsummit.org/html/whats_new/otherstories_fishing_2808.htm | archive-date=2006-05-28 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe cover story of the May 15, 2003 issue of the science journal [[Nature (journal)|''Nature'']] \u2013 with Dr. [[Ransom A. Myers]], an internationally prominent fisheries biologist (Dalhousie University, Halifax, Canada) as the lead author \u2013 was devoted to a summary of the scientific information. The story asserted that, as compared with 1950 levels, only a remnant (in some instances, as little as 10%) of all large ocean-fish stocks are left in the seas. These large ocean fish are the species at the top of the food chains (e.g., [[tuna]], [[cod]], among others). This article was subsequently criticized as being fundamentally flawed, although much debate still exists (Walters 2003; Hampton et al. 2005; Maunder et al. 2006; Polacheck 2006;Sibert et al. 2006) and the majority of fisheries scientists now consider the results irrelevant with respect to large [[pelagic]]s (the open seas).<ref>[http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/PFRP/large_pelagics/large_pelagic_predators.html ''Changes in the Biomass of Large Pelagic Predators''] \u2013 Pelagic Fisheries Research Program</ref>\n\nThe fishing down the food web is something that occurs when overfishing arises. Once all larger fish are caught, the fisherman will start to fish the smaller individuals, which would lead to more fish needing to be caught to keep up with demand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://fisheries.org/2015/07/fishing-down-through-the-food-web/|title=Fishing Down through the Food Web|date=2015-07-18|work=American Fisheries Society|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> This decreases fish populations, as well as genetic diversity of the species, making them more susceptible to disease, and less likely to adapt to their stressors and the environment.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sonsthagen|first=Sarah A.|last2=Wilson|first2=Robert E.|last3=Underwood|first3=Jared G.|date=2017-12-01|title=Genetic implications of bottleneck effects of differing severities on genetic diversity in naturally recovering populations: An example from Hawaiian coot and Hawaiian gallinule|journal=Ecology and Evolution|volume=7|issue=23|pages=9925\u20139934|doi=10.1002/ece3.3530|pmid=29238526|pmc=5723630|issn=2045-7758}}</ref> Additionally, catching smaller fish leads to breeding of smaller offspring, which can be problematic for fish. In many species, the smaller the female, the less fecund it is, impacting the fish population.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Beldade|first=R.|last2=Holbrook|first2=S. J.|last3=Schmitt|first3=R. J.|last4=Planes|first4=S.|last5=Malone|first5=D.|last6=Bernardi|first6=G.|date=2012-06-07|title=Larger female fish contribute disproportionately more to self-replenishment |journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|volume=279|issue=1736|pages=2116\u20132121|doi=10.1098/rspb.2011.2433 |pmc=3321707|pmid=22279163}}</ref>\n\n==Ecological disruption==\nOver-fishing can result in the over-exploitation of marine ecosystem services.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Daskalov|first=Georgi M.|last2=Grishin|first2=Alexander N.|last3=Rodionov|first3=Sergei|last4=Mihneva|first4=Vesselina|date=2007-06-19|title=Trophic cascades triggered by overfishing reveal possible mechanisms of ecosystem regime shifts|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|volume=104|issue=25|pages=10518\u201310523|doi=10.1073/pnas.0701100104|pmid=17548831|pmc=1965545|bibcode=2007PNAS..10410518D}}</ref> Fishing can cause several negative physiological and psychological effects for fish populations including: increased stress levels and bodily injuries resulting from lodged fish hooks.<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite journal|last=Cooke|first=Steven J.|last2=Suski|first2=Cory D.|date=2005-05-01|title=Do we need species-specific guidelines for catch-and-release recreational angling to effectively conserve diverse fishery resources?|journal=Biodiversity & Conservation|volume=14|issue=5|pages=1195\u20131209|doi=10.1007/s10531-004-7845-0|issn=0960-3115}}</ref> Often times, when this threshold is crossed, [[hysteresis]] may occur within the environment.<ref name=\":0\" /> More specifically, some ecological disturbances observed within the [[Black Sea]] marine ecosystem resulted from a combination of over-fishing and various other related human activities which adversely affected the marine environment and ecosystem.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Daskalov|first=Georgi M.|date=2002|title=Overfishing drives a trophic cascade in the Black Sea|journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series|volume=225|pages=53\u201363|doi=10.3354/meps225053|issn=0171-8630|bibcode=2002MEPS..225...53D|doi-access=free}}</ref> Ecological disruption can also occur due to the over-fishing of critical fish species such as the tilefish and grouper fish who can be referred to as [[Ecosystem engineer|ecosystem-engineers]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Coleman|first=Felicia C.|last2=Williams|first2=Susan L.|authorlink2=Susan L. Williams|title=Overexploiting marine ecosystem engineers: potential consequences for biodiversity|journal=Trends in Ecology & Evolution|volume=17|issue=1|pages=40\u201344|doi=10.1016/s0169-5347(01)02330-8|year=2002}}</ref>\n\nFishing may disrupt [[food web]]s by targeting specific, in-demand species. There might be too much fishing of prey species such as [[sardine]]s and [[anchovies]], thus reducing the food supply for the predators. Disrupting these types of wasp-waist species may have effects throughout the ecosystem.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cury, Bakun, Crawford, Jarre, Quinones, Shannon, Verheye|date=2000|title=Small pelagics in upwelling systems: patterns of interaction and structural changes in ''wasp-waist'' ecosystems.|journal=ICES Journal of Marine Science|volume=57|issue=3|pages=603\u2013618|doi=10.1006/jmsc.2000.0712|doi-access=free}}</ref> It may also cause the increase of prey species when the target fishes are predator species, such as [[salmon]] and [[tuna]].\n\nOverfishing and pollution of the oceans also affect their carbon storage ability and thus contribute to the climate crisis.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/04/tackling-ocean|title=Tackling degraded oceans could mitigate climate crisis - report|last=Harvey|first=Fiona|date=2019-12-04|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Bycatch==\n{{main|Bycatch}}\n[[Bycatch]] is the portion of the catch that is not the target species. These are either kept to be sold or discarded. In some instances the discarded portion is known as [[discards]]. Even sports fisherman discard a lot of non-target and target fish on the bank while fishing. For every 1 pound of the target species caught, up to 5 pounds of unintended marine species are caught and discarded as bycatch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fao.org/3/W6602E/w6602E09.htm|title=Discards and bycatch in Shrimp trawl fisheries.|website=www.fao.org|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref> As many as 40% (63 billion pounds) of fish caught globally every year are discarded, and as many as 650,000 whales, dolphins and seals were killed every year by fishing vessels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oceana.org/sites/default/files/reports/Bycatch_Report_FINAL.pdf|title=WASTED CATCH: UNSOLVED PROBLEMS IN U.S. FISHERIES|last=Keledjian|first=Amanda}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2014/mar/20/americas-nine-most-wasteful-fisheries-named|title=America's nine most wasteful fisheries named|last=Goldenberg|first=Suzanne|date=2014-03-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-30|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Shark finning and culling==\n===Shark finning===\n{{main|Shark finning}}\n[[Shark finning]] is the act of removing fins from sharks and discarding the rest of the shark. The sharks are often still alive when discarded, but without their fins.<ref>Schindler, D.E., Essington, T.E., Kitchell, J.F., Boggs, C. and Hilborn, R. (2002) http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/wol1/doi/10.1890/1051-0761(2002)012%5B0735:SATFIO%5D2.0.CO;2/abstract \"Sharks and tunas: fisheries impacts on predators with contrasting life histories\". Ecological Applications, 12 (3): 735\u2013748. doi:10.1890/1051-0761(2002)012[0735:SATFIO]2.0.CO;2</ref><ref>Spiegel, J. (2000) http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/bcic24&div=22&id=&page= \"Even Jaws deserves to keep his fins: outlawing shark finning throughout global waters\". Boston College International and Comparative Law Review, 24 (2): 409\u2013438.</ref> Unable to swim effectively, they sink to the bottom of the ocean and die of suffocation or are eaten by other predators. Though studies suggest that 73 million sharks are finned each year,<ref name=\"sharkfinning\">https://www.livescience.com/1027-shark-slaughter-73-million-killed-year.html ''Shark Slaughter: 73 Million Killed Each Year.'' Ker Than. September 26, 2006. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> scientists have noted that the numbers may actually be higher, with roughly 100 million sharks being killed by finning each year.<ref>https://ocean.si.edu/ocean-life/sharks-rays/shark-finning-sharks-turned-prey Ocean.si.edu. ''Shark finning: Sharks turned prey\". Caty Fairclough. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> The deaths of millions of sharks has caused catastrophic damage to the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref name=\"sharkfinning\"/>\n\n===Shark culling===\n{{main|Shark culling}}\n[[Shark culling]] is the killing of sharks in government-run \"shark control\" programs.<ref>http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-22/can-governments-protect-people-from-killer-sharks/5158880 \"Can governments protect people from killer sharks?\". ABC News. 2013-12-22. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> These programs exist to reduce the risk of [[shark attack]]s \u2014 however, environmentalists say that they do not reduce the risk of shark attacks; they also say that shark culling harms the [[marine ecosystem]].<ref>http://pursuit.unimelb.edu.au/articles/sharks-how-a-cull-could-ruin-an-ecosystem Schetzer, Alana. \"Sharks: How a cull could ruin an ecosystem\". puruit.unimelb.edu.au. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"sharkculling\">https://web.archive.org/web/20181002102324/https://www.marineconservation.org.au/pages/shark-culling.html \"Shark Culling\". marineconservation.org.au. Archived from the original on 2018-10-02. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> Shark culling currently occurs in [[New South Wales]], [[Queensland]], [[KwaZulu-Natal]] and [[R\u00e9union]].<ref name=\"sharkculling\"/><ref name=\"sharkangels\">http://www.sharkangels.org/index.php/media/news/157-shark-nets \"Shark Nets\". sharkangels.org. Archived from the original on 2018-09-19. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref><ref>https://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=11847758 \"Man Who Devoted Life To Sharks, Killed Off The Coast Of Reunion\". nzherald.co.nz. April 30, 2017. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> Queensland's \"shark control\" program killed roughly 50,000 sharks between 1962 and 2018 \u2014 Queensland's program uses lethal devices such as [[shark nets]] and [[drum line (shark control)|drum lines]].<ref>https://www.news.com.au/technology/science/animals/aussie-shark-population-is-staggering-decline/news-story/49e910c828b6e2b735d1c68e6b2c956e Aussie shark population in staggering decline. Rhian Deutrom. December 14, 2018. Retrieved January 1, 2018.</ref><ref name=\"sharkculling\"/> Thousands of other animals, such as [[turtle]]s and [[dolphin]]s, have been killed in Queensland as [[bycatch]].<ref>http://www.afd.org.au/news-articles/queenslands-shark-control-program-has-snagged-84000-animals Action for Dolphins. Queensland\u2019s Shark Control Program Has Snagged 84,000 Animals. Thom Mitchell. November 20, 2015. Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> Queensland's shark culling program has been called \"outdated, cruel and ineffective\".<ref>https://www.ntd.tv/2018/09/04/video-endangered-hammerhead-sharks-dead-on-drum-line-in-great-barrier-reef/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919094449/https://www.ntd.tv/2018/09/04/video-endangered-hammerhead-sharks-dead-on-drum-line-in-great-barrier-reef/ |date=2018-09-19 }} Phillips, Jack (September 4, 2018). \"Video: Endangered Hammerhead Sharks Dead on Drum Line in Great Barrier Reef\". ntd.tv.  Retrieved January 1, 2019.</ref> The shark culling program in New South Wales (which uses nets) has killed thousands of sharks, turtles, dolphins, and [[whales]].<ref name=\"sharkculling\"/> KwaZulu-Natal's shark culling program killed more than 33,000 sharks in a 30-year period.<ref name=\"sharkangels\"/>\n\n==Marine debris==\n{{main|Marine debris}}\nRecent research has shown that, by mass, fishing debris, such as buoys, lines, and nets, accounts for more than two-thirds of large plastic debris found in the oceans;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Eriksen|first=Marcus|last2=Lebreton|first2=Laurent C. M.|last3=Carson|first3=Henry S.|last4=Thiel|first4=Martin|last5=Moore|first5=Charles J.|last6=Borerro|first6=Jose C.|last7=Galgani|first7=Francois|last8=Ryan|first8=Peter G.|last9=Reisser|first9=Julia|date=2014-12-10|title=Plastic Pollution in the World's Oceans: More than 5 Trillion Plastic Pieces Weighing over 250,000 Tons Afloat at Sea|journal=[[PLOS ONE]]|volume=9|issue=12|pages=e111913|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0111913|pmc=4262196|pmid=25494041|bibcode=2014PLoSO...9k1913E}}</ref> in the [[Great Pacific Garbage Patch]], fishing nets alone comprise at least 46% of the debris.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lebreton|first=L.|last2=Slat|first2=B.|last3=Ferrari|first3=F.|last4=Sainte-Rose|first4=B.|last5=Aitken|first5=J.|last6=Marthouse|first6=R.|last7=Hajbane|first7=S.|last8=Cunsolo|first8=S.|last9=Schwarz|first9=A.|displayauthors=4|date=2018-03-22|title=Evidence that the Great Pacific Garbage Patch is rapidly accumulating plastic|journal=[[Scientific Reports]]|volume=8|issue=1|pages=4666|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-22939-w|pmid=29568057|pmc=5864935|first10=A.|first11=K.|first12=P.|first13=H.|last10=Levivier|last11=Noble|last12=Debeljak|last13=Maral|first14=R.|first15=R.|first16=J.|last14=Schoeneich-Argent|last15=Brambini|last16=Reisser|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.4666L}}</ref> Similarly, fishing debris has been shown to be a major source of plastic debris found on the shores of Korea.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jang|first=Yong Chang|last2=Lee|first2=Jongmyoung|last3=Hong|first3=Sunwook|last4=Lee|first4=Jong Su|last5=Shim|first5=Won Joon|last6=Song|first6=Young Kyoung|date=2014-07-06|title=Sources of plastic marine debris on beaches of Korea: More from the ocean than the land|url=|journal=Ocean Science Journal|volume=49|issue=2|pages=151\u2013162|bibcode=2014OSJ....49..151J|doi=10.1007/s12601-014-0015-8|issn=1738-5261}}</ref> [[Marine life]] interacts with debris in two ways: either through [[Plastic pollution#Entanglement|entanglement]] (where debris entangles or entraps animals), or ingestion of the debris (either intentionally or accidentally). Both are harmful to the animal.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Marine Debris|last=Laist|first=David W.|date=1997|publisher=Springer|isbn=9781461384885|editor-last=Coe|editor-first=James M.|series=Springer Series on Environmental Management|location=New York, NY|pages=99\u2013139|chapter=Impacts of Marine Debris: Entanglement of Marine Life in Marine Debris Including a Comprehensive List of Species with Entanglement and Ingestion Records|doi=10.1007/978-1-4613-8486-1_10|editor-last2=Rogers|editor-first2=Donald}}</ref> Marine debris consisting of old fishing nets or trawls can often be linked to phenomena such as ghost fishing, wherein the netting debris, referred to as [[ghost net]]s, continues to entangle and capture fish.<ref name=\":4\" /> A study performed in southern Japan on [[octopus]]es noted that there was an estimated mortality rate of 212,000\u2013505,000 octopuses per year within the area's fishing grounds, due in large part to ghost fishing.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matsuoka|first=Tatsuro|last2=Nakashima|first2=Toshiko|last3=Nagasawa|first3=Naoki|date=2005-07-01|title=A review of ghost fishing: scientific approaches to evaluation and solutions|url=https://www.wpcouncil.org/documents/APECSeminar/Panel%201-%20Science%20and%20Policy/Presentation%20by%20Dr.%20Tatsuro%20Matsuoka.pdf|journal=Fisheries Science|volume=71|issue=4|pages=691|doi=10.1111/j.1444-2906.2005.01019.x|issn=0919-9268}}</ref> Tracking garbage and monitoring the logistics of human waste disposal, especially waste materials primarily associated with fishing, is one method to reduce marine debris.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Sigler|first=Michelle|date=2014-11-01|title=The Effects of Plastic Pollution on Aquatic Wildlife: Current Situations and Future Solutions|url=https://www.earthexpeditions.org/system/files/Sigler_Michelle_Water%20Air%20Soil%20Pollut_2014.pdf|journal=Water, Air, & Soil Pollution|volume=225|issue=11|pages=2184|doi=10.1007/s11270-014-2184-6|issn=0049-6979|bibcode=2014WASP..225.2184S}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Gregory|first=Murray R.|date=2009-07-27|title=Environmental implications of plastic debris in marine settings\u2014entanglement, ingestion, smothering, hangers-on, hitch-hiking and alien invasions|journal=[[Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London B: Biological Sciences]]|volume=364|issue=1526|pages=2013\u20132025|doi=10.1098/rstb.2008.0265|issn=0962-8436|pmc=2873013|pmid=19528053}}</ref> Using technological or mechanical innovations such as marine debris-clearing drones can further serve to reduce the amount of debris within oceans.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Importance of Recreational Fishing Impacts ==\n{{main|Recreational fishing}}\n\nRecreational fishing is fishing done for sport or competition, whereas commercial fishing is catching seafood, often in mass quantities, for profit. Both can have different environmental impacts when it comes to fishing.\n\nThough many assume recreational fishing does not have a large impact on fish, it actually accounts for almost a quarter of the fish caught in the United States, many of those being commercially valuable fish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2004/08/040827094111.htm|title=Study In Science Reveals Recreational Fishing Takes Big Bite Of Ocean Catch|work=ScienceDaily|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> Since recreational fishing is not nearly as regulated or monitored as commercial fishing, this is large section of environmental impact that needs to be taken into account.\n\nRecreational fishing has its biggest impact on marine debris, overfishing, and fish mortality. Release mortality in recreational fisheries is the same as the impacts of bycatch in commercial fisheries.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=J.|first=Cooke, Steven|last2=G.|first2=Cowx, Ian|date=2004-09-01|title=The Role of Recreational Fishing in Global Fish Crises|journal=BioScience|volume=54|issue=9|pages=857|doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2004)054[0857:TRORFI]2.0.CO;2|issn=0006-3568|doi-access=free}}</ref> Studies have suggested that improving recreational fisheries management on a global scale could generate substantial social benefits of the same scale as reforming commercial fisheries.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Joshua K. Abbott |first1=Patrick Lloyd-Smith, Daniel Willard, and Wiktor Adamowicz |title=Status-quo management of marine recreational fisheries undermines angler welfare |journal=PNAS |volume=115 |date=September 4, 2018 |issue=36 |pages=8948\u20138953 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1809549115 |pmid=30127021 |pmc=6130401 }}</ref>\n\n==Countermeasures==\n\n=== Fisheries management and fish farming ===\n{{main|Fisheries management|Fish farming}}\nOne method to increase fish population numbers and reduce the severity of adverse environmental impacts and ecological disturbances is the utilization of traditional [[fisheries management]] systems within fisheries.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Hilborn|first=Ray|last2=Ovando|first2=Daniel|date=2014-08-01|title=Reflections on the success of traditional fisheries management|journal=ICES Journal of Marine Science|volume=71|issue=5|pages=1040\u20131046|doi=10.1093/icesjms/fsu034|issn=1054-3139|doi-access=free}}</ref> Essentially, traditional fisheries management incorporates the aspects of fisheries management; however, the conservation efforts take into account concepts that place restrictions on the type of gear used and the allotment of permitted angling.<ref name=\":6\" /> Traditional fisheries management also incorporates communities within its conservation efforts which often result in management scenarios where there is co-management conservation efforts led by communities.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n[[Ecosystem-based management]] of fisheries is another method used for fish conservation and impact remediation.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Pikitch|first=Ellen K.|date=2012-10-26|title=The Risks of Overfishing|journal=Science|volume=338|issue=6106|pages=474\u2013475|doi=10.1126/science.1229965|issn=0036-8075|pmid=23112316|bibcode=2012Sci...338..474P}}</ref> Instead of solely focusing conservation efforts on a single species of marine life, ecosystem-based management is used across various species of fish within an environment.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\" /> To improve the adoption of these types of fisheries management, it is important to reduce barriers to entry for management scenarios in order to make these methods more accessible to fisheries globally.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nMany governments and intergovernmental bodies have implemented [[fisheries management]] policies designed to curb the environmental impact of fishing. Fishing conservation aims to control the human activities that may completely decrease a fish stock or washout an entire aquatic environment. These laws include the quotas on the total catch of particular species in a fishery, effort quotas (e.g., number of days at sea), the limits on the number of vessels allowed in specific areas, and the imposition of seasonal restrictions on fishing.\n\nIn 2008 a large scale study of fisheries that used [[individual transferable quota]]s and ones that didn't provided strong evidence that individual transferable quotas can help to prevent collapses and restore fisheries that appear to be in decline.<ref>Costello, Christopher; Gaines, Steven D and Lynham, John (2008) [http://fiesta.bren.ucsb.edu/~costello/research/CatchShares/ ''Can Catch Shares Prevent Fisheries Collapse?''] Science Vol 321, No 5896, pp 1678\u20131681.</ref><ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/channel/earth/dn14762-guaranteed-fish-quotas-halt-commercial-freeforall.html  New Scientist: Guaranteed fish quotas halt commercial free-for-all]</ref><ref>[http://www.economist.com/science/displayStory.cfm?source=hptextfeature&story_id=12253181 A Rising Tide: Scientists find proof that privatising fishing stocks can avert a disaster] The Economist, 18th Sept, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2008-09/s-nso091208.php New study offers solution to global fisheries collapse] Eureka alert.</ref>\n\n[[Fish farming]] has been proposed as a more sustainable alternative to traditional capture of [[Wild fisheries|wild fish]]. However, fish farming has been found to have negative impacts on nearby wild fish<ref>[http://biology.plosjournals.org/perlserv/?request=get-document&doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.0060046 PLoS Biology - Can Farmed and Wild Salmon Coexist?<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and farming of predatory fish [[Aquaculture of salmon#Impact on forage fish|like salmon]] can rely on fish feed that is based on [[fish meal]] and [[Fish oil|oil]] from [[Forage fish|wild fish]].<ref name=\"Alliance\">[[Seafood Choices Alliance]] (2005) [http://www.seafoodchoices.com/resources/afishianado_pdfs/Salmon_Spring05.pdf It's all about salmon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924095748/http://www.seafoodchoices.com/resources/afishianado_pdfs/Salmon_Spring05.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref>\n\n=== Marine reserves ===\n[[Marine reserve]]s serve to foster both environmental protection and marine wildlife safety.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Roberts|first=Callum M.|last2=Polunin|first2=Nicholas V. C.|date=1993|title=Marine Reserves: Simple Solutions to Managing Complex Fisheries?|jstor=4314106|journal=Ambio|volume=22|issue=6|pages=363\u2013368}}</ref> The reserves themselves are established via environmental protection plans or policies which designate a specific marine environment as protected.<ref name=\":7\" /> Coral reefs are one of the many examples which involve the application of marine reserves in establishing marine protected areas.<ref name=\":7\" /> There have also been marine reserve initiatives located in the United States, [[Caribbean]], [[Philippines]], and [[Egypt]].<ref name=\":7\" /> To mitigate the negative environmental impacts of fishing within marine environments, marine reserves are intended to create, enhance, and re-introduce biodiversity within the area.<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Aburto-Oropeza|first=Octavio|last2=Erisman|first2=Brad|last3=Galland|first3=Grantly R.|last4=Mascare\u00f1as-Osorio|first4=Ismael|last5=Sala|first5=Enric|last6=Ezcurra|first6=Exequiel|date=2011-08-12|title=Large Recovery of Fish Biomass in a No-Take Marine Reserve|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=6|issue=8|pages=e23601|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0023601|pmid=21858183|pmc=3155316|issn=1932-6203|bibcode=2011PLoSO...623601A}}</ref> As a result, the primary benefits arising from the implementation of this type of management effort include positive impacts towards habitat protection and species conservation.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Catch-and-release ===\nBased upon [[Catch and release|catch-and-release]] research, this method of mitigation involves several practices to reduce the negative environmental impacts of fishing that include: the duration, timing, and type of hook used during angling.<ref name=\":52\"/> To increase the effectiveness of catch and release fishing and mitigate its negative impacts, species-specific guidelines are required.<ref name=\":52\" /> These guidelines help tailor specific rules and regulations to specific species of fish in relation to their locations and mating and migration cycles.<ref name=\":52\" /> A metastudy in 2005 found that the average catch and release mortality rate was 18%, but varied greatly by species.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bartholomew|first=Aaron|last2=Bohnsack|first2=James A.|date=2005-02-01|title=A Review of Catch-and-Release Angling Mortality with Implications for No-take Reserves|journal=Reviews in Fish Biology and Fisheries|volume=15|issue=1|pages=129\u2013154|doi=10.1007/s11160-005-2175-1|issn=1573-5184}}</ref> While catch-and-release fishing has been wildly used in recreational fishing, it is also beneficial for maintaining fish populations at a stable level for commercial fisheries to receive social and economic benefits.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Donaldson|first=Michael R.|last2=Arlinghaus|first2=Robert|last3=Hanson|first3=Kyle C.|last4=Cooke|first4=Steven J.|date=2008-03-01|title=Enhancing catch-and-release science with biotelemetry|journal=Fish and Fisheries|volume=9|issue=1|pages=79\u2013105|doi=10.1111/j.1467-2979.2007.00265.x|issn=1467-2979|citeseerx=10.1.1.589.1499}}</ref> Combining catch-and-release fishing with [[biotelemetry]] data collection methods allows for researchers to study the biological effects of catch-and-release fishing on fish in order to better suit future conservation efforts and remedies.<ref name=\":10\" /> The environmental impact of recreational fishing may be alleviated to some extent by [[catch and release]] fishing.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Finless Foods]]\n*[[Population dynamics of fisheries]]\n* [[List of harvested aquatic animals by weight]]\n*[[Shark culling]]\n*[[Shark finning]]\n*[[Sustainable seafood]]\n*[[Marine debris]]\n*[[Destructive fishing practices]]\n\n'''Books:'''\n*''[[The End of the Line: How Overfishing Is Changing the World and What We Eat]]'' (book)\n*''[[One Fish, Two Fish, Crawfish, Bluefish]]'' (book)\n\n'''Related:'''\n*[[Environmental effects of meat production]]\n*[[Human impact on the environment]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Castro, P. and M. Huber. (2003). Marine Biology. 4thed. Boston: McGraw Hill.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Hampton | first1 = J. | last2 = Sibert | first2 = J. R. | last3 = Kleiber | first3 = P. | last4 = Maunder | first4 = M. N. | last5 = Harley | first5 = S. J. | year = 2005 | title = Changes in abundance of large pelagic predators in the Pacific Ocean | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 434 | issue = | pages = E2\u2013E3 }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Maunder | first1 = M.N. | last2 = Sibert | first2 = J.R. | last3 = Fonteneau | first3 = A. | last4 = Hampton | first4 = J. | last5 = Kleiber | first5 = P. | last6 = Harley | first6 = S. | year = 2006 | title = Interpreting catch-per-unit-of-effort data to assess the status of individual stocks and communities | url = | journal = ICES Journal of Marine Science | volume = 63 | issue = 8| pages = 1373\u20131385 | doi=10.1016/j.icesjms.2006.05.008| doi-access = free }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Myers | first1 = Ransom | last2 = Worm | first2 = Boris | year = 2003 | title = Rapid worldwide depletion of predatory fish communities | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 423 | issue = 6937| pages = 280\u20133 | doi = 10.1038/nature01610 | pmid = 12748640 | bibcode = 2003Natur.423..280M }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Polacheck | first1 = T | year = 2006 | title = Tuna longline catch rates in the Indian Ocean: did industrial fishing result in a 90% rapid decline in the abundance of large predatory species? | url = | journal = Marine Policy | volume = 30 | issue = 5| pages = 470\u2013482 | doi=10.1016/j.marpol.2005.06.016}}\n*FAO Fisheries Department. (2002). The State of World Fisheries and Aquaculture. Rome: Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Sibert | display-authors = etal  | year = 2006 | title = Biomass, Size, and Trophic Status of Top Predators in the Pacific Ocean | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0a7dc0f67d244832137549192eedada7188e6563| journal = Science | volume = 314 | issue = 5806| pages =  1773\u20131776| doi=10.1126/science.1135347 | pmid=17170304| bibcode = 2006Sci...314.1773S }}\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Walters | first1 = C. J. | year = 2003 | title = Folly and fantasy in the analysis of spatial catch rate data | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b4a200754478530eadfee40d8f79a271f64ef3a3| journal = Canadian Journal of Fisheries and Aquatic Sciences | volume = 60 | issue = 12| pages = 1433\u20131436 | doi=10.1139/f03-152}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.soest.hawaii.edu/PFRP/ Pelagic Fisheries Research Program]\n*[http://www.icsf.net International Collective in Support of Fishworkers website]\n*[http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/N03201755.htm United Nations conference in criticism of deep-sea trawling]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080329072043/http://www.savethehighseas.org/display.cfm?ID=139 Bush backs international deep-sea trawling moratorium]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928074029/http://www.uwtv.org/programs/displayevent.aspx?rID=2515&fID=456 Re-interpreting the Fisheries Crisis seminar by Prof. Ray Hilborn]\n*[http://www.fishonline.org/ UK Database of commercially sold fish with stock status]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080515202354/http://seafoodwatch.org/cr/seafoodwatch.asp Database on stock status of US seafood]\n* [http://www.conservationinstitute.org/ Conservation Science Institute]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110714235353/http://www.olrac.com/knowledge-base The facts about the Commercial Fishing Environment]\n\n{{human impact on the environment|state=expanded}}\n{{fishery science topics|expanded=none}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Environmental Effects Of Fishing}}\n[[Category:Environmental impact of fishing| ]]\n", "name_user": "Seligne", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEffects on Marine habitat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environmental_impact_of_fishing"}
{"title_page": "NOx", "text_new": "{{About|nitrogen oxides produced during combustion|a more extensive list of nitrogen oxides|nitrogen oxide|other meanings of \"Nox\"|Nox (disambiguation){{!}}Nox}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:NO<sub>x</sub>}}\nIn [[atmospheric chemistry]], '''{{NOx}}''' is a generic term for the nitrogen oxides that are most relevant for [[air pollution]], namely [[nitric oxide]] (NO) and [[nitrogen dioxide]] ({{NOx|x=2}}).<ref name=\"Mollenhauer2010\">\n  {{cite book|last1=Mollenhauer|first1=Klaus|last2=Tsch\u00f6ke|first2=Helmut|title=Handbook of Diesel Engines|date=2010|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3540890829|pages=445\u2013446|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1zykqE-UN2QC&lpg=PA446&pg=PA445#v=onepage|ref=Mollenhauer2010}}\n</ref><ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\">\n  {{cite journal|last1=Omidvarborna|title=NOx emissions from low-temperature combustion of biodiesel made of various feedstocks and blends|journal=Fuel Processing Technology|volume=140|pages=113\u2013118|doi=10.1016/j.fuproc.2015.08.031|display-authors=etal|date=December 2015}}\n</ref>  These gases contribute to the formation of [[smog]] and [[acid rain]], as well as affecting [[tropospheric ozone]].\n\n{{NOx}} gases are usually produced from the reaction among [[nitrogen]] and [[oxygen]] during [[combustion]] of fuels, such as [[hydrocarbons]], in air; especially at high temperatures, such as in car engines.<ref name=\"Mollenhauer2010\"/><ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/><ref name=Annamalai2007>\n  {{cite book|last1=Annamalai|first1=Kalyan|last2=Puri|first2=Ishwar K.|title=Combustion Science and Engineering|date=2007|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8493-2071-2|page=775|url=https://books.google.at/books?id=kdfx5_sC1G4C&lpg=PA755&pg=PA755#v=onepage|ref=Annamalai2007}}\n</ref> In areas of high motor vehicle traffic, such as in large cities, the nitrogen oxides emitted can be a significant source of air pollution. {{NOx}} gases are also produced naturally by [[lightning]].\n\nThe term {{NOx}} is chemistry shorthand for molecules containing one nitrogen and one or more oxygen atom.  It is generally meant to include [[nitrous oxide]] (N<sub>2</sub>O),<ref name=\"Mollenhauer2010\"/> although [[nitrous oxide]] is a fairly inert oxide of nitrogen that has many uses as an [[oxidizer]] for rockets and car engines, an [[anesthetic]], and a [[propellant]] for [[aerosol spray]]s and [[whipped cream]].  Nitrous oxide plays hardly any role in air pollution, although it may have a significant impact on the [[ozone depletion|ozone layer]],<ref name=\"sciozo\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ravishankara | first1 = A. R. | last2 = Daniel | first2 = J. S. | last3 = Portmann | first3 = R. W. | year = 2009 | title = Nitrous Oxide (N<sub>2</sub>O): The Dominant Ozone-Depleting Substance Emitted in the 21st Century | url = | journal = Science | volume = 326 | issue = 5949| pages = 123\u2013125 | doi = 10.1126/science.1176985 | pmid = 19713491 }}</ref> and is a significant [[greenhouse gas]].\n\n'''{{NOx|x=''y''}}''' is defined as the sum of {{NOx}} plus the '''{{NOx|x=''z''}}''' compounds produced from the oxidation of {{NOx}} which include [[nitric acid]], [[nitrous acid]] (HONO), [[dinitrogen pentoxide]] (N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>), [[peroxyacetyl nitrate]] (PAN), alkyl nitrates (RONO<sub>2</sub>), peroxyalkyl nitrates (ROONO<sub>2</sub>), the nitrate radical (NO<sub>3</sub>), and [[peroxynitric acid]] (HNO<sub>4</sub>).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www3.epa.gov/ttnamti1/files/2006conference/neuschuler.pdf|title=Air Monitoring Instrumentation Nitrogen Oxides (NOy)|author=US Environmental Protection Agency}}</ref><ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-3rd\">{{Cite book |title=Atmospheric chemistry and physics : from air pollution to climate change |first1=John H. |last1=Seinfeld |first2=Spyros N. |last2=Pandis |edition= Third |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |location=Hoboken, New Jersey |isbn=9781119221166 |oclc=929985467|date=2016-03-29 }}</ref>{{Rp|30}}\n\n== Formation and reactions ==\n\nBecause of energy limitations, oxygen and nitrogen do not react at ambient temperatures. But at high temperatures, they undergo an [[endothermic]] reaction producing various [[oxide]]s of nitrogen. Such temperatures arise inside an [[internal combustion engine]] or a power station [[boiler]], during the combustion of a mixture of air and fuel, and naturally in a [[lightning]] flash.\n\nIn [[atmospheric chemistry]], the term {{NOx}} denotes the total concentration of NO and {{NOx|x=2}} since the conversion between these two species is rapid in the stratosphere and troposphere.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-3rd\"/> During daylight hours, these concentrations together with that of [[ozone]] are in [[steady state]], also known as [[photostationary state]](PSS); the ratio of NO to {{NOx|x=2}} is determined by the intensity of [[sunshine]] (which converts {{NOx|x=2}} to NO) and the concentration of [[ozone]] (which reacts with NO to again form {{NOx|x=2}}).\n\nIn other words, the concentration of ozone in the atmosphere is determined by the ratio of these two species.\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|1}}|2=   <math chem>\\ce{NO2 + h\\nu -> NO + O\\ (^3P)},  \\qquad \\lambda < 424 \\ce{nm}</math>}}\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|2}}|2=   <chem>O\\ (^3P) + O2 + M -> O3 + M </chem>}}\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|3}}|2=   <chem>O3 + NO -> NO2 + O2</chem>}}\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|4}}|2=<math chem>\\frac\\ce{[NO2]}\\ce{[NO]}=\\frac{k_3 [\\ce{O3}]}{j_\\ce{NO2}}</math>}}\n\nThis relationship between {{NOx}} and ozone is also known as the [[Leighton relationship]].\n\nThe time \u03c4 that is needed to reach a steady state among {{NOx}} and ozone is dominated by reaction ({{EquationNote|3}}), which reverses reactions ({{EquationNote|1}})+({{EquationNote|2}}):\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|5}}|2=<math chem>\\tau = \\frac{1}{k_3 [\\ce{NO}]}</math>}}\n\nfor mixing ratio of NO, [NO] = 10 part per billion (ppb), the time constant is 40 minutes; for [NO] = 1 ppb, 4 minutes.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-2nd\">{{cite book |first1=John H. |last1=Seinfeld |first2=Spyros N. |last2=Pandis |title=Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change |edition= 2nd rev. |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |location=Hoboken, New Jersey |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-471-72018-8}}</ref>{{rp|211}}\n\n=== Formation of smog ===\nWhen {{NOx}} and [[volatile organic compound]]s (VOCs) react in the presence of sunlight, they form photochemical [[smog]], a significant form of air pollution. The presence of photochemical smog increases during the summer when the incident solar radiation is higher. The emitted hydrocarbons from industrial activities and transportation react with NO<sub>x</sub> quickly and increase the concentration of ozone and peroxide compounds, especially [[peroxyacetyl nitrate]] (PAN).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Chemistry of the natural atmosphere|last=Peter.|first=Warneck|date=2000|publisher=Academic Press|isbn=9780127356327|edition= 2nd|location=San Diego|oclc=162128886}}</ref>\n\nChildren, people with lung diseases such as [[asthma]], and people who work or exercise outside are particularly susceptible to adverse effects of smog such as damage to lung tissue and reduction in lung function.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/airprogm/oar/urbanair/nox/hlth.html |title=Health and Environmental Impacts of {{NOx}} |accessdate=2007-12-26 |publisher=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Formation of nitric acid and acid rain ===\n\nNO<sub>2</sub> is further oxidized in the gas phase during daytime by reaction with OH\n\n:NO<sub>2</sub> + OH (+M) \u2192 HNO<sub>3</sub> (+M),\n\nwhere M denotes a third molecule required to stabilize the addition product. [[Nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>) is highly soluble in liquid water in aerosol particles or cloud drops.\n\nNO<sub>2</sub> also reacts with ozone to form nitrate radical\n\n:NO<sub>2</sub> + O<sub>3</sub> \u2192 NO<sub>3</sub> + O<sub>2</sub>.\n\nDuring the daytime, NO<sub>3</sub> is quickly photolyzed back to NO<sub>2</sub>, but at night it can react with a second NO<sub>2</sub> to form [[dinitrogen pentoxide]].\n\n:NO<sub>2</sub> + NO<sub>3</sub> (+M) \u2192 N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> (+M).\n\nN<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> reacts rapidly with liquid water (in aerosol particles or cloud drops, but not in the gas phase) to form HNO<sub>3</sub>,\n\n:N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O(liq) \u2192 2 HNO<sub>3</sub>(aq)\n\nThese are thought to be the principal pathways for formation of nitric acid in the atmosphere.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-2nd\"/>{{rp|224\u2013225}} This nitric acid contributes to [[acid rain]] or may deposit to soil, where it makes [[nitrate]], which is of use to growing plants. The aqueous phase reaction\n\n:2&nbsp;{{NOx|x=2}} + H<sub>2</sub>O \u2192 HNO<sub>2</sub> + HNO<sub>3</sub>\n\nis too slow to be of any significance in the atmosphere.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-2nd\"/>{{rp|336}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n=== Natural sources ===\n\n[[Nitric oxide]] is produced during [[thunderstorm]]s due to the extreme heating and cooling within a [[lightning]] strike. This causes stable molecules such as N<sub>2</sub> and O<sub>2</sub> to convert into significant amounts of NO similar to the process that occurs during high temperature fuel combustion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Murray|first=Lee T.|date=2016-04-25|title=Lightning NO x and Impacts on Air Quality|journal=Current Pollution Reports|language=en|volume=2|issue=2|pages=115\u2013133|doi=10.1007/s40726-016-0031-7|issn=2198-6592|doi-access=free}}</ref> NO<sub>x</sub> from lightning can become oxidized to produce [[nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>), this can be precipitated out as acid rain or deposited onto particles in the air. Elevated production of NO<sub>x</sub> from lightning depends on the season and geographic location. The occurrence of lightning is more common over land near the equator in the inter-tropical convergence zone (ITCZ) during summer months.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hauglustaine|first=Didier|last2=Emmons|first2=Louisa|last3=Newchurch|first3=Mike|last4=Brasseur|first4=Guy|last5=Takao|first5=Toshinori|last6=Matsubara|first6=Kouji|last7=Johnson|first7=James|last8=Ridley|first8=Brian|last9=Stith|first9=Jeff|title=On the Role of Lightning NOx in the Formation of Tropospheric Ozone Plumes: A Global Model Perspective|journal=Journal of Atmospheric Chemistry|language=en|volume=38|issue=3|pages=277\u2013294|doi=10.1023/a:1006452309388|issn=0167-7764|date=March 2001|bibcode=2001JAtC...38..277H}}</ref> This area migrates slightly as seasons change. NO<sub>x</sub> production from lightning can be observed through satellite observations.\n\nScientists Ott et al.<ref name=\"repository.kaust.edu.sa\">{{cite journal|title=Production of lightning NOx and its vertical distribution calculated from three-dimensional cloud-scale chemical transport model simulations |author1=Lesley E. Ott |author2=Kenneth E. Pickering |author3=Georgiy L. Stenchikov |author4=Dale J. Allen |author5=Alex J. DeCaria |author6=Brian Ridley |author7=Ruei-Fong Lin |author8=Stephen Lang |author9=Wei-Kuo Tao  |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |volume=115 |issue=D4 |page=D04301 |doi=10.1029/2009JD011880 |year=2010|url = http://repository.kaust.edu.sa/kaust/handle/10754/552104|bibcode=2010JGRD..115.4301O |hdl=10754/552104 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> estimated that each flash of lightning on average in the several mid-latitude and subtropical thunderstorms studied turned {{convert|7|kg|abbr=on}} of nitrogen into chemically reactive {{NOx}}. With 1.4 billion lightning flashes per year, multiplied by 7 kilograms per lightning strike, they estimated the total amount of {{NOx}} produced by lightning per year is 8.6 million tonnes.  However, {{NOx}} emissions resulting from fossil fuel combustion are estimated at 28.5 million tonnes.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.tau.ac.il/~colin/courses/AtmosElec/Schumann07.pdf|title= The global lightning-induced nitrogen oxides source|author1=U. Schumann  |author2=H. Huntrieser |lastauthoramp=yes |journal=Atmos. Chem. Phys.|volume=7 |issue= 14|page=3823 |doi= 10.5194/acp-7-3823-2007|year=2007|accessdate=2016-05-31}}</ref>\n\nA recent discovery indicated that cosmic ray and solar flares can significantly influence the number of lightning strikes occurring on Earth. Therefore, space weather can be a major driving force of lightning-produced atmospheric {{NOx}}.<ref name=\"Annamalai2007\"/>  Atmospheric constituents such as nitrogen oxides can be stratified vertically in the atmosphere.  Ott noted that the lightning-produced {{NOx}} is typically found at altitudes greater than 5&nbsp;km, while combustion and biogenic (soil) {{NOx}} are typically found near the sources at near surface elevation (where it can cause the most significant health effects).<ref name=\"repository.kaust.edu.sa\"/>\n\n=== Biogenic sources ===\n\n[[Agricultural]] [[fertilization (soil)|fertilization]] and the use of [[nitrogen fixing]] plants also contribute to atmospheric {{NOx}}, by promoting [[nitrogen fixation]] by microorganisms.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n|author=J.N. Galloway|date=September 2004\n|title=Nitrogen cycles: past, present, and future\n|journal=Biogeochemistry\n|volume=70\n|issue=2\n|pages=153\u2013226\n|doi=10.1007/s10533-004-0370-0\n|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite journal\n|author1=E.A. Davidson  |author2=W. Kingerlee\n |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1997\n|title=A global inventory of nitric oxide emissions from soils\n|journal=Nutrient Cycling in Agroecosystems\n|volume=48\n|pages=37\u201350\n|doi=10.1023/A:1009738715891\n}}</ref> The nitrification process transforms ammonia into nitrate. And the denitrification is basically the reverse process of nitrification. During the denitrification, nitrate is reduced to nitrite then NO then N<sub>2</sub>O and finally nitrogen. Through these processes, NO<sub>x</sub> is emitted to the atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Atmospheric Chemistry|last=Istv\u00e1n Lagzi, R\u00f3bert M\u00e9sz\u00e1ros, Gy\u00f6rgyi Gelyb\u00f3, \u00c1d\u00e1m Leel\u0151ssy|publisher=E\u00f6tv\u00f6s Lor\u00e1nd University|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nA recent study conducted by the University of California Davis, found that adding nitrogen fertilizer to soil in California is contributing 25 percent or more to state-wide NO<sub>x</sub> pollution levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eesi.org/articles/view/new-study-finds-nitrogen-fertilizer-major-contributor-to-smog-in-california|title=New Study Finds Nitrogen Fertilizer a Major Contributor to Smog in California {{!}} Article {{!}} EESI|last=Inc.|first=Piccirilli Dorsey|website=www.eesi.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref> When nitrogen fertilizer is added to the soil, excess ammonium and nitrate not used by plants can be converted to NO by microorganism in the soil, which escapes into the air. NO<sub>x</sub> is a precursor for smog formation which is already a known issue for the state of California. In addition to contributing to smog, when nitrogen fertilizer is added to the soil and the excess is released in the form of NO, or leached as [[nitrate]] this can be a costly process for the farming industry.\n\nA 2018 study by the Indiana University determined that forests in the eastern United States can expect to see increases in NO<sub>x</sub>, as a result to changes in the types of trees which predominate. Due to human activity and [[Climate change in the United States|climate change]], the maples, sassafrass, and tulip poplar are pushing out the beneficial oak, beech, and hickory. The team determined that the first three tree species, maples, [[sassafras]]s, and tulip poplar, are associated with ammonia-oxidizing bacteria known to \"emit reactive nitrogen from soil.\" By contrast, the second three tree species, oak, beech and hickory, are associated with microbes that \"absorb reactive nitrogen oxides,\" and thus can have a positive impact on the nitrogen oxide component of air quality. Nitrogen oxide release from forest soils is expected to be highest in Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Kentucky and Ohio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.iu.edu/stories/2019/01/iub/releases/22-study-predicts-air-pollutants-forest-soils.html|title=IU study predicts air pollutant increase from U.S. forest soils|last=Fryling|first=Kevin|date=2019-01-22|website=News at IU|language=en|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Industrial sources (anthropogenic sources) ===\n\nThe three primary sources of {{NOx}} in [[combustion]] processes:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.e-inst.com/training/combustion/nitrogen-oxides-nox/|title=Nitrogen Oxides: What is NOx? {{!}} E Instruments {{!}} e-inst.com|work=E Instruments {{!}} e-inst.com|access-date=2018-11-05|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.epa.gov/ttn/catc/dir1/fnoxdoc.pdf|title=Nitrogen Oxides (NOx), Why and How They Are Controlled|date=November 1999|website=Clean Air Technology Center, Information Transfer and Program Integration Division, Office of Air Quality Planning and Standards, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency}}</ref>\n\n* thermal {{NOx}}\n* fuel {{NOx}}\n* prompt {{NOx}}\n\nThermal {{NOx}} formation, which is highly temperature dependent, is recognized as the most relevant source when combusting natural gas. Fuel {{NOx}} tends to dominate during the combustion of fuels, such as coal, which have a significant nitrogen content, particularly when burned in combustors designed to minimise thermal {{NOx}}. The contribution of prompt {{NOx}} is normally considered negligible. A fourth source, called ''feed'' {{NOx}} is associated with the combustion of nitrogen present in the feed material of cement rotary kilns, at between 300&nbsp;\u00b0C and 800&nbsp;\u00b0C, where it is considered a minor contributor.\n\n==== Thermal ====\n\nThermal {{NOx}} refers to {{NOx}} formed through high temperature oxidation of the diatomic nitrogen found in combustion air.<ref name=Beychok>{{cite journal|author=Milton R. Beychok|date=March 1973| title=NOX emission from fuel combustion controlled|journal=[[Oil & Gas Journal]]|volume=|issue=|pages=53\u201356}}</ref> The formation rate is primarily a function of temperature and the [[Residence time distribution|residence time]] of nitrogen at that temperature. At high temperatures, usually above 1600&nbsp;\u00b0C (2900&nbsp;\u00b0F), molecular nitrogen (N<sub>2</sub>) and oxygen (O<sub>2</sub>) in the combustion air dissociate into their atomic states and participate in a series of reactions.\n\nThe three principal reactions (the extended [[Zel'dovich mechanism]]) producing thermal {{NOx}} are:\n\n:N<sub>2</sub>+ O {{eqm}} NO + N\n:N + O<sub>2</sub> {{eqm}} NO + O\n:N + OH<chem>{.}</chem> {{eqm}} NO + H<chem>{.}</chem>\n\nAll three reactions are reversible. [[Yakov Borisovich Zel'dovich|Zeldovich]] was the first to suggest the importance of the first two reactions.<ref name=\"Zel'dovich\">{{cite journal|author=Y.B. Zel'dovich|date=1946| title=The Oxidation of Nitrogen in Combustion Explosions|journal=Acta Physicochimica U.S.S.R.|volume=21|issue=|pages=577\u2013628}}</ref> The last reaction of atomic nitrogen with the [[hydroxyl radical]], <sup>\u2022</sup>HO, was added by Lavoie, Heywood and Keck<ref name=Lavoie>{{cite journal|author1=G.A. Lavoie |author2=J.B. Heywood |author3=J.C. Keck |date=1970| title=Experimental and Theoretical Study of Nitric Oxide Formation in Internal Combustion Engines|journal=Combust. Sci. Tech.|volume=1|issue=4|pages=313\u2013326|doi=10.1080/00102206908952211 }}</ref> to the mechanism and makes a significant contribution to the formation of thermal {{NOx}}.\n\n==== Fuel ====\n\nIt is estimated that transportation fuels cause 54% of the anthropogenic (i.e. human-caused) {{NOx}}. The major source of {{NOx}} production from nitrogen-bearing fuels such as certain coals and oil, is the conversion of fuel bound nitrogen to {{NOx}} during combustion.<ref name=Beychok/> During combustion, the nitrogen bound in the fuel is released as a [[Radical (chemistry)|free radical]] and ultimately forms free N<sub>2</sub>, or NO. Fuel {{NOx}} can contribute as much as 50% of total emissions through the combusting oil and as much as 80% through the combusting of coal.\n\nAlthough the complete mechanism is not fully understood, there are two primary pathways of formation. The first involves the oxidation of volatile nitrogen species during the initial stages of combustion. During the release and before the oxidation of the volatiles, nitrogen reacts to form several intermediaries which are then oxidized into NO. If the volatiles evolve into a reducing atmosphere, the nitrogen evolved can readily be made to form nitrogen gas, rather than {{NOx}}. The second pathway involves the combustion of nitrogen contained in the char matrix during the combustion of the [[Charring|char]] portion of the fuels. This reaction occurs much more slowly than the volatile phase. Only around 20% of the char nitrogen is ultimately emitted as {{NOx}}, since much of the {{NOx}} that forms during this process is reduced to nitrogen by the char, which is nearly pure carbon.\n\n==== Prompt ====\n\nNitrogen oxides are released during manufacturing of nitrogen fertilizers. Though nitrous oxide is emitted during its application, it is then reacted in atmosphere to form nitrogen oxides. This third source is attributed to the reaction of atmospheric nitrogen, N<sub>2</sub>, with radicals such as C, CH, and CH<sub>2</sub> fragments derived from fuel,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fenimore |first1=C P |title=Formation of nitric oxide in premixed hydrocarbon flames |journal=Symposium (International) on Combustion |date=1971 |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=373\u2013380 |doi=10.1016/S0082-0784(71)80040-1 |url=}}</ref> rather than thermal or fuel processes. Occurring in the earliest stage of combustion, this results in the formation of fixed species of nitrogen such as NH ([[nitrogen monohydride]]), NCN ([[diradical]] cyano[[nitrene]]),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pfeifle|first=Mark|last2=Georgievskii|first2=Yuri|last3=Jasper|first3=Ahren W.|last4=Klippenstein|first4=Stephen J.|date=2017-08-28|title=Theoretical investigation of intersystem crossing in the cyanonitrene molecule, <sup>1</sup>NCN \u2192 <sup>3</sup>NCN|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=147|issue=8|pages=084310|doi=10.1063/1.4999788|issn=0021-9606}}</ref> HCN ([[hydrogen cyanide]]), <sup>\u2022</sup>H<sub>2</sub>CN ([[dihydrogen cyanide]]) and <sup>\u2022</sup>CN ([[cyano]] radical) which can oxidize to NO.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shrestha|first=Krishna Prasad|last2=Seidel|first2=Lars|last3=Zeuch|first3=Thomas|last4=Mauss|first4=Fabian|date=2019-05-02|title=Kinetic Modeling of NOx Formation and Consumption during Methanol and Ethanol Oxidation|journal=Combustion Science and Technology|volume=0|issue=9|pages=1628\u20131660|doi=10.1080/00102202.2019.1606804|issn=0010-2202}}</ref> In fuels that contain nitrogen, the incidence of prompt {{NOx}} is comparatively small and it is generally only of interest for the most exacting emission targets.\n\n== Health and environment effects ==\n{{NOx}} reacts with [[ammonia]], moisture, and other compounds to form [[nitric acid]] vapor and related particles. Small particles can penetrate deeply into sensitive lung tissue and damage it, causing premature death in extreme cases. Inhalation of such particles causes or worsens respiratory diseases, such as [[emphysema]] or [[bronchitis]], and aggravates existing heart disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/air/urbanair/nox/noxfldr.pdf |title=How nitrogen oxides affect the way we live and breathe |accessdate=2008-12-10 |publisher=Environmental protection agency |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080716063437/http://www.epa.gov/air/urbanair/nox/noxfldr.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-07-16}}</ref>\n\n{{NOx}} reacts with [[volatile organic compounds]] in the presence of sunlight to form [[ozone]]. Ozone can cause adverse effects such as damage to lung tissue and reduction in lung function mostly in susceptible populations (children, elderly, asthmatics). Ozone can be transported by wind currents and cause health impacts far from the original sources. The American Lung Association estimates that nearly 50 percent of United States inhabitants live in counties that are not in ozone compliance.<ref>[http://www.epa.gov/airscience/quick-finder/ozone.htm Ozone], Environmental Protection Agency.</ref> In South East England, ground level ozone pollution tends to be highest in the countryside and in suburbs, while in central London and on major roads NO emissions are able to \"mop up\" ozone to form {{NOx|x=2}} and oxygen.<ref>[http://www.londonair.org.uk/LondonAir/Guide/WhatIsO3.aspx London Air - What is Ozone?], King's College London, Environmental Research Group</ref>\n\n{{NOx}} also readily reacts with common organic chemicals, and even ozone, to form a wide variety of toxic products: [[nitroarenes]], [[nitrosamines]] and also the [[nitrate radical]] some of which may cause [[DNA]] [[mutations]]. Recently another pathway, via {{NOx}}, to ozone has been found that predominantly occurs in coastal areas via formation of nitryl chloride when {{NOx}} comes into contact with salt mist.<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=2453175|title=Air Pollution: Salt Mist Is the Right Seasoning for Ozone|last=Potera|first=Carol|journal=Environ Health Perspect|year= 2008|volume=116|issue=7|page=A288|pmid=18629329|doi=10.1289/ehp.116-a288}}</ref>\n\nThe direct effect of the emission of {{NOx}} has positive contribution to the greenhouse effect.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lammel|first=Gerhard|last2=Gra\u00dfl|first2=Hartmut|date=1995|title=Greenhouse effect of NOX|journal=Environmental Science and Pollution Research|language=en|volume=2|issue=1|pages=40\u201345|doi=10.1007/bf02987512|pmid=24234471|issn=0944-1344}}</ref> Instead of reacting with ozone in Reaction 3, NO can also react with HO<sub>2</sub>\u00b7 and organic peroxyradicals (RO<sub>2</sub>\u00b7) and thus increase the concentration of ozone. Once the concentration of {{NOx}} exceeds a certain level, atmospheric reactions result in net ozone formation. Since tropospheric ozone can absorb infrared radiation, this indirect effect of {{NOx}} is intensifying global warming.\n\nThere are also other indirect effects of {{NOx}} that can either increase or decrease the greenhouse effect. First of all, through the reaction of NO with HO<sub>2</sub> radicals, <sup>\u2022</sup>OH radicals are recycled, which oxidize methane molecules, meaning {{NOx}} emissions can counter the effect of greenhouse gases. For instance, ship traffic emits a great amount of NO<sub>x</sub> which provides a source of NO<sub>x</sub> over the ocean. Then, photolysis of NO<sub>2</sub> leads to the formation of ozone and the further formation of hydroxyl radicals (\u00b7OH) through ozone photolysis. Since the major sink of methane in the atmosphere is by reaction with <sup>\u2022</sup>OH radicals, the NO<sub>x</sub> emissions from ship travel may lead to a net global cooling.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oecd.org/greengrowth/greening-transport/45095528.pdf |title=Globalisation, Transport and the Environment |publisher=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development |location=France}}</ref> However, {{NOx}} in the atmosphere may undergo dry or wet deposition and return to land in the form of HNO<sub>3</sub>/NO<sub>3</sub><sup>\u2212</sup>. Through this way, the deposition leads to nitrogen fertilization and the subsequent formation of [[nitrous oxide]] (N<sub>2</sub>O) in soil, which is another greenhouse gas. In conclusion, considering several direct and indirect effects, {{NOx}} emissions have a negative contribution to global warming.<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|date=2014|chapter-url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/climate-change-2013-the-physical-science-basis/technical-summary/10E03E078830604105FFA9EC99840672|volume=|pages=31\u2013116|editor-last=Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|publisher=Cambridge University Press|language=en|doi=10.1017/cbo9781107415324.005|isbn=9781107415324|access-date=2018-11-15|title=Climate Change 2013 - the Physical Science Basis|chapter=Technical Summary}}</ref>\n\n{{NOx}} in the atmosphere is removed through several pathways. During daytime, NO<sub>2</sub> reacts with hydroxyl radicals (\u00b7OH) and forms [[nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>), which can easily be removed by dry and wet deposition. Organic peroxyradicals (RO<sub>2</sub>\u00b7) can also react with NO and NO<sub>2</sub> and result in the formation of [[organic nitrate]]s. These are ultimately broken down to inorganic nitrate, which is a useful nutrient for plants. During nighttime, NO<sub>2</sub> and NO can form [[nitrous acid]] (HONO) through surface-catalyzed reaction.<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\">{{Cite book|title=Chemistry of the upper and lower atmosphere : theory, experiments, and applications |first1=Barbara J |last1=Finlayson-Pitts |first2=James N |last2=Pitts |year=2000 |publisher=Academic Press |location=San Diego |isbn=9780080529073 |oclc=162128929}}</ref> Although the reaction is relatively slow, it is an important reaction in urban areas.<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\" /> In addition, the nitrate radical (NO<sub>3</sub>) is formed by the reaction between NO<sub>2</sub> and ozone. At night, NO<sub>3</sub> further reacts with NO<sub>2</sub> and establishes an equilibrium reaction with dinitrogen pentoxide (N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>).<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\" /> Via heterogeneous reaction, N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> reacts with water vapor or liquid water and forms [[nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>). As mentioned above, nitric acid can be removed through wet and dry deposition and this results in the removal of {{NOx}} from the atmosphere.<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\" />\n\n== Biodiesel and {{NOx}} ==\n\n[[Biodiesel]] and its blends in general are known to reduce harmful tailpipe emissions such as: [[carbon monoxide]]; particulate matter (PM), otherwise known as [[soot]]; and unburned [[hydrocarbon]] emissions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://19january2017snapshot.epa.gov/www3/otaq/models/analysis/biodsl/p02001.pdf |title=A Comprehensive Analysis of Biodiesel Impacts on Exhaust Emissions (Draft Technical Report) |publisher=Environmental Protection Agency |location=US |date=October 2002}}</ref>  While earlier studies suggested biodiesel could sometimes decrease NOx and sometimes increase NOx emissions, subsequent investigation has shown that blends of up to 20% biodiesel in USEPA-approved diesel fuel have no significant impact on NOx emissions compared with regular [[diesel fuel|diesel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy07osti/40554.pdf |title=Effects of Biodiesel Blends on Vehicle Emissions |first1=R.L. |last1=McCormick |first2=A. |last2=Williams |first3=J. |last3=Ireland |first4=M. |last4=Brimhall |first5=R.R. |last5=Hayes |publisher=National Renewable Energy Laboratory |location=US |date=October 2006 |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> The state of California uses a special formulation of diesel fuel to produce less NOx relative to diesel fuel used in the other 49 states.  This has been deemed necessary by the California Air Resources Board (CARB) to offset the combination of vehicle congestion, warm temperatures, extensive sunlight, PM, and topography that all contribute to the formation of ozone and smog.  CARB has established a special regulation for Alternative Diesel Fuels to ensure that any new fuels, including biodiesel, coming into the market do not substantially increase NOx emissions. The reduction of {{NOx}} emissions is one of the most important challenges for advances in vehicle technology. While diesel vehicles sold in the US since 2010 are dramatically cleaner than previous diesel vehicles, urban areas continue to seek more ways to reduce the formation of smog and ozone. {{NOx}} formation during combustion is associated with a number of factors such as combustion temperature.  As such, it can be observed that the vehicle drive cycle, or the load on the engine have more significant impact on NOx emissions than the type of fuel used.  This may be especially true for modern, clean diesel vehicles that continuously monitor engine operation electronically and actively control engine parameters and exhaust system operations to limit NOx emission to less than 0.2 g/km.  Low-temperature combustion or LTC technology<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/> may help reduce thermal formation of {{NOx}} during combustion, however a tradeoff exists as high temperature combustion produces less PM or soot and results in greater power and [[fuel efficiency]].\n\n== Regulation and emission control technologies ==\n[[Selective catalytic reduction]] (SCR) and [[selective non-catalytic reduction]] (SNCR) reduce post combustion {{NOx}} by reacting the exhaust with [[urea]] or ammonia to produce nitrogen and water. SCR is now being used in ships,<ref>[http://blueoceansoln.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/W%C3%A4rtsil%C3%A4-Wet-Package-2008-1.pdf W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 Low {{NOx}} Solutions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929073006/http://blueoceansoln.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/W%C3%A4rtsil%C3%A4-Wet-Package-2008-1.pdf |date=2015-09-29 }} [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]], 2008</ref> diesel trucks and in some diesel cars. The use of [[exhaust gas recirculation]] and [[catalytic converter]]s in motor vehicle engines have significantly [[automobile emissions control|reduced vehicular emissions]]. {{NOx}} was the main focus of the [[Volkswagen emissions violations]].\n\nOther technologies such as [[flameless oxidation]] ([[FLOX]]) and [[staged combustion]] significantly reduce thermal {{NOx}} in industrial processes. [[LO-NOx burner|Bowin low {{NOx}} technology]] is a hybrid of staged-premixed-radiant combustion technology with a major surface combustion preceded by a minor radiant combustion. In the Bowin burner, air and fuel gas are premixed at a ratio greater than or equal to the stoichiometric combustion requirement.<ref>Bob Joynt & Stephen Wu, ''Nitrogen oxides emissions standards for domestic gas appliances background study'' Combustion Engineering Consultant; February 2000</ref> [[Water injection (engines)|Water Injection]] technology, whereby water is introduced into the combustion chamber, is also becoming an important means of {{NOx}} reduction through increased efficiency in the overall combustion process. Alternatively, the water (e.g. 10 to 50%) is emulsified into the fuel oil before the injection and combustion. This emulsification can either be made in-line (unstabilized) just before the injection or as a drop-in fuel with chemical additives for long term emulsion stability (stabilized). Inline emulsified fuel/water mixtures show {{NOx}} reductions between 4 and 83%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hielscher.com/ultrasonics/oil_nox_reduction.htm |title=NOx-Reduction by Oil/Water-Emulsification |accessdate=2010-05-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n{{nitrogen compounds}}\n\n[[Category:Oxides]]\n[[Category:Airborne pollutants]]\n[[Category:Smog]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen\u2013oxygen compounds]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|nitrogen oxides produced during combustion|a more extensive list of nitrogen oxides|nitrogen oxide|other meanings of \"Nox\"|Nox (disambiguation){{!}}Nox}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:NO<sub>x</sub>}}\nIn [[atmospheric chemistry]], '''{{NOx}}''' is a generic term for the nitrogen oxides that are most relevant for [[air pollution]], namely [[nitric oxide]] (NO) and [[nitrogen dioxide]] ({{NOx|x=2}}).<ref name=\"Mollenhauer2010\">\n  {{cite book|last1=Mollenhauer|first1=Klaus|last2=Tsch\u00f6ke|first2=Helmut|title=Handbook of Diesel Engines|date=2010|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3540890829|pages=445\u2013446|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1zykqE-UN2QC&lpg=PA446&pg=PA445#v=onepage|ref=Mollenhauer2010}}\n</ref><ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\">\n  {{cite journal|last1=Omidvarborna|title=NOx emissions from low-temperature combustion of biodiesel made of various feedstocks and blends|journal=Fuel Processing Technology|volume=140|pages=113\u2013118|doi=10.1016/j.fuproc.2015.08.031|display-authors=etal|date=December 2015}}\n</ref>  These gases contribute to the formation of [[smog]] and [[acid rain]], as well as affecting [[tropospheric ozone]].\n\n{{NOx}} gases are usually produced from the reaction among [[nitrogen]] and [[oxygen]] during [[combustion]] of fuels, such as [[hydrocarbons]], in air; especially at high temperatures, such as in car engines.<ref name=\"Mollenhauer2010\"/><ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/><ref name=Annamalai2007>\n  {{cite book|last1=Annamalai|first1=Kalyan|last2=Puri|first2=Ishwar K.|title=Combustion Science and Engineering|date=2007|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-8493-2071-2|page=775|url=https://books.google.at/books?id=kdfx5_sC1G4C&lpg=PA755&pg=PA755#v=onepage|ref=Annamalai2007}}\n</ref> In areas of high motor vehicle traffic, such as in large cities, the nitrogen oxides emitted can be a significant source of air pollution. {{NOx}} gases are also produced naturally by [[lightning]].\n\nThe term {{NOx}} is chemistry shorthand for molecules containing one nitrogen and one or more oxygen atom.  It is generally meant to include [[nitrous oxide]] (N<sub>2</sub>O),<ref name=\"Mollenhauer2010\"/> although [[nitrous oxide]] is a fairly inert oxide of nitrogen that has many uses as an [[oxidizer]] for rockets and car engines, an [[anesthetic]], and a [[propellant]] for [[aerosol spray]]s and [[whipped cream]].  Nitrous oxide plays hardly any role in air pollution, although it may have a significant impact on the [[ozone depletion|ozone layer]],<ref name=\"sciozo\">A. R. Ravishankara, J. S. Daniel, R. W. Portmann (2009), \"Nitrous Oxide (N<sub>2</sub>O): The Dominant Ozone-Depleting Substance Emitted in the 21st Century\". ''Science'', volume 326, issue 5949, pages 123\u2013125. {{pmid|19713491}}{{doi|10.1126/science.1176985}}</ref> and is a significant [[greenhouse gas]].\n\n'''{{NOx|x=''y''}}''' is defined as the sum of {{NOx}} plus the '''{{NOx|x=''z''}}''' compounds produced from the oxidation of {{NOx}} which include [[nitric acid]], [[nitrous acid]] (HONO), [[dinitrogen pentoxide]] (N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>), [[peroxyacetyl nitrate]] (PAN), alkyl nitrates (RONO<sub>2</sub>), peroxyalkyl nitrates (ROONO<sub>2</sub>), the nitrate radical (NO<sub>3</sub>), and [[peroxynitric acid]] (HNO<sub>4</sub>).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www3.epa.gov/ttnamti1/files/2006conference/neuschuler.pdf|title=Air Monitoring Instrumentation Nitrogen Oxides (NOy)|author=US Environmental Protection Agency}}</ref><ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-3rd\">{{Cite book |title=Atmospheric chemistry and physics : from air pollution to climate change |first1=John H. |last1=Seinfeld |first2=Spyros N. |last2=Pandis |edition= Third |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |location=Hoboken, New Jersey |isbn=9781119221166 |oclc=929985467|date=2016-03-29 }}</ref>{{Rp|30}}\n\n== Formation and reactions ==\n\nBecause of energy limitations, oxygen and nitrogen do not react at ambient temperatures. But at high temperatures, they undergo an [[endothermic]] reaction producing various [[oxide]]s of nitrogen. Such temperatures arise inside an [[internal combustion engine]] or a power station [[boiler]], during the combustion of a mixture of air and fuel, and naturally in a [[lightning]] flash.\n\nIn [[atmospheric chemistry]], the term {{NOx}} denotes the total concentration of NO and {{NOx|x=2}} since the conversion between these two species is rapid in the stratosphere and troposphere.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-3rd\"/> During daylight hours, these concentrations together with that of [[ozone]] are in [[steady state]], also known as [[photostationary state]](PSS); the ratio of NO to {{NOx|x=2}} is determined by the intensity of [[sunshine]] (which converts {{NOx|x=2}} to NO) and the concentration of [[ozone]] (which reacts with NO to again form {{NOx|x=2}}).\n\nIn other words, the concentration of ozone in the atmosphere is determined by the ratio of these two species.\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|1}}|2=   <math chem>\\ce{NO2 + h\\nu -> NO + O\\ (^3P)},  \\qquad \\lambda < 424 \\ce{nm}</math>}}\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|2}}|2=   <chem>O\\ (^3P) + O2 + M -> O3 + M </chem>}}\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|3}}|2=   <chem>O3 + NO -> NO2 + O2</chem>}}\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|4}}|2=<math chem>\\frac\\ce{[NO2]}\\ce{[NO]}=\\frac{k_3 [\\ce{O3}]}{j_\\ce{NO2}}</math>}}\n\nThis relationship between {{NOx}} and ozone is also known as the [[Leighton relationship]].\n\nThe time \u03c4 that is needed to reach a steady state among {{NOx}} and ozone is dominated by reaction ({{EquationNote|3}}), which reverses reactions ({{EquationNote|1}})+({{EquationNote|2}}):\n\n{{NumBlk|:|3={{EquationRef|5}}|2=<math chem>\\tau = \\frac{1}{k_3 [\\ce{NO}]}</math>}}\n\nfor mixing ratio of NO, [NO] = 10 part per billion (ppb), the time constant is 40 minutes; for [NO] = 1 ppb, 4 minutes.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-2nd\">{{cite book |first1=John H. |last1=Seinfeld |first2=Spyros N. |last2=Pandis |title=Atmospheric Chemistry and Physics: From Air Pollution to Climate Change |edition= 2nd rev. |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |location=Hoboken, New Jersey |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-471-72018-8}}</ref>{{rp|211}}\n\n=== Formation of smog ===\nWhen {{NOx}} and [[volatile organic compound]]s (VOCs) react in the presence of sunlight, they form photochemical [[smog]], a significant form of air pollution. The presence of photochemical smog increases during the summer when the incident solar radiation is higher. The emitted hydrocarbons from industrial activities and transportation react with NO<sub>x</sub> quickly and increase the concentration of ozone and peroxide compounds, especially [[peroxyacetyl nitrate]] (PAN).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Chemistry of the natural atmosphere|last=Peter.|first=Warneck|date=2000|publisher=Academic Press|isbn=9780127356327|edition= 2nd|location=San Diego|oclc=162128886}}</ref>\n\nChildren, people with lung diseases such as [[asthma]], and people who work or exercise outside are particularly susceptible to adverse effects of smog such as damage to lung tissue and reduction in lung function.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/airprogm/oar/urbanair/nox/hlth.html |title=Health and Environmental Impacts of {{NOx}} |accessdate=2007-12-26 |publisher=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Formation of nitric acid and acid rain ===\n\nNO<sub>2</sub> is further oxidized in the gas phase during daytime by reaction with OH\n\n:NO<sub>2</sub> + OH (+M) \u2192 HNO<sub>3</sub> (+M),\n\nwhere M denotes a third molecule required to stabilize the addition product. [[Nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>) is highly soluble in liquid water in aerosol particles or cloud drops.\n\nNO<sub>2</sub> also reacts with ozone to form nitrate radical\n\n:NO<sub>2</sub> + O<sub>3</sub> \u2192 NO<sub>3</sub> + O<sub>2</sub>.\n\nDuring the daytime, NO<sub>3</sub> is quickly photolyzed back to NO<sub>2</sub>, but at night it can react with a second NO<sub>2</sub> to form [[dinitrogen pentoxide]].\n\n:NO<sub>2</sub> + NO<sub>3</sub> (+M) \u2192 N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> (+M).\n\nN<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> reacts rapidly with liquid water (in aerosol particles or cloud drops, but not in the gas phase) to form HNO<sub>3</sub>,\n\n:N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> + H<sub>2</sub>O(liq) \u2192 2 HNO<sub>3</sub>(aq)\n\nThese are thought to be the principal pathways for formation of nitric acid in the atmosphere.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-2nd\"/>{{rp|224\u2013225}} This nitric acid contributes to [[acid rain]] or may deposit to soil, where it makes [[nitrate]], which is of use to growing plants. The aqueous phase reaction\n\n:2&nbsp;{{NOx|x=2}} + H<sub>2</sub>O \u2192 HNO<sub>2</sub> + HNO<sub>3</sub>\n\nis too slow to be of any significance in the atmosphere.<ref name=\"SeinfeldPandis-2nd\"/>{{rp|336}}\n\n== Sources ==\n\n=== Natural sources ===\n\n[[Nitric oxide]] is produced during [[thunderstorm]]s due to the extreme heating and cooling within a [[lightning]] strike. This causes stable molecules such as N<sub>2</sub> and O<sub>2</sub> to convert into significant amounts of NO similar to the process that occurs during high temperature fuel combustion.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Murray|first=Lee T.|date=2016-04-25|title=Lightning NO x and Impacts on Air Quality|journal=Current Pollution Reports|language=en|volume=2|issue=2|pages=115\u2013133|doi=10.1007/s40726-016-0031-7|issn=2198-6592|doi-access=free}}</ref> NO<sub>x</sub> from lightning can become oxidized to produce [[nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>), this can be precipitated out as acid rain or deposited onto particles in the air. Elevated production of NO<sub>x</sub> from lightning depends on the season and geographic location. The occurrence of lightning is more common over land near the equator in the inter-tropical convergence zone (ITCZ) during summer months.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hauglustaine|first=Didier|last2=Emmons|first2=Louisa|last3=Newchurch|first3=Mike|last4=Brasseur|first4=Guy|last5=Takao|first5=Toshinori|last6=Matsubara|first6=Kouji|last7=Johnson|first7=James|last8=Ridley|first8=Brian|last9=Stith|first9=Jeff|title=On the Role of Lightning NOx in the Formation of Tropospheric Ozone Plumes: A Global Model Perspective|journal=Journal of Atmospheric Chemistry|language=en|volume=38|issue=3|pages=277\u2013294|doi=10.1023/a:1006452309388|issn=0167-7764|date=March 2001|bibcode=2001JAtC...38..277H}}</ref> This area migrates slightly as seasons change. NO<sub>x</sub> production from lightning can be observed through satellite observations.\n\nScientists Ott et al.<ref name=\"repository.kaust.edu.sa\">{{cite journal|title=Production of lightning NOx and its vertical distribution calculated from three-dimensional cloud-scale chemical transport model simulations |author1=Lesley E. Ott |author2=Kenneth E. Pickering |author3=Georgiy L. Stenchikov |author4=Dale J. Allen |author5=Alex J. DeCaria |author6=Brian Ridley |author7=Ruei-Fong Lin |author8=Stephen Lang |author9=Wei-Kuo Tao  |last-author-amp=yes |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research |volume=115 |issue=D4 |page=D04301 |doi=10.1029/2009JD011880 |year=2010|url = http://repository.kaust.edu.sa/kaust/handle/10754/552104|bibcode=2010JGRD..115.4301O |hdl=10754/552104 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> estimated that each flash of lightning on average in the several mid-latitude and subtropical thunderstorms studied turned {{convert|7|kg|abbr=on}} of nitrogen into chemically reactive {{NOx}}. With 1.4 billion lightning flashes per year, multiplied by 7 kilograms per lightning strike, they estimated the total amount of {{NOx}} produced by lightning per year is 8.6 million tonnes.  However, {{NOx}} emissions resulting from fossil fuel combustion are estimated at 28.5 million tonnes.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.tau.ac.il/~colin/courses/AtmosElec/Schumann07.pdf|title= The global lightning-induced nitrogen oxides source|author1=U. Schumann  |author2=H. Huntrieser |lastauthoramp=yes |journal=Atmos. Chem. Phys.|volume=7 |issue= 14|page=3823 |doi= 10.5194/acp-7-3823-2007|year=2007|accessdate=2016-05-31}}</ref>\n\nA recent discovery indicated that cosmic ray and solar flares can significantly influence the number of lightning strikes occurring on Earth. Therefore, space weather can be a major driving force of lightning-produced atmospheric {{NOx}}.<ref name=\"Annamalai2007\"/>  Atmospheric constituents such as nitrogen oxides can be stratified vertically in the atmosphere.  Ott noted that the lightning-produced {{NOx}} is typically found at altitudes greater than 5&nbsp;km, while combustion and biogenic (soil) {{NOx}} are typically found near the sources at near surface elevation (where it can cause the most significant health effects).<ref name=\"repository.kaust.edu.sa\"/>\n\n=== Biogenic sources ===\n\n[[Agricultural]] [[fertilization (soil)|fertilization]] and the use of [[nitrogen fixing]] plants also contribute to atmospheric {{NOx}}, by promoting [[nitrogen fixation]] by microorganisms.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n|author=J.N. Galloway|date=September 2004\n|title=Nitrogen cycles: past, present, and future\n|journal=Biogeochemistry\n|volume=70\n|issue=2\n|pages=153\u2013226\n|doi=10.1007/s10533-004-0370-0\n|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite journal\n|author1=E.A. Davidson  |author2=W. Kingerlee\n |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1997\n|title=A global inventory of nitric oxide emissions from soils\n|journal=Nutrient Cycling in Agroecosystems\n|volume=48\n|pages=37\u201350\n|doi=10.1023/A:1009738715891\n}}</ref> The nitrification process transforms ammonia into nitrate. And the denitrification is basically the reverse process of nitrification. During the denitrification, nitrate is reduced to nitrite then NO then N<sub>2</sub>O and finally nitrogen. Through these processes, NO<sub>x</sub> is emitted to the atmosphere.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Atmospheric Chemistry|last=Istv\u00e1n Lagzi, R\u00f3bert M\u00e9sz\u00e1ros, Gy\u00f6rgyi Gelyb\u00f3, \u00c1d\u00e1m Leel\u0151ssy|publisher=E\u00f6tv\u00f6s Lor\u00e1nd University|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nA recent study conducted by the University of California Davis, found that adding nitrogen fertilizer to soil in California is contributing 25 percent or more to state-wide NO<sub>x</sub> pollution levels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eesi.org/articles/view/new-study-finds-nitrogen-fertilizer-major-contributor-to-smog-in-california|title=New Study Finds Nitrogen Fertilizer a Major Contributor to Smog in California {{!}} Article {{!}} EESI|last=Inc.|first=Piccirilli Dorsey|website=www.eesi.org|language=en|access-date=2018-10-18}}</ref> When nitrogen fertilizer is added to the soil, excess ammonium and nitrate not used by plants can be converted to NO by microorganism in the soil, which escapes into the air. NO<sub>x</sub> is a precursor for smog formation which is already a known issue for the state of California. In addition to contributing to smog, when nitrogen fertilizer is added to the soil and the excess is released in the form of NO, or leached as [[nitrate]] this can be a costly process for the farming industry.\n\nA 2018 study by the Indiana University determined that forests in the eastern United States can expect to see increases in NO<sub>x</sub>, as a result to changes in the types of trees which predominate. Due to human activity and [[Climate change in the United States|climate change]], the maples, sassafrass, and tulip poplar are pushing out the beneficial oak, beech, and hickory. The team determined that the first three tree species, maples, [[sassafras]]s, and tulip poplar, are associated with ammonia-oxidizing bacteria known to \"emit reactive nitrogen from soil.\" By contrast, the second three tree species, oak, beech and hickory, are associated with microbes that \"absorb reactive nitrogen oxides,\" and thus can have a positive impact on the nitrogen oxide component of air quality. Nitrogen oxide release from forest soils is expected to be highest in Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Kentucky and Ohio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.iu.edu/stories/2019/01/iub/releases/22-study-predicts-air-pollutants-forest-soils.html|title=IU study predicts air pollutant increase from U.S. forest soils|last=Fryling|first=Kevin|date=2019-01-22|website=News at IU|language=en|access-date=2019-01-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Industrial sources (anthropogenic sources) ===\n\nThe three primary sources of {{NOx}} in [[combustion]] processes:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.e-inst.com/training/combustion/nitrogen-oxides-nox/|title=Nitrogen Oxides: What is NOx? {{!}} E Instruments {{!}} e-inst.com|work=E Instruments {{!}} e-inst.com|access-date=2018-11-05|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www3.epa.gov/ttn/catc/dir1/fnoxdoc.pdf|title=Nitrogen Oxides (NOx), Why and How They Are Controlled|date=November 1999|website=Clean Air Technology Center, Information Transfer and Program Integration Division, Office of Air Quality Planning and Standards, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency}}</ref>\n\n* thermal {{NOx}}\n* fuel {{NOx}}\n* prompt {{NOx}}\n\nThermal {{NOx}} formation, which is highly temperature dependent, is recognized as the most relevant source when combusting natural gas. Fuel {{NOx}} tends to dominate during the combustion of fuels, such as coal, which have a significant nitrogen content, particularly when burned in combustors designed to minimise thermal {{NOx}}. The contribution of prompt {{NOx}} is normally considered negligible. A fourth source, called ''feed'' {{NOx}} is associated with the combustion of nitrogen present in the feed material of cement rotary kilns, at between 300&nbsp;\u00b0C and 800&nbsp;\u00b0C, where it is considered a minor contributor.\n\n==== Thermal ====\n\nThermal {{NOx}} refers to {{NOx}} formed through high temperature oxidation of the diatomic nitrogen found in combustion air.<ref name=Beychok>{{cite journal|author=Milton R. Beychok|date=March 1973| title=NOX emission from fuel combustion controlled|journal=[[Oil & Gas Journal]]|volume=|issue=|pages=53\u201356}}</ref> The formation rate is primarily a function of temperature and the [[Residence time distribution|residence time]] of nitrogen at that temperature. At high temperatures, usually above 1600&nbsp;\u00b0C (2900&nbsp;\u00b0F), molecular nitrogen (N<sub>2</sub>) and oxygen (O<sub>2</sub>) in the combustion air dissociate into their atomic states and participate in a series of reactions.\n\nThe three principal reactions (the extended [[Zel'dovich mechanism]]) producing thermal {{NOx}} are:\n\n:N<sub>2</sub>+ O {{eqm}} NO + N\n:N + O<sub>2</sub> {{eqm}} NO + O\n:N + OH<chem>{.}</chem> {{eqm}} NO + H<chem>{.}</chem>\n\nAll three reactions are reversible. [[Yakov Borisovich Zel'dovich|Zeldovich]] was the first to suggest the importance of the first two reactions.<ref name=\"Zel'dovich\">{{cite journal|author=Y.B. Zel'dovich|date=1946| title=The Oxidation of Nitrogen in Combustion Explosions|journal=Acta Physicochimica U.S.S.R.|volume=21|issue=|pages=577\u2013628}}</ref> The last reaction of atomic nitrogen with the [[hydroxyl radical]], <sup>\u2022</sup>HO, was added by Lavoie, Heywood and Keck<ref name=Lavoie>{{cite journal|author1=G.A. Lavoie |author2=J.B. Heywood |author3=J.C. Keck |date=1970| title=Experimental and Theoretical Study of Nitric Oxide Formation in Internal Combustion Engines|journal=Combust. Sci. Tech.|volume=1|issue=4|pages=313\u2013326|doi=10.1080/00102206908952211 }}</ref> to the mechanism and makes a significant contribution to the formation of thermal {{NOx}}.\n\n==== Fuel ====\n\nIt is estimated that transportation fuels cause 54% of the anthropogenic (i.e. human-caused) {{NOx}}. The major source of {{NOx}} production from nitrogen-bearing fuels such as certain coals and oil, is the conversion of fuel bound nitrogen to {{NOx}} during combustion.<ref name=Beychok/> During combustion, the nitrogen bound in the fuel is released as a [[Radical (chemistry)|free radical]] and ultimately forms free N<sub>2</sub>, or NO. Fuel {{NOx}} can contribute as much as 50% of total emissions through the combusting oil and as much as 80% through the combusting of coal.\n\nAlthough the complete mechanism is not fully understood, there are two primary pathways of formation. The first involves the oxidation of volatile nitrogen species during the initial stages of combustion. During the release and before the oxidation of the volatiles, nitrogen reacts to form several intermediaries which are then oxidized into NO. If the volatiles evolve into a reducing atmosphere, the nitrogen evolved can readily be made to form nitrogen gas, rather than {{NOx}}. The second pathway involves the combustion of nitrogen contained in the char matrix during the combustion of the [[Charring|char]] portion of the fuels. This reaction occurs much more slowly than the volatile phase. Only around 20% of the char nitrogen is ultimately emitted as {{NOx}}, since much of the {{NOx}} that forms during this process is reduced to nitrogen by the char, which is nearly pure carbon.\n\n==== Prompt ====\n\nNitrogen oxides are released during manufacturing of nitrogen fertilizers. Though nitrous oxide is emitted during its application, it is then reacted in atmosphere to form nitrogen oxides. This third source is attributed to the reaction of atmospheric nitrogen, N<sub>2</sub>, with radicals such as C, CH, and CH<sub>2</sub> fragments derived from fuel,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fenimore |first1=C P |title=Formation of nitric oxide in premixed hydrocarbon flames |journal=Symposium (International) on Combustion |date=1971 |volume=13 |issue=1 |pages=373\u2013380 |doi=10.1016/S0082-0784(71)80040-1 |url=}}</ref> rather than thermal or fuel processes. Occurring in the earliest stage of combustion, this results in the formation of fixed species of nitrogen such as NH ([[nitrogen monohydride]]), NCN ([[diradical]] cyano[[nitrene]]),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pfeifle|first=Mark|last2=Georgievskii|first2=Yuri|last3=Jasper|first3=Ahren W.|last4=Klippenstein|first4=Stephen J.|date=2017-08-28|title=Theoretical investigation of intersystem crossing in the cyanonitrene molecule, <sup>1</sup>NCN \u2192 <sup>3</sup>NCN|journal=The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume=147|issue=8|pages=084310|doi=10.1063/1.4999788|issn=0021-9606}}</ref> HCN ([[hydrogen cyanide]]), <sup>\u2022</sup>H<sub>2</sub>CN ([[dihydrogen cyanide]]) and <sup>\u2022</sup>CN ([[cyano]] radical) which can oxidize to NO.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shrestha|first=Krishna Prasad|last2=Seidel|first2=Lars|last3=Zeuch|first3=Thomas|last4=Mauss|first4=Fabian|date=2019-05-02|title=Kinetic Modeling of NOx Formation and Consumption during Methanol and Ethanol Oxidation|journal=Combustion Science and Technology|volume=0|issue=9|pages=1628\u20131660|doi=10.1080/00102202.2019.1606804|issn=0010-2202}}</ref> In fuels that contain nitrogen, the incidence of prompt {{NOx}} is comparatively small and it is generally only of interest for the most exacting emission targets.\n\n== Health and environment effects ==\n{{NOx}} reacts with [[ammonia]], moisture, and other compounds to form [[nitric acid]] vapor and related particles. Small particles can penetrate deeply into sensitive lung tissue and damage it, causing premature death in extreme cases. Inhalation of such particles causes or worsens respiratory diseases, such as [[emphysema]] or [[bronchitis]], and aggravates existing heart disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/air/urbanair/nox/noxfldr.pdf |title=How nitrogen oxides affect the way we live and breathe |accessdate=2008-12-10 |publisher=Environmental protection agency |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080716063437/http://www.epa.gov/air/urbanair/nox/noxfldr.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-07-16}}</ref>\n\n{{NOx}} reacts with [[volatile organic compounds]] in the presence of sunlight to form [[ozone]]. Ozone can cause adverse effects such as damage to lung tissue and reduction in lung function mostly in susceptible populations (children, elderly, asthmatics). Ozone can be transported by wind currents and cause health impacts far from the original sources. The American Lung Association estimates that nearly 50 percent of United States inhabitants live in counties that are not in ozone compliance.<ref>[http://www.epa.gov/airscience/quick-finder/ozone.htm Ozone], Environmental Protection Agency.</ref> In South East England, ground level ozone pollution tends to be highest in the countryside and in suburbs, while in central London and on major roads NO emissions are able to \"mop up\" ozone to form {{NOx|x=2}} and oxygen.<ref>[http://www.londonair.org.uk/LondonAir/Guide/WhatIsO3.aspx London Air - What is Ozone?], King's College London, Environmental Research Group</ref>\n\n{{NOx}} also readily reacts with common organic chemicals, and even ozone, to form a wide variety of toxic products: [[nitroarenes]], [[nitrosamines]] and also the [[nitrate radical]] some of which may cause [[DNA]] [[mutations]]. Recently another pathway, via {{NOx}}, to ozone has been found that predominantly occurs in coastal areas via formation of nitryl chloride when {{NOx}} comes into contact with salt mist.<ref>{{cite journal|pmc=2453175|title=Air Pollution: Salt Mist Is the Right Seasoning for Ozone|last=Potera|first=Carol|journal=Environ Health Perspect|year= 2008|volume=116|issue=7|page=A288|pmid=18629329|doi=10.1289/ehp.116-a288}}</ref>\n\nThe direct effect of the emission of {{NOx}} has positive contribution to the greenhouse effect.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lammel|first=Gerhard|last2=Gra\u00dfl|first2=Hartmut|date=1995|title=Greenhouse effect of NOX|journal=Environmental Science and Pollution Research|language=en|volume=2|issue=1|pages=40\u201345|doi=10.1007/bf02987512|pmid=24234471|issn=0944-1344}}</ref> Instead of reacting with ozone in Reaction 3, NO can also react with HO<sub>2</sub>\u00b7 and organic peroxyradicals (RO<sub>2</sub>\u00b7) and thus increase the concentration of ozone. Once the concentration of {{NOx}} exceeds a certain level, atmospheric reactions result in net ozone formation. Since tropospheric ozone can absorb infrared radiation, this indirect effect of {{NOx}} is intensifying global warming.\n\nThere are also other indirect effects of {{NOx}} that can either increase or decrease the greenhouse effect. First of all, through the reaction of NO with HO<sub>2</sub> radicals, <sup>\u2022</sup>OH radicals are recycled, which oxidize methane molecules, meaning {{NOx}} emissions can counter the effect of greenhouse gases. For instance, ship traffic emits a great amount of NO<sub>x</sub> which provides a source of NO<sub>x</sub> over the ocean. Then, photolysis of NO<sub>2</sub> leads to the formation of ozone and the further formation of hydroxyl radicals (\u00b7OH) through ozone photolysis. Since the major sink of methane in the atmosphere is by reaction with <sup>\u2022</sup>OH radicals, the NO<sub>x</sub> emissions from ship travel may lead to a net global cooling.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oecd.org/greengrowth/greening-transport/45095528.pdf |title=Globalisation, Transport and the Environment |publisher=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development |location=France}}</ref> However, {{NOx}} in the atmosphere may undergo dry or wet deposition and return to land in the form of HNO<sub>3</sub>/NO<sub>3</sub><sup>\u2212</sup>. Through this way, the deposition leads to nitrogen fertilization and the subsequent formation of [[nitrous oxide]] (N<sub>2</sub>O) in soil, which is another greenhouse gas. In conclusion, considering several direct and indirect effects, {{NOx}} emissions have a negative contribution to global warming.<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|date=2014|chapter-url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/climate-change-2013-the-physical-science-basis/technical-summary/10E03E078830604105FFA9EC99840672|volume=|pages=31\u2013116|editor-last=Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change|publisher=Cambridge University Press|language=en|doi=10.1017/cbo9781107415324.005|isbn=9781107415324|access-date=2018-11-15|title=Climate Change 2013 - the Physical Science Basis|chapter=Technical Summary}}</ref>\n\n{{NOx}} in the atmosphere is removed through several pathways. During daytime, NO<sub>2</sub> reacts with hydroxyl radicals (\u00b7OH) and forms [[nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>), which can easily be removed by dry and wet deposition. Organic peroxyradicals (RO<sub>2</sub>\u00b7) can also react with NO and NO<sub>2</sub> and result in the formation of [[organic nitrate]]s. These are ultimately broken down to inorganic nitrate, which is a useful nutrient for plants. During nighttime, NO<sub>2</sub> and NO can form [[nitrous acid]] (HONO) through surface-catalyzed reaction.<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\">{{Cite book|title=Chemistry of the upper and lower atmosphere : theory, experiments, and applications |first1=Barbara J |last1=Finlayson-Pitts |first2=James N |last2=Pitts |year=2000 |publisher=Academic Press |location=San Diego |isbn=9780080529073 |oclc=162128929}}</ref> Although the reaction is relatively slow, it is an important reaction in urban areas.<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\" /> In addition, the nitrate radical (NO<sub>3</sub>) is formed by the reaction between NO<sub>2</sub> and ozone. At night, NO<sub>3</sub> further reacts with NO<sub>2</sub> and establishes an equilibrium reaction with dinitrogen pentoxide (N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>).<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\" /> Via heterogeneous reaction, N<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> reacts with water vapor or liquid water and forms [[nitric acid]] (HNO<sub>3</sub>). As mentioned above, nitric acid can be removed through wet and dry deposition and this results in the removal of {{NOx}} from the atmosphere.<ref name=\"Finlayson-Pitts\" />\n\n== Biodiesel and {{NOx}} ==\n\n[[Biodiesel]] and its blends in general are known to reduce harmful tailpipe emissions such as: [[carbon monoxide]]; particulate matter (PM), otherwise known as [[soot]]; and unburned [[hydrocarbon]] emissions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://19january2017snapshot.epa.gov/www3/otaq/models/analysis/biodsl/p02001.pdf |title=A Comprehensive Analysis of Biodiesel Impacts on Exhaust Emissions (Draft Technical Report) |publisher=Environmental Protection Agency |location=US |date=October 2002}}</ref>  While earlier studies suggested biodiesel could sometimes decrease NOx and sometimes increase NOx emissions, subsequent investigation has shown that blends of up to 20% biodiesel in USEPA-approved diesel fuel have no significant impact on NOx emissions compared with regular [[diesel fuel|diesel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy07osti/40554.pdf |title=Effects of Biodiesel Blends on Vehicle Emissions |first1=R.L. |last1=McCormick |first2=A. |last2=Williams |first3=J. |last3=Ireland |first4=M. |last4=Brimhall |first5=R.R. |last5=Hayes |publisher=National Renewable Energy Laboratory |location=US |date=October 2006 |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref> The state of California uses a special formulation of diesel fuel to produce less NOx relative to diesel fuel used in the other 49 states.  This has been deemed necessary by the California Air Resources Board (CARB) to offset the combination of vehicle congestion, warm temperatures, extensive sunlight, PM, and topography that all contribute to the formation of ozone and smog.  CARB has established a special regulation for Alternative Diesel Fuels to ensure that any new fuels, including biodiesel, coming into the market do not substantially increase NOx emissions. The reduction of {{NOx}} emissions is one of the most important challenges for advances in vehicle technology. While diesel vehicles sold in the US since 2010 are dramatically cleaner than previous diesel vehicles, urban areas continue to seek more ways to reduce the formation of smog and ozone. {{NOx}} formation during combustion is associated with a number of factors such as combustion temperature.  As such, it can be observed that the vehicle drive cycle, or the load on the engine have more significant impact on NOx emissions than the type of fuel used.  This may be especially true for modern, clean diesel vehicles that continuously monitor engine operation electronically and actively control engine parameters and exhaust system operations to limit NOx emission to less than 0.2 g/km.  Low-temperature combustion or LTC technology<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/> may help reduce thermal formation of {{NOx}} during combustion, however a tradeoff exists as high temperature combustion produces less PM or soot and results in greater power and [[fuel efficiency]].\n\n== Regulation and emission control technologies ==\n[[Selective catalytic reduction]] (SCR) and [[selective non-catalytic reduction]] (SNCR) reduce post combustion {{NOx}} by reacting the exhaust with [[urea]] or ammonia to produce nitrogen and water. SCR is now being used in ships,<ref>[http://blueoceansoln.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/W%C3%A4rtsil%C3%A4-Wet-Package-2008-1.pdf W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 Low {{NOx}} Solutions] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929073006/http://blueoceansoln.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/W%C3%A4rtsil%C3%A4-Wet-Package-2008-1.pdf |date=2015-09-29 }} [[W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4]], 2008</ref> diesel trucks and in some diesel cars. The use of [[exhaust gas recirculation]] and [[catalytic converter]]s in motor vehicle engines have significantly [[automobile emissions control|reduced vehicular emissions]]. {{NOx}} was the main focus of the [[Volkswagen emissions violations]].\n\nOther technologies such as [[flameless oxidation]] ([[FLOX]]) and [[staged combustion]] significantly reduce thermal {{NOx}} in industrial processes. [[LO-NOx burner|Bowin low {{NOx}} technology]] is a hybrid of staged-premixed-radiant combustion technology with a major surface combustion preceded by a minor radiant combustion. In the Bowin burner, air and fuel gas are premixed at a ratio greater than or equal to the stoichiometric combustion requirement.<ref>Bob Joynt & Stephen Wu, ''Nitrogen oxides emissions standards for domestic gas appliances background study'' Combustion Engineering Consultant; February 2000</ref> [[Water injection (engines)|Water Injection]] technology, whereby water is introduced into the combustion chamber, is also becoming an important means of {{NOx}} reduction through increased efficiency in the overall combustion process. Alternatively, the water (e.g. 10 to 50%) is emulsified into the fuel oil before the injection and combustion. This emulsification can either be made in-line (unstabilized) just before the injection or as a drop-in fuel with chemical additives for long term emulsion stability (stabilized). Inline emulsified fuel/water mixtures show {{NOx}} reductions between 4 and 83%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hielscher.com/ultrasonics/oil_nox_reduction.htm |title=NOx-Reduction by Oil/Water-Emulsification |accessdate=2010-05-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n{{nitrogen compounds}}\n\n[[Category:Oxides]]\n[[Category:Airborne pollutants]]\n[[Category:Smog]]\n[[Category:Nitrogen\u2013oxygen compounds]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NOx"}
{"title_page": "Scotiabank Arena", "text_new": "{{about|the indoor sporting arena in Toronto|the arena in Calgary|Scotiabank Saddledome|the arena in Halifax, Nova Scotia|Scotiabank Centre|the arena in Ottawa formerly known as Scotiabank Place|Canadian Tire Centre}}\n{{Redirect|Air Canada Centre|the headquarters of Air Canada in Montreal|Air Canada#Headquarters}}\n{{short description|Indoor arena in Toronto, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Scotiabank Arena\n| nickname = The Hanger<br  />The ACC\n| logo_image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena logo.svg|250px]]\n| image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena - 2018 (cropped).jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Exterior view of the arena in 2018\n| address = 40 [[Bay Street]]\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|38|36|N|79|22|45|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| publictransit = {{rint|toronto|rail}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]<br />{{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Union station (TTC)|Union subway station]]<br />{{rint|gotransit|bus}} [[Union Station Bus Terminal|GO Bus Terminal]]\n| broke_ground = March 12, 1997\n| opened = February 19, 1999\n| Acreage = {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4306707/air-canada-centre-gets-new-name/|title=Air Canada Centre sign removed on eve of facility becoming Scotiabank Arena|work=Global News|accessdate=September 27, 2018|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n| operator = \n| former_names = Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. --> {{small|(1999\u20132018)}}\n| construction_cost = {{CAD|265&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/corporate/CompanyFacts.asp|title=Company Facts|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=Air Canada Centre}}</ref><ref name=cost/><br />(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|265000000|1999}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars{{inflation-fn|CA}})\n| architect = Brisbin Brook Beynon Architects (Architect of Record)<br />[[Populous (company)|HOK Sport]]<br />(Consulting Architects)<ref>{{cite web |title=Clubhouse Confidential: When a Bunch of Alpha Males Get Together Daily in a Confined Space, Lots of Things\u2014Good and Bad\u2014Can Happen|first=Michael|last=Faber|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1024724/3/index.htm|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 14, 2002|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| project_manager = Clarendon Projects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|title=Clarendon Projects \u2013 Air Canada Centre|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151414/http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = [[Halcrow Group|Yolles Partnership Inc.]]<ref>[http://www.halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ Halcrow Yolles \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026034118/http://halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ |date=October 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| services engineer = The Mitchell Partnership, Inc.<ref>[http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf The Mitchell Partnership \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115741/http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf |date=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n| general_contractor = [[PCL Construction|PCL Constructors Western, Inc.]]\n| tenants = [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Raptors]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Rock]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (2001\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2001\u20132002)<br />[[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (2010\u2013present, occasional home games)\n| seating_capacity = [[Basketball]]: 19,800 (20,511 with standing room)<br />[[Ice hockey|Hockey]]: 18,800 (20,270 with standing room)<br />[[Lacrosse]]: 18,800<br />[[Concert]]s: 19,800<br />[[Theatre]]: 5,200<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://www.aircanadacentre.com/venue-information/about|publisher=Air Canada Centre|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| parking = 2 underground levels for 212 vehicles<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>\n| website = [https://www.scotiabankarena.com/ scotiabankarena.com]\n}}\n\n'''Scotiabank Arena''', formerly '''Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. -->''', is a multi-purpose [[arena]] located on [[Bay Street]] in the [[South Core, Toronto|South Core]] district of [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]] [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Toronto Rock]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). In addition, the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] play occasional games at the arena. The arena was previously home to the [[Toronto Phantoms]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) during their brief existence.\n\nThe arena  is {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft}} in size. It is owned and operated by [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.]] (MLSE), the same group that owns the Leafs and the Raptors, as well as their respective development teams. In 2018, Scotiabank Arena was the 13th busiest arena in the world and the busiest in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/Chart/2019/01/2018YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues_705.pdf|title=2018 YEAR END Worldwide Ticket Sales TOP 200 ARENA VENUES|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|date=2018|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> It is also the most photographed location in Canada on [[Instagram]] according to [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2018/07/01/scotiabank-arena-now-officially-the-home-of-maple-leafs-and-raptors.html|title=Scotiabank Arena now officially the home of Maple Leafs and Raptors - The Star|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref> Scotiabank Arena is connected to [[Union Station (Toronto)|Toronto Union]] railway station, [[Union station (TTC)|subway station]] and [[Union Station Bus Terminal|bus terminal]] via the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]].\n\nScotiabank Arena has, from its initial design to completion, revolutionized many concepts included in new arenas and stadiums built since then.{{according to whom|date=October 2019}} These features include luxury suites accessible on the ground floor, splitting the main scoreboard into several sections, rotating all sponsor signage in the bowl at once (to allow dominant messaging or \"neutralization\" for events that disallow commercial advertising), and multiple restaurants in and out of the main arena bowl view.\n\nScotiabank Arena also hosts other events, such as concerts, political conventions and [[Esports|video game competitions]].\n\n==History==\n===Site History===\n[[File:Toronto in 1858.jpg|left|thumb|A map showing downtown Toronto in 1858]]The stadium is located on land that was once part of Toronto's inner harbour.  Infill of the inner harbour began in the 1850's and accelerated with the arrival of the railroad resulting in the current day shape of downtown <ref>https://www.cgenarchive.org/toronto-lakeshores.html</ref>.  By 1858 the site was located between two warfs (Rees & Tinnings Warf). As land was expanded southward, it remained under Government control as possible locations of various Union Station expansions.  The majority of the land was still part of the lake up until the early 1900's. By 1925 The northern parcel of the property was turned into of Bayside Park, which had been part of an early proposal that was to have seen the lands south of the rail corridor transformed into an extensive lakeside park that followed today's Esplande. The remaining land was most likely under the control of Central Harbor Terminals<ref>https://maps.library.utoronto.ca/dvhmp/maps.html</ref>.\n\nIn the 1930s the property became the proposed home to [[Canada Post]]'s Toronto Postal Delivery Building.  In the 1920's a postal handling facility already existed in the east wing of the city's then New Union Station (Downtown Toronto's 3rd major train station)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=A Toronto Album 2: More Glimpses of the City That Was|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=K0tIsZ_TAIoC&pg=PA43 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=43 |isbn=}}</ref>. But it quickly reached capacity by the 1930s due to major population growth of Toronto and its surrounding region.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotiabankarena.com/venue-information/about/history|title=History {{!}} Scotiabank Arena|last=Arena|first=Scotiabank|website=www.scotiabankarena.com|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref>. In 1937 the Postmaster General appealed to the Minister of Public Works to approve a new replacement facility at the corner of Bay & Fleet Street (now Lake Shore Boulevard). Approval was granted by the federal Department of Public Works in part to stimulate the depression impacted construction industry<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. Design and construction of the warehouse built with steel & concrete would begin in 1938. Designed by [[Charles B. Dolphin]] it's a building that incorporates a combination of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Moderne]] architectural style. The original building would be built for around $2,000,000 (CAD)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref> [$ 35 million 2020],  The building was strategically located south of Union Station and was connected directly to the train platforms via an underground tunnel. Trains would be able to directly unload mail and move it directly to the mail sorting centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Toronto Postal Delivery Building Postcard.jpg|thumb|left|Toronto Postal Delivery Building c.1950s]]\nUpon completion in 1941 the building would be temporarily handed over to Department of National Defence for wartime storage purposes, and be finally turned over to Canada Post in 1946. Required modifications were made to the building to return it back to its postal delivery purposes as a result of alterations done by the Department of National Defence.  After the refurbishment work was completed in 1948, the building now possessed the capability and equipment for proper mail sorting and other mailing processing functions. Though it was designed as a mail sorting warehouse it was also the home of Postal Station \"A\" which served mostly institutional & commercial clients.  The Ground floor was where the mail was dropped off by both railway carts and postal vans. Unsorted mail was moved by conveyor belts to the top floor and via gravity fed mail chutes sorted by size & destination.  Eventually the sorted mail would end up back on the ground floor where it would be sent out for delivery<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. The building would be used as a postal sorting centre up until 1989.\n\n====Postal Building Sculptures==== \nThe structures most notable feature (which has been retained) are the exterior 13-part series of limestone [[bas relief]] carvings by [[Louis Temporale]] Sr. [[Order of Canada|CM]] which depicts the history of transportation and communication in Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>.  Carved in 1938-39 begins with scenes showing human speech, a runner carrying a message, aboriginals communicating by smoke signal, a group of voyageurs, a schooner & a Royal Mail steamship crossing the ocean from England, the CN train used during the 1939 Royal Tour, the mythical flying boat named 'Canopus' and northern travel by dog sled<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location= |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref>. The sculptors son Louis Temporale jr. helped with restoration efforts in 1998 and in 2016 was still critical of the lack of protection of the artwork by stadium ownership for over 20 years. The nearby elevated Gardiner Expressway results in salt spray which is speeding up the deterioration of the limestone<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/mlse-acc-art-temporale-heritage-1.3395714|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>. \n\n====1990s Transition to Stadium====\nThe the late 1980s, the building & antiquated sorting equipment was in need of major renovations & expensive upgrades. In a cost cutting move (part of larger overall service changes & cuts made to the Crown Corporation under the [[Brian Mulroney]] Conservatives), Canada Post decided to close the facility and move operations to an alternate more modern c.1970s letter processing faculty on nearby Eastern Avenue. A structure with easy access to highways was designed specificity for transport truck delivery of mail. By 1989, all of the old building's work was transferred here.<ref name=\":0\" />. The 1980s real estate boom saw the building site become surrounded by skyscrapers, hotels, convention centres, SkyDome stadium & condo towers.  In the early 1990s, real estate developers [[Bramalea (company)|Bramalea Ltd]] and [[Trizec Properties|Trizec]] arranged to purchase the building from Canada Post, and redevelop the site into a {{convert|230,000|m2|sqft|adj=on}} office, retail and residential space. Financial and development details of the purchase imposed various conditions prior to development, including rezoning by the city, remediation of soil contamination by Canada Post.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bramalea's Moves Shake Taxpayers|first=Stevie|last=Cameron|date=November 15, 1992|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nDue to financing difficulties & an ongoing recession which saw many downtown Toronto high rise construction projects paused or cancelled resulted in the building's ownership was reverted back to Canada Post in 1993 and with the structure reaming abandoned. The Toronto Raptors purchased the unused building from Canada Post the following year.<ref name=\"rapnba\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/history/raptors_history.html/| title=Laying the Groundwork for the NBA in Toronto| website=nba.com| accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal terminal now Air Canada Centre.jpg|thumb|left|The arena retains the eastern & southern walls of the original postal structure built, through a process of [[facadism]].]]\nConstruction of the arena was started by the Toronto Raptors, under their initial ownership group headed by Canadian businessman [[John Bitove]]. In 1995, it had been decided that the NBA would expand into Canada. The Toronto Raptors were created and would need an indoor arena to play in. The Canada Post building was chosen to be the new home of the Raptors due to its downtown location and lot size. Other venues such as [[Exhibition Place]], North York Centre, Bay and Wellesley, and Bay and Dundas were also considered. The Canada Post building was purchased for {{CAD|60}} million.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Raptors initially played in SkyDome (now [[Rogers Centre]]) while the arena was constructed.<ref name=\"blogTo\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Bateman|title=That time the Raptors and the Maple Leafs moved to the ACC|url=http://www.blogto.com/city/2014/02/that_time_the_raptors_and_leafs_moved_to_the_acc/|website=blogTo|date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Groundbreaking took place in March 1997. The building retained the [[Art Deco]] Queenston limestone facade of the Toronto Postal Delivery Building along the east (along [[Bay Street]]) and south ([[Lake Shore Boulevard]]) walls of that structure, but the rest of the building (facing [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]) was removed to make room for the arena, through the process of [[facadism]]. The original building is protected under the ''[[Ontario Heritage Act]]''.\n\n====Arena 'Wars'====\nWhen MLGL ([[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment|Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited]] at the time the controlling company of the Toronto Maple Leafs) lost out on their desire to be the franchise owners of the Raptors, competition between the two organizations heated up centred around venues. MLGL declined to allow Maple Leaf Gardens to be used for the NBA upstart as a result pushing Bitove to secure rights to have the Raptors' opening seasons played at SkyDome until construction of the new stadium to be complete.\n\nThe 1930s-era Maple Leaf Gardens was showing its age; the Maple Leafs in desperate desire for a new facility began developing plans for building an all-new stadium with one of the key criteria for the new location that it must be within close walking proximity to both the subway system and GO Transit. During the early stages of construction, MLGL floated to the media plans for their own plans to build a competing single-use stadium on adjacent property just to the north of the stadium atop the train sheds at Union Station (similar to how [[Madison Square Garden]] was constructed) as the new home for the Toronto Maple Leafs.<ref name=ArenaWars>{{cite news|title=Leafs ready to Move (Page 2)|first=Craig|last=Daniels|date=April 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> The reaction from Raptors was nothing but anger. \"This proposed (Maple Leaf) location really disturbs us\" stated team president Richard Peddie, who went on to say that they would fight the Leafs \"every step of the way\" and he didn't understand why the Leafs have refused to join with the Raptors at their site; claiming that the Leafs want to \"build virtually on top of us\".<ref name=\"ArenaWars\" /> The major problem of the Union Station proposal is the land that the stadium would be built on was actually City of Toronto land that was leased out to CN Rail and CP Rail, which were in a major, long-standing dispute over rent payments (dating back to 1969). As a result, MLGL offered the city $156 Million (1997 CAD) in cash & assets to settle any and all outstanding claims and to buy the air rights above the Union Station train platforms.\n\nDuring this period John Bitove who disputed over the future of the arena who as a result of a [[shotgun clause]] was forced to sell his stake to Allan Slaight (who wanted a joint arena deal with MLGL) and now with majority ownership immediately went into talks with MLGL which eventually purchased both the Raptors and their partially completed arena, which subsequently resulted in major modifications to the original design, which was basketball-specific, to make the arena become more suitable for hockey. Originally planned to cost $217&nbsp;million, MLGL increased the budget to $265&nbsp;million after taking control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> The Raptors were twice fined a million dollars (which were donated to their charitable foundation) by the NBA for missing deadlines to begin construction of their new arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors' arena bites dust|last=Christe|first=James|date=May 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\n====Construction==== \nAfter the purchase of the Raptors and the Air Canada Centre the new owners entered into a design-build contract with PCL with the commitment to finish the stadium in 24-months by March 1st 1999<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>.  The intergartion of the Maple Leafs into the new structure would result in a 25% increase in construction costs (over $25 million CAD in 1999)<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>. \n\nThe completed structure included a 15-storey tower (reduced from a proposed 30-stories), four restaurants, and an underground parking lot. \n\n====Opening====\nIn 1998, a strange twist of scheduling conflicts had the Toronto Raptors playing their final regular-season game at [[Copps Coliseum]] in Hamilton, as the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] had first right of refusal for all SkyDome dates.  The Raptors had attempted to play the April 19 match at Maple Leaf Gardens, but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors Move Final Game to Hamilton|date=January 7, 1998|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.apnews.com/7027ff09054e45b3b7471205f12cb521}}</ref>\n[[File:Air Canada Centre in 1999.jpg|thumb|right|Air Canada Centre in July 1999, five months after the arena opened]]\n\nOn December 30th 1998, the building's construction was completed, 9 days ahead of schedule. Opening events took place early the next year and [[Steve Stavro]] (who was the majority shareholder of MLGL) was named CEO. The initial hockey game took place February 20, 1999 (Toronto Maple Leafs vs. [[Montreal Canadiens]]), the first basketball Game on February 21, 1999 (Toronto Raptors vs. [[Vancouver Grizzlies]]), and the opening concert on February 22, 1999 ([[The Tragically Hip]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> Features of the new building consist of a {{convert|65000|sqft|adj=on}} arena and a {{convert|165000|sqft|adj=on}} office tower. There is also an east\u2013west covered, climate controlled galleria and walkway onsite that contains restaurants, the ticket office, and other commercial units. The Galleria also connects Scotiabank Arena to popular locations in the downtown core such as Union Station, Bay Street and York Street. Scotiabank Arena is connected to the underground PATH network. The Galleria also doubles as a historical museum by displaying numerous artifacts from the old Canada Post building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Air-Canada-Centre.aspx|title=Air Canada Centre|work=PCL Constructors|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn its first ten years of operation, the new arena had an estimated economic benefit of $2.4&nbsp;billion. This boosted Toronto's economy and led to further construction in the downtown core. Many projects in the area were completed ahead of schedule as a result of a desire to increase the infrastructure of downtown Toronto, and also from private funding (approximately $13&nbsp;million) that was invested in seeing the economic growth of Toronto. These projects included the Bay West Teamway, Union Plaza, the Galleria (shopping centre), and Bremner Boulevard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Air Canada]] purchased [[naming rights]] to the arena for US$30&nbsp;million for 20 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/marketing/|work=CBC News|title=Branding for dollars|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref>.  Several nicknames for the arena would emerge including 'The Hanger', but it would be the acronym 'ACC' which would be the most commonly referenced shorthand for the stadium and is still commonly used by local residents.\n\n==Current History== \n[[File:PATH Escalators Construction Scotiabank Arena.jpg|thumb|right|Escalators for a new [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] system connection to the under-construction [[CIBC Square]] office complex being installed in the arena's lobby in 2019]]\nIn 2003, MLSE completed a $5-million upgrade of the arena, including a new LED signage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=459588|title=Air Canada Centre Renovations to Improve Ultimate Fan Experience|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  During the summer of 2015, a $10-million upgrade of the arena was carried out, which included the installation of a new scoreboard four times larger than the previous one. The old scoreboard was later installed at [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2015/07/24/acc-to-debut-new-scoreboard-this-year.html|title=Air Canada Centre to debut new scoreboard this year|first=Raju|last=Mudhar|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the winter of 2003\u20132004, the [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] imposed a seven-day penalty on the arena for \"permitting drunken patrons to be in the licensed patrons{{sic}}\" in the fall of 2002 at a Toronto Maple Leafs game and also a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert. As a result of these misdemeanours, there was no alcohol served at the arena from December 21 to 28 in 2003. The venue had multiple major events during this time frame, which included a Toronto Raptors\u2013[[Orlando Magic]] game on December 21, a Toronto Maple Leafs\u2013[[Florida Panthers]] game on December 23, and [[Disney on Ice]]: [[Toy Story 2]], which ran from December 25, 2003 to January 1, 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/air-canada-centre-loses-liquor-licence-for-a-week-1.401537|title=Air Canada Centre loses liquor licence for a week {{!}} CBC Sports|work=CBC|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC08942 - Legends Row (37049346192).jpg|thumb|In September 2014, a group of life-sized statues were installed at the southwest corner of the arena.]]\nOn September 6, 2014, a group of statues known as ''Legends Row'' was unveiled outside the arena at the southwest corner of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2014/09/06/maple_leaf_legends_row_unveils_first_three_honourees.html|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row starts with Ted Kennedy, Darryl Sittler, Johnny Bower|publisher=Torstar Corporation|accessdate=September 27, 2018|work=Toronto Star|date=September 7, 2014|last=Rubin|first=Josh}}</ref> The statues were situated in multiple waves from 2014 to 2016 and include [[Ted Kennedy (ice hockey)|Ted Kennedy]], [[Johnny Bower]], [[Darryl Sittler]], [[B\u00f6rje Salming|Borje Salming]], [[Syl Apps]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Mats Sundin]], [[Dave Keon]], [[Turk Broda]], and [[Tim Horton]]. In 2017, the final four statues were unveiled including [[Red Kelly]], [[Frank Mahovlich]], [[Charlie Conacher]], and [[Wendel Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/maple-leafs-legends-row-adds-conacher-kelly-mahovlich-and-clark/c-286915412|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row 'is full' with four added|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''Legends Row'' now features 14 life-sized statues of former Maple Leaf players alongside a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|round=5}} granite players' bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/2017/10/05/4-more-leafs-added-to-legends-row/wcm/53247716-67d7-445e-9f20-a91a51890592|title=Four more Maple Leafs added to Legends Row|work=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|date=October 5, 2017|last=Hornby|first=Lance|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Renaming====\nThe Air Canada Centre was renamed Scotiabank Arena on July 1, 2018. The landmark 20-year sponsorship agreement between Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment and [[Scotiabank]] is worth about C$800&nbsp;million. This is believed to be the highest-priced annual building and team sponsorship in North American sports history.<ref name=\"MLSEScotiaBankArena\">{{cite news|title=HOME OF THE MAPLE LEAFS AND RAPTORS TO BECOME SCOTIABANK ARENA NEXT SUMMER|url=http://mlse.com/news/scotiabankarena/|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestheadTSN\">{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|website=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The arena is the third in Canada to bear naming rights to Scotiabank.\n\n==Maple Leaf Square==\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|A popular gathering point during [[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] and [[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]] playoff runs, the arena has a large video screen that overlooks the atrium of Maple Leaf Square.]]\n{{main|Maple Leaf Square}}\nIn late 2005, Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment announced that they would be renovating the western side of the Air Canada Centre during the 2008 off-season to connect it with the [[Maple Leaf Square]] development. Maple Leaf Square is jointly owned by MLSE, [[Cadillac Fairview]] and Lantera Developments. The $500&nbsp;million development includes two restaurants, Hotel Le Germain at Maple Leaf Square boutique hotel, extensive retail shopping, including a {{convert|840|m2|sqft|adj=on}} Leafs, [[Toronto Marlies|Marlies]], Raptors, and [[Toronto FC]] store, two 54-storey condominiums, a [[Longo's]] supermarket, and a public square. It opened in 2010. The two-year, $48&nbsp;million renovation of the ACC added a new atrium that includes a High-Definition broadcast studio for [[Leafs Nation Network]] (formerly Leafs TV), [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV (Canadian TV channel)|GolTV Canada]].\n\nThe outside wall of the atrium features a {{convert|9.1|by|15.2|m|ft|adj=on}} video screen overlooking the plaza, which often broadcasts games taking place inside the arena. During [[Stanley Cup playoffs|NHL]] and [[NBA playoffs|NBA playoff]] runs, the square attracts thousands of Leafs and Raptors fans, respectively, sometimes broadcasting away playoff matches featuring the Leafs and/or the Raptors as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=NBA.com/Raptors|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> A section of the square is designated Ford Fan Zone at Maple Leaf Square, with naming rights given to the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]. During Raptors playoff runs, the square has acquired the nickname \"[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]\" after the 1993 film adaptation that inspired the team's name. During the [[2019 NBA Playoffs]] and especially during the [[2019 NBA Finals]], other city squares across Canada also acquired the Jurassic Park nickname, such as in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-jurassic-park-spin-offs-ontario-1.5159009|publisher=CBC|title=Jurassic Park spin-offs popping up as Raptors fever sweeps Canada|author=Lucas Powers}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Concerts===\n{{main|List of entertainment events at Scotiabank Arena}}\n\n===Political conventions===\nIn 2003, the governing [[Liberal Party of Canada]] held their [[2003 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|leadership convention]] at the Air Canada Centre. [[Paul Martin]] was elected as the new leader of the party and thus also became [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]], succeeding [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]].\n\n===Sports===\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1 = Raptors vs Bucks 2.jpg\n | width1 = 165\n | image2 = Buffalo Bandits at Toronto Rock.jpg\n | width2 = 155\n | image3 = Toronto AirCanadaCenter 01.jpg\n | width3 = 165\n |footer= Scotiabank Arena is a [[Multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose arena]] that is able to host a number of sporting events, including basketball, box lacrosse, and ice hockey.\n}}\nThe first Maple Leafs home game took place on February 20, 1999, versus the Montreal Canadiens, won by the Leafs 3\u20132 on an [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal by [[Steve Thomas (ice hockey)|Steve Thomas]]. Maple Leaf home games are generally sold out,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryl|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/toronto-maple-leafs/#h3_jump_10|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and there is a waitlist since the start of 2015 for Season Ticket Holders for upcoming seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Purchase Season Seats|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=73129|website=Toronto Maple Leafs|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The first Raptors game took place the following night versus the then-[[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]]. The Raptors won 102\u201387 in front of a sell-out crowd. The facility hosted the [[2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game|2000 NHL All-Star Game]], the championship game of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], all games of the [[2016 World Cup of Hockey]] and the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game]], the first NBA All-Star Game held outside of the United States.\n\nThe Toronto Rock also moved to the Air Canada Centre from Maple Leaf Gardens for the [[2001 NLL season]]. The Rock's first game was a 17\u20137 win over the [[Ottawa Rebel]] on December 21, 2000.\n\nOn October 3, 2003, Air Canada Centre had a power outage during the third quarter of a Raptors pre-season game against the Athens-based club [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The game was called final, because the power was not restored in time and the Raptors already had a [[Mercy rule|30-point lead]].\n\nAir Canada Centre hosted the [[2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] for the first time, as well as hosted the final match of that tournament, in which Canada was crowned champion, defeating Russia. The ACC co-hosted that tournament with [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, and both venues co-hosted the [[2017 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2017 edition of the same event]], though the ACC did not host the medal rounds.\n[[File:Laura Wright performs during the Invictus Flag Raising (37021670620).jpg|thumb|Flag raising during the [[2017 Invictus Games]] closing ceremonies]]\nIn 2017, the Air Canada Centre hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for [[2017 Invictus Games|that year's Invictus Games]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.invictusgames2017.com/ceremonies/|title=Ceremonies|publisher=Invictus Games Toronto 2017|year=2016|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, the ACC presented the opening ceremony as a live two-hour event spectacular. This ceremony was designed to welcome and honour the 550 competitors and their families who come from 17 different competing nations. The show featured hundreds of cast members, including honorary men and women from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]]. The cast showed a display of ceremony in multiple different productions and the raising of the flag. Other guests of the event included celebrities, world dignitaries, headline music stars and other special guests. They gathered to celebrate the service and stories of the members of the 2017 Invictus Games. Headline performers included [[Laura Wright (singer)|Laura Wright]], [[Alessia Cara]], [[The Tenors]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], and [[La Bottine Souriante]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe ACC hosted the Invictus Games Toronto 2017 Closing Ceremony on September 20, 2017. The event featured an arrangement of international headline music artists, coming together to celebrate and recognize the Invictus Games competitors. The closing ceremony featured headline musical guests [[Bachman & Turner]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[C\u0153ur de pirate|Coeur de Pirate]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. This celebration also included words from world dignitaries as the Games are passed to the host nation of the [[2018 Invictus Games|Invictus Games 2018]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe venue hosted its first championship series when the Raptors played the [[Golden State Warriors]] in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]. The Raptors won the NBA championship, albeit in the Warriors' home arena of [[Oracle Arena]] in [[Oakland]] in Game 6.\n\nThe arena has also played host to five [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/05/ufc-165-heads-to-air-canada-centre-in-toronto-on-sept-21|title=UFC 165 heads to Air Canada Centre in Toronto on Sept. 21|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UFC206\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/8/19/12562718/ufc-releases-schedule-for-rest-of-2016-including-ufc-206-in-toronto|title=UFC releases schedule for rest of 2016 including UFC 206 in Toronto|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| [[UFC 140]]\n| Saturday, December 10, 2011\n|-\n| [[UFC 152]]\n| Saturday, September 22, 2012\n|-\n| [[UFC 165]]\n| Saturday, September 21, 2013\n|-\n| [[UFC 206]]\n|Saturday, December 10, 2016\n|-\n| [[UFC 231]]\n|Saturday, December 8, 2018\n|}\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n\n===Video game competitions===\nOn August 27 and 28, 2016, Air Canada Centre hosted the [[2016 Summer North American League of Legends Championship Series|sixth season of the Summer North American Championship Series]] of ''[[League of Legends]]'' (LoL), marking the first [[League of Legends Championship Series|professional ''League of Legends'' competition]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/na-summer-finals-coming-toronto|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is a popular [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) [[PC game|computer game]] by American video game developer [[Riot Games]]; ''League of Legends'' competitions are among the most viewed among professional video game competitions worldwide. During the final round, [[Team SoloMid]] (TSM) defeated [[Cloud9]] (C9) three matches to one in a best-of-five format. The Summer North American Championship Series serve as the qualifiers for the annual [[League of Legends World Championship]] for North American teams.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.scotiabankarena.com/}}\n* [http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html Toronto's Historical Plaques; Toronto Postal Delivery Building]\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Ice hockey|Canada|Ontario}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n&nbsp;\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Raptors]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Rock]]\n | years = 2000\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]]\n | years = 2001\u20132002\n | before = [[XL Center|Hartford Civic Center]]\n | after = last arena\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[National Hockey League All-Star Game|NHL All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2000\n | before = [[Amalie Arena|St. Pete Times Forum]]\n | after = [[Pepsi Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of the<br />[[NBA All-Star Game]]\n | years = 2016\n | before = [[Madison Square Garden]]\n | after = [[Smoothie King Center]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Host of<br />[[Unforgiven (2006)|Unforgiven]]\n | years = 2006\n | before = [[Chesapeake Energy Arena|Ford Center]]\n | after = [[FedExForum]]\n}}\n{{End}}\n{{Toronto landmarks}}\n{{Sport venues in Toronto}}\n{{NHL Arenas}}\n{{NBA Arenas}}\n{{NLL Arenas}}\n{{Toronto Maple Leafs}}\n{{Toronto Raptors}}\n{{Toronto Phantoms}}\n{{Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment}}\n{{Canada Cup World Cup of Hockey Finals venues}}\n}}<!-- end of infoboxes -->\n\n[[Category:Indoor ice hockey venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Indoor lacrosse venues in Canada]]\n[[Category:Basketball venues in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Music venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Sports venues completed in 1999]]\n[[Category:Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n[[Category:Toronto Raptors venues]]\n[[Category:Sports venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:National Hockey League venues]]\n[[Category:National Basketball Association venues]]\n[[Category:PATH (Toronto)]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey venues in Toronto]]\n[[Category:City of Toronto Heritage Properties]]\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Scotiabank]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the indoor sporting arena in Toronto|the arena in Calgary|Scotiabank Saddledome|the arena in Halifax, Nova Scotia|Scotiabank Centre|the arena in Ottawa formerly known as Scotiabank Place|Canadian Tire Centre}}\n{{Redirect|Air Canada Centre|the headquarters of Air Canada in Montreal|Air Canada#Headquarters}}\n{{short description|Indoor arena in Toronto, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=January 2015}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox venue\n| stadium_name = Scotiabank Arena\n| nickname = The Hanger<br  />The ACC\n| logo_image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena logo.svg|250px]]\n| image = [[File:Scotiabank Arena - 2018 (cropped).jpg|250px]]\n| caption = Exterior view of the arena in 2018\n| address = 40 [[Bay Street]]\n| location = [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|43|38|36|N|79|22|45|W|type:landmark_scale:2000|display=it}}\n| pushpin_map = Canada Toronto#Canada Ontario#Canada\n| pushpin_relief = yes\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Toronto##Location in Ontario##Location in Canada\n| publictransit = {{rint|toronto|rail}} [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]<br />{{rint|toronto|subway|1}} [[Union station (TTC)|Union subway station]]<br />{{rint|gotransit|bus}} [[Union Station Bus Terminal|GO Bus Terminal]]\n| broke_ground = March 12, 1997\n| opened = February 19, 1999\n| Acreage = {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4306707/air-canada-centre-gets-new-name/|title=Air Canada Centre sign removed on eve of facility becoming Scotiabank Arena|work=Global News|accessdate=September 27, 2018|publisher=Corus Entertainment Inc.|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| owner = [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]\n| operator = \n| former_names = Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. --> {{small|(1999\u20132018)}}\n| construction_cost = {{CAD|265&nbsp;million}}<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theaircanadacentre.com/corporate/CompanyFacts.asp|title=Company Facts|accessdate=August 29, 2017|publisher=Air Canada Centre}}</ref><ref name=cost/><br />(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|CA|265000000|1999}}}} in {{Inflation-year|CA}} dollars{{inflation-fn|CA}})\n| architect = Brisbin Brook Beynon Architects (Architect of Record)<br />[[Populous (company)|HOK Sport]]<br />(Consulting Architects)<ref>{{cite web |title=Clubhouse Confidential: When a Bunch of Alpha Males Get Together Daily in a Confined Space, Lots of Things\u2014Good and Bad\u2014Can Happen|first=Michael|last=Faber|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1024724/3/index.htm|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 14, 2002|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n| project_manager = Clarendon Projects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|title=Clarendon Projects \u2013 Air Canada Centre|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402151414/http://www.clarendonprojects.com/aircanadacentre.html|archivedate=April 2, 2012}}</ref>\n| structural engineer = [[Halcrow Group|Yolles Partnership Inc.]]<ref>[http://www.halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ Halcrow Yolles \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026034118/http://halcrow.com/Our-projects/Project-details/Air-Canada-Centre-Canada/ |date=October 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n| services engineer = The Mitchell Partnership, Inc.<ref>[http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf The Mitchell Partnership \u2013 Air Canada Centre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517115741/http://www.tmptoronto.com/document_library/Air%20Canada%20Centre.pdf |date=May 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n| general_contractor = [[PCL Construction|PCL Constructors Western, Inc.]]\n| tenants = [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] ([[National Hockey League|NHL]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Raptors]] ([[National Basketball Association|NBA]]) (1999\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Rock]] ([[National Lacrosse League|NLL]]) (2001\u2013present)<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]] ([[Arena Football League|AFL]]) (2001\u20132002)<br />[[Toronto Marlies]] ([[American Hockey League|AHL]]) (2010\u2013present, occasional home games)\n| seating_capacity = [[Basketball]]: 19,800 (20,511 with standing room)<br />[[Ice hockey|Hockey]]: 18,800 (20,270 with standing room)<br />[[Lacrosse]]: 18,800<br />[[Concert]]s: 19,800<br />[[Theatre]]: 5,200<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=https://www.aircanadacentre.com/venue-information/about|publisher=Air Canada Centre|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| parking = 2 underground levels for 212 vehicles<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>\n| website = [https://www.scotiabankarena.com/ scotiabankarena.com]\n}}\n\n'''Scotiabank Arena''', formerly '''Air Canada Centre<!-- This article uses Canadian English. \"Centre\" is the correct spelling in this case. -->''', is a multi-purpose [[arena]] located on [[Bay Street]] in the [[South Core, Toronto|South Core]] district of [[Downtown Toronto|Downtown]] [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada. It is the home of the [[Toronto Maple Leafs]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL), the [[Toronto Raptors]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) and the [[Toronto Rock]] of the [[National Lacrosse League]] (NLL). In addition, the minor league [[Toronto Marlies]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Raptors 905]] of the [[NBA G League]] play occasional games at the arena. The arena was previously home to the [[Toronto Phantoms]] of the [[Arena Football League]] (AFL) during their brief existence.\n\nThe arena  is {{convert|61780.5|m2|sqft}} in size. It is owned and operated by [[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment|Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment Ltd.]] (MLSE), the same group that owns the Leafs and the Raptors, as well as their respective development teams. In 2018, Scotiabank Arena was the 13th busiest arena in the world and the busiest in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pollstar.com/Chart/2019/01/2018YearEndWorldwideTicketSalesTop200ArenaVenues_705.pdf|title=2018 YEAR END Worldwide Ticket Sales TOP 200 ARENA VENUES|publisher=[[Pollstar]]|date=2018|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref> It is also the most photographed location in Canada on [[Instagram]] according to [[BuzzFeed]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2018/07/01/scotiabank-arena-now-officially-the-home-of-maple-leafs-and-raptors.html|title=Scotiabank Arena now officially the home of Maple Leafs and Raptors - The Star|publisher=Toronto Star}}</ref> Scotiabank Arena is connected to [[Union Station (Toronto)|Toronto Union]] railway station, [[Union station (TTC)|subway station]] and [[Union Station Bus Terminal|bus terminal]] via the [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]].\n\nScotiabank Arena has, from its initial design to completion, revolutionized many concepts included in new arenas and stadiums built since then.{{according to whom|date=October 2019}} These features include luxury suites accessible on the ground floor, splitting the main scoreboard into several sections, rotating all sponsor signage in the bowl at once (to allow dominant messaging or \"neutralization\" for events that disallow commercial advertising), and multiple restaurants in and out of the main arena bowl view.\n\nScotiabank Arena also hosts other events, such as concerts, political conventions and [[Esports|video game competitions]].\n\n==History==\n===Site History===\n[[File:Toronto in 1858.jpg|left|thumb|A map showing downtown Toronto in 1858]]The stadium is located on land that was once part of Toronto's inner harbour.  Infill of the inner harbour began in the 1850's and accelerated with the arrival of the railroad resulting in the current day shape of downtown <ref>https://www.cgenarchive.org/toronto-lakeshores.html</ref>.  By 1858 the site was located between two warfs (Rees & Tinnings Warf). As land was expanded southward, it remained under Government control as possible locations of various Union Station expansions.  The majority of the land was still part of the lake up until the early 1900's. By 1925 The northern parcel of the property was turned into of Bayside Park, which had been part of an early proposal that was to have seen the lands south of the rail corridor transformed into an extensive lakeside park that followed today's Esplande. The remaining land was most likely under the control of Central Harbor Terminals<ref>https://maps.library.utoronto.ca/dvhmp/maps.html</ref>.\n\nIn the 1930s the property became the proposed home to [[Canada Post]]'s Toronto Postal Delivery Building.  In the 1920's a postal handling facility already existed in the east wing of the city's then New Union Station (Downtown Toronto's 3rd major train station)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=A Toronto Album 2: More Glimpses of the City That Was|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=K0tIsZ_TAIoC&pg=PA43 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=43 |isbn=}}</ref>. But it quickly reached capacity by the 1930s due to major population growth of Toronto and its surrounding region.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotiabankarena.com/venue-information/about/history|title=History {{!}} Scotiabank Arena|last=Arena|first=Scotiabank|website=www.scotiabankarena.com|language=en|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref>. In 1937 the Postmaster General appealed to the Minister of Public Works to approve a new replacement facility at the corner of Bay & Fleet Street (now Lake Shore Boulevard). Approval was granted by the federal Department of Public Works in part to stimulate the depression impacted construction industry<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. Design and construction of the warehouse built with steel & concrete would begin in 1938. Designed by [[Charles B. Dolphin]] it's a building that incorporates a combination of [[Art Deco]] and [[Art Moderne]] architectural style. The original building would be built for around $2,000,000 (CAD)<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location=Toronto |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref> [$ 35 million 2020],  The building was strategically located south of Union Station and was connected directly to the train platforms via an underground tunnel. Trains would be able to directly unload mail and move it directly to the mail sorting centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Toronto Postal Delivery Building Postcard.jpg|thumb|left|Toronto Postal Delivery Building c.1950s]]\nUpon completion in 1941 the building would be temporarily handed over to Department of National Defence for wartime storage purposes, and be finally turned over to Canada Post in 1946. Required modifications were made to the building to return it back to its postal delivery purposes as a result of alterations done by the Department of National Defence.  After the refurbishment work was completed in 1948, the building now possessed the capability and equipment for proper mail sorting and other mailing processing functions. Though it was designed as a mail sorting warehouse it was also the home of Postal Station \"A\" which served mostly institutional & commercial clients.  The Ground floor was where the mail was dropped off by both railway carts and postal vans. Unsorted mail was moved by conveyor belts to the top floor and via gravity fed mail chutes sorted by size & destination.  Eventually the sorted mail would end up back on the ground floor where it would be sent out for delivery<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020</ref>. The building would be used as a postal sorting centre up until 1989.\n\n====Postal Building Sculptures==== \nThe structures most notable feature (which has been retained) are the exterior 13-part series of limestone [[bas relief]] carvings by [[Louis Temporale]] Sr. [[Order of Canada|CM]] which depicts the history of transportation and communication in Canada. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tayloronhistory.com/2013/02/12/torontos-architectural-gemsthe-postal-delivery-building-now-the-acc/|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>.  Carved in 1938-39 begins with scenes showing human speech, a runner carrying a message, aboriginals communicating by smoke signal, a group of voyageurs, a schooner & a Royal Mail steamship crossing the ocean from England, the CN train used during the 1939 Royal Tour, the mythical flying boat named 'Canopus' and northern travel by dog sled<ref>{{cite book |last=Filey |first=Mike |author-link= |date=1992 |title=Toronto Sketches: The Way We Were |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NNUAuL5S7gUC&pg=PA82 |location= |publisher=Dundurn Press |page=82 |isbn=}}</ref>. The sculptors son Louis Temporale jr. helped with restoration efforts in 1998 and in 2016 was still critical of the lack of protection of the artwork by stadium ownership for over 20 years. The nearby elevated Gardiner Expressway results in salt spray which is speeding up the deterioration of the limestone<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/mlse-acc-art-temporale-heritage-1.3395714|title=History|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>. \n\n====1990s Transition to Stadium====\nThe the late 1980s, the building & antiquated sorting equipment was in need of major renovations & expensive upgrades. In a cost cutting move (part of larger overall service changes & cuts made to the Crown Corporation under the [[Brian Mulroney]] Conservatives), Canada Post decided to close the facility and move operations to an alternate more modern c.1970s letter processing faculty on nearby Eastern Avenue. A structure with easy access to highways was designed specificity for transport truck delivery of mail. By 1989, all of the old building's work was transferred here.<ref name=\":0\" />. The 1980s real estate boom saw the building site become surrounded by skyscrapers, hotels, convention centres, SkyDome stadium & condo towers.  In the early 1990s, real estate developers [[Bramalea (company)|Bramalea Ltd]] and [[Trizec Properties|Trizec]] arranged to purchase the building from Canada Post, and redevelop the site into a {{convert|230,000|m2|sqft|adj=on}} office, retail and residential space. Financial and development details of the purchase imposed various conditions prior to development, including rezoning by the city, remediation of soil contamination by Canada Post.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bramalea's Moves Shake Taxpayers|first=Stevie|last=Cameron|date=November 15, 1992|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\nDue to financing difficulties & an ongoing recession which saw many downtown Toronto high rise construction projects paused or cancelled resulted in the building's ownership was reverted back to Canada Post in 1993 and with the structure reaming abandoned. The Toronto Raptors purchased the unused building from Canada Post the following year.<ref name=\"rapnba\">{{cite web| url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/history/raptors_history.html/| title=Laying the Groundwork for the NBA in Toronto| website=nba.com| accessdate=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Postal terminal now Air Canada Centre.jpg|thumb|left|The arena retains the eastern & southern walls of the original postal structure built, through a process of [[facadism]].]]\nConstruction of the arena was started by the Toronto Raptors, under their initial ownership group headed by Canadian businessman [[John Bitove]]. In 1995, it had been decided that the NBA would expand into Canada. The Toronto Raptors were created and would need an indoor arena to play in. The Canada Post building was chosen to be the new home of the Raptors due to its downtown location and lot size. Other venues such as [[Exhibition Place]], North York Centre, Bay and Wellesley, and Bay and Dundas were also considered. The Canada Post building was purchased for {{CAD|60}} million.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Raptors initially played in SkyDome (now [[Rogers Centre]]) while the arena was constructed.<ref name=\"blogTo\">{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Bateman|title=That time the Raptors and the Maple Leafs moved to the ACC|url=http://www.blogto.com/city/2014/02/that_time_the_raptors_and_leafs_moved_to_the_acc/|website=blogTo|date=February 22, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Groundbreaking took place in March 1997. The building retained the [[Art Deco]] Queenston limestone facade of the Toronto Postal Delivery Building along the east (along [[Bay Street]]) and south ([[Lake Shore Boulevard]]) walls of that structure, but the rest of the building (facing [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]) was removed to make room for the arena, through the process of [[facadism]]. The original building is protected under the ''[[Ontario Heritage Act]]''.\n\n====Arena 'Wars'====\nWhen MLGL ([[Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment|Maple Leaf Gardens, Limited]] at the time the controlling company of the Toronto Maple Leafs) lost out on their desire to be the franchise owners of the Raptors, competition between the two organizations heated up centred around venues. MLGL declined to allow Maple Leaf Gardens to be used for the NBA upstart as a result pushing Bitove to secure rights to have the Raptors' opening seasons played at SkyDome until construction of the new stadium to be complete.\n\nThe 1930s-era Maple Leaf Gardens was showing its age; the Maple Leafs in desperate desire for a new facility began developing plans for building an all-new stadium with one of the key criteria for the new location that it must be within close walking proximity to both the subway system and GO Transit. During the early stages of construction, MLGL floated to the media plans for their own plans to build a competing single-use stadium on adjacent property just to the north of the stadium atop the train sheds at Union Station (similar to how [[Madison Square Garden]] was constructed) as the new home for the Toronto Maple Leafs.<ref name=ArenaWars>{{cite news|title=Leafs ready to Move (Page 2)|first=Craig|last=Daniels|date=April 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Toronto Sun]]}}</ref> The reaction from Raptors was nothing but anger. \"This proposed (Maple Leaf) location really disturbs us\" stated team president Richard Peddie, who went on to say that they would fight the Leafs \"every step of the way\" and he didn't understand why the Leafs have refused to join with the Raptors at their site; claiming that the Leafs want to \"build virtually on top of us\".<ref name=\"ArenaWars\" /> The major problem of the Union Station proposal is the land that the stadium would be built on was actually City of Toronto land that was leased out to CN Rail and CP Rail, which were in a major, long-standing dispute over rent payments (dating back to 1969). As a result, MLGL offered the city $156 Million (1997 CAD) in cash & assets to settle any and all outstanding claims and to buy the air rights above the Union Station train platforms.\n\nDuring this period John Bitove who disputed over the future of the arena who as a result of a [[shotgun clause]] was forced to sell his stake to Allan Slaight (who wanted a joint arena deal with MLGL) and now with majority ownership immediately went into talks with MLGL which eventually purchased both the Raptors and their partially completed arena, which subsequently resulted in major modifications to the original design, which was basketball-specific, to make the arena become more suitable for hockey. Originally planned to cost $217&nbsp;million, MLGL increased the budget to $265&nbsp;million after taking control.<ref name=cost>{{cite news|title=Upgrades added to cost|first=David|last=Shoalts|date=February 17, 1999|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref> The Raptors were twice fined a million dollars (which were donated to their charitable foundation) by the NBA for missing deadlines to begin construction of their new arena.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors' arena bites dust|last=Christe|first=James|date=May 16, 1997|publisher=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>\n\n====Construction==== \nAfter the purchase of the Raptors and the Air Canada Centre the new owners entered into a design-build contract with PCL with the commitment to finish the stadium in 24-months by March 1st 1999<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>.  The intergartion of the Maple Leafs into the new structure would result in a 25% increase in construction costs (over $25 million CAD in 1999)<ref>https://canada.constructconnect.com/dcn/news/projects/2017/03/pcl-construction-reflects-on-building-the-air-canada-centre-1022273w</ref>. \n\nThe completed structure included a 15-storey tower (reduced from a proposed 30-stories), four restaurants, and an underground parking lot. \n\n====Opening====\nIn 1998, a strange twist of scheduling conflicts had the Toronto Raptors playing their final regular-season game at [[Copps Coliseum]] in Hamilton, as the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] had first right of refusal for all SkyDome dates.  The Raptors had attempted to play the April 19 match at Maple Leaf Gardens, but were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite news|title=Raptors Move Final Game to Hamilton|date=January 7, 1998|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|url=https://www.apnews.com/7027ff09054e45b3b7471205f12cb521}}</ref>\n[[File:Air Canada Centre in 1999.jpg|thumb|right|Air Canada Centre in July 1999, five months after the arena opened]]\n\nOn December 30th 1998, the building's construction was completed, 9 days ahead of schedule. Opening events took place early the next year and [[Steve Stavro]] (who was the majority shareholder of MLGL) was named CEO. The initial hockey game took place February 20, 1999 (Toronto Maple Leafs vs. [[Montreal Canadiens]]), the first basketball Game on February 21, 1999 (Toronto Raptors vs. [[Vancouver Grizzlies]]), and the opening concert on February 22, 1999 ([[The Tragically Hip]]).<ref name=\":0\" /> Features of the new building consist of a {{convert|65000|sqft|adj=on}} arena and a {{convert|165000|sqft|adj=on}} office tower. There is also an east\u2013west covered, climate controlled galleria and walkway onsite that contains restaurants, the ticket office, and other commercial units. The Galleria also connects Scotiabank Arena to popular locations in the downtown core such as Union Station, Bay Street and York Street. Scotiabank Arena is connected to the underground PATH network. The Galleria also doubles as a historical museum by displaying numerous artifacts from the old Canada Post building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pcl.com/Projects-that-Inspire/Pages/Air-Canada-Centre.aspx|title=Air Canada Centre|work=PCL Constructors|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn its first ten years of operation, the new arena had an estimated economic benefit of $2.4&nbsp;billion. This boosted Toronto's economy and led to further construction in the downtown core. Many projects in the area were completed ahead of schedule as a result of a desire to increase the infrastructure of downtown Toronto, and also from private funding (approximately $13&nbsp;million) that was invested in seeing the economic growth of Toronto. These projects included the Bay West Teamway, Union Plaza, the Galleria (shopping centre), and Bremner Boulevard.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[Air Canada]] purchased [[naming rights]] to the arena for US$30&nbsp;million for 20 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/marketing/|work=CBC News|title=Branding for dollars|date=February 15, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==Current History== \n[[File:PATH Escalators Construction Scotiabank Arena.jpg|thumb|right|Escalators for a new [[PATH (Toronto)|PATH]] system connection to the under-construction [[CIBC Square]] office complex being installed in the arena's lobby in 2019]]\nIn 2003, MLSE completed a $5-million upgrade of the arena, including a new LED signage system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=459588|title=Air Canada Centre Renovations to Improve Ultimate Fan Experience|date=September 9, 2003|accessdate=January 6, 2014|publisher=[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]}}</ref>  During the summer of 2015, a $10-million upgrade of the arena was carried out, which included the installation of a new scoreboard four times larger than the previous one. The old scoreboard was later installed at [[Coca-Cola Coliseum|Ricoh Coliseum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2015/07/24/acc-to-debut-new-scoreboard-this-year.html|title=Air Canada Centre to debut new scoreboard this year|first=Raju|last=Mudhar|date=July 24, 2015|accessdate=July 24, 2015|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the winter of 2003\u20132004, the [[Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario]] imposed a seven-day penalty on the arena for \"permitting drunken patrons to be in the licensed patrons{{sic}}\" in the fall of 2002 at a Toronto Maple Leafs game and also a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert. As a result of these misdemeanours, there was no alcohol served at the arena from December 21 to 28 in 2003. The venue had multiple major events during this time frame, which included a Toronto Raptors\u2013[[Orlando Magic]] game on December 21, a Toronto Maple Leafs\u2013[[Florida Panthers]] game on December 23, and [[Disney on Ice]]: [[Toy Story 2]], which ran from December 25, 2003 to January 1, 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/air-canada-centre-loses-liquor-licence-for-a-week-1.401537|title=Air Canada Centre loses liquor licence for a week {{!}} CBC Sports|work=CBC|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n[[File:DSC08942 - Legends Row (37049346192).jpg|thumb|In September 2014, a group of life-sized statues were installed at the southwest corner of the arena.]]\nOn September 6, 2014, a group of statues known as ''Legends Row'' was unveiled outside the arena at the southwest corner of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/leafs/2014/09/06/maple_leaf_legends_row_unveils_first_three_honourees.html|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row starts with Ted Kennedy, Darryl Sittler, Johnny Bower|publisher=Torstar Corporation|accessdate=September 27, 2018|work=Toronto Star|date=September 7, 2014|last=Rubin|first=Josh}}</ref> The statues were situated in multiple waves from 2014 to 2016 and include [[Ted Kennedy (ice hockey)|Ted Kennedy]], [[Johnny Bower]], [[Darryl Sittler]], [[B\u00f6rje Salming|Borje Salming]], [[Syl Apps]], [[George Armstrong (ice hockey)|George Armstrong]], [[Mats Sundin]], [[Dave Keon]], [[Turk Broda]], and [[Tim Horton]]. In 2017, the final four statues were unveiled including [[Red Kelly]], [[Frank Mahovlich]], [[Charlie Conacher]], and [[Wendel Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/maple-leafs-legends-row-adds-conacher-kelly-mahovlich-and-clark/c-286915412|title=Maple Leafs Legends Row 'is full' with four added|website=NHL.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 15, 2018}}</ref> ''Legends Row'' now features 14 life-sized statues of former Maple Leaf players alongside a {{convert|9|m|ft|adj=mid|-long|round=5}} granite players' bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/2017/10/05/4-more-leafs-added-to-legends-row/wcm/53247716-67d7-445e-9f20-a91a51890592|title=Four more Maple Leafs added to Legends Row|work=Toronto Sun|publisher=Postmedia Network Inc.|date=October 5, 2017|last=Hornby|first=Lance|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Renaming====\nThe Air Canada Centre was renamed Scotiabank Arena on July 1, 2018. The landmark 20-year sponsorship agreement between Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment and [[Scotiabank]] is worth about C$800&nbsp;million. This is believed to be the highest-priced annual building and team sponsorship in North American sports history.<ref name=\"MLSEScotiaBankArena\">{{cite news|title=HOME OF THE MAPLE LEAFS AND RAPTORS TO BECOME SCOTIABANK ARENA NEXT SUMMER|url=http://mlse.com/news/scotiabankarena/|publisher=[[Maple Leaf Sports & Entertainment]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"WestheadTSN\">{{cite news|last=Westhead|first=Rick|title=MLSE agrees to record arena rights deal with Scotiabank|url=https://www.tsn.ca/talent/mlse-agrees-to-record-arena-rights-deal-with-scotiabank-1.842133|website=[[The Sports Network|TSN]]|date=August 29, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref> The arena is the third in Canada to bear naming rights to Scotiabank.\n\n==Maple Leaf Square==\n[[File:First period play gets a little rowdy.jpg|thumb|A popular gathering point during [[Toronto Maple Leafs|Maple Leafs]] and [[Toronto Raptors|Raptors]] playoff runs, the arena has a large video screen that overlooks the atrium of Maple Leaf Square.]]\n{{main|Maple Leaf Square}}\nIn late 2005, Maple Leaf Sports and Entertainment announced that they would be renovating the western side of the Air Canada Centre during the 2008 off-season to connect it with the [[Maple Leaf Square]] development. Maple Leaf Square is jointly owned by MLSE, [[Cadillac Fairview]] and Lantera Developments. The $500&nbsp;million development includes two restaurants, Hotel Le Germain at Maple Leaf Square boutique hotel, extensive retail shopping, including a {{convert|840|m2|sqft|adj=on}} Leafs, [[Toronto Marlies|Marlies]], Raptors, and [[Toronto FC]] store, two 54-storey condominiums, a [[Longo's]] supermarket, and a public square. It opened in 2010. The two-year, $48&nbsp;million renovation of the ACC added a new atrium that includes a High-Definition broadcast studio for [[Leafs Nation Network]] (formerly Leafs TV), [[NBA TV Canada]] and [[GolTV (Canadian TV channel)|GolTV Canada]].\n\nThe outside wall of the atrium features a {{convert|9.1|by|15.2|m|ft|adj=on}} video screen overlooking the plaza, which often broadcasts games taking place inside the arena. During [[Stanley Cup playoffs|NHL]] and [[NBA playoffs|NBA playoff]] runs, the square attracts thousands of Leafs and Raptors fans, respectively, sometimes broadcasting away playoff matches featuring the Leafs and/or the Raptors as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Canada Centre Re-Opens Bigger And Better After Summer Hiatus|url=http://www.nba.com/raptors/news/accexpansion_presser_091109.html|publisher=NBA Media Ventures, LLC|website=NBA.com/Raptors|date=September 11, 2009|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref> A section of the square is designated Ford Fan Zone at Maple Leaf Square, with naming rights given to the [[Ford Motor Company of Canada]]. During Raptors playoff runs, the square has acquired the nickname \"[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]]\" after the 1993 film adaptation that inspired the team's name. During the [[2019 NBA Playoffs]] and especially during the [[2019 NBA Finals]], other city squares across Canada also acquired the Jurassic Park nickname, such as in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/raptors-jurassic-park-spin-offs-ontario-1.5159009|publisher=CBC|title=Jurassic Park spin-offs popping up as Raptors fever sweeps Canada|author=Lucas Powers}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\n===Concerts===\n{{main|List of entertainment events at Scotiabank Arena}}\n\n===Political conventions===\nIn 2003, the governing [[Liberal Party of Canada]] held their [[2003 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|leadership convention]] at the Air Canada Centre. [[Paul Martin]] was elected as the new leader of the party and thus also became [[Prime Minister of Canada|prime minister]], succeeding [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]].\n\n===Sports===\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1 = Raptors vs Bucks 2.jpg\n | width1 = 165\n | image2 = Buffalo Bandits at Toronto Rock.jpg\n | width2 = 155\n | image3 = Toronto AirCanadaCenter 01.jpg\n | width3 = 165\n |footer= Scotiabank Arena is a [[Multi-purpose stadium|multi-purpose arena]] that is able to host a number of sporting events, including basketball, box lacrosse, and ice hockey.\n}}\nThe first Maple Leafs home game took place on February 20, 1999, versus the Montreal Canadiens, won by the Leafs 3\u20132 on an [[overtime (ice hockey)|overtime]] goal by [[Steve Thomas (ice hockey)|Steve Thomas]]. Maple Leaf home games are generally sold out,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Cheryl|title=Toronto Maple Leafs|url=http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/toronto-maple-leafs/#h3_jump_10|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> and there is a waitlist since the start of 2015 for Season Ticket Holders for upcoming seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Purchase Season Seats|url=http://mapleleafs.nhl.com/club/page.htm?id=73129|website=Toronto Maple Leafs|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> The first Raptors game took place the following night versus the then-[[Memphis Grizzlies|Vancouver Grizzlies]]. The Raptors won 102\u201387 in front of a sell-out crowd. The facility hosted the [[2000 National Hockey League All-Star Game|2000 NHL All-Star Game]], the championship game of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], all games of the [[2016 World Cup of Hockey]] and the [[2016 NBA All-Star Game]], the first NBA All-Star Game held outside of the United States.\n\nThe Toronto Rock also moved to the Air Canada Centre from Maple Leaf Gardens for the [[2001 NLL season]]. The Rock's first game was a 17\u20137 win over the [[Ottawa Rebel]] on December 21, 2000.\n\nOn October 3, 2003, Air Canada Centre had a power outage during the third quarter of a Raptors pre-season game against the Athens-based club [[Panathinaikos B.C.|Panathinaikos]]. The game was called final, because the power was not restored in time and the Raptors already had a [[Mercy rule|30-point lead]].\n\nAir Canada Centre hosted the [[2015 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships]] for the first time, as well as hosted the final match of that tournament, in which Canada was crowned champion, defeating Russia. The ACC co-hosted that tournament with [[Bell Centre]] in Montreal, and both venues co-hosted the [[2017 World Junior Ice Hockey Championships|2017 edition of the same event]], though the ACC did not host the medal rounds.\n[[File:Laura Wright performs during the Invictus Flag Raising (37021670620).jpg|thumb|Flag raising during the [[2017 Invictus Games]] closing ceremonies]]\nIn 2017, the Air Canada Centre hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for [[2017 Invictus Games|that year's Invictus Games]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.invictusgames2017.com/ceremonies/|title=Ceremonies|publisher=Invictus Games Toronto 2017|year=2016|accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2017, the ACC presented the opening ceremony as a live two-hour event spectacular. This ceremony was designed to welcome and honour the 550 competitors and their families who come from 17 different competing nations. The show featured hundreds of cast members, including honorary men and women from the [[Canadian Armed Forces]]. The cast showed a display of ceremony in multiple different productions and the raising of the flag. Other guests of the event included celebrities, world dignitaries, headline music stars and other special guests. They gathered to celebrate the service and stories of the members of the 2017 Invictus Games. Headline performers included [[Laura Wright (singer)|Laura Wright]], [[Alessia Cara]], [[The Tenors]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], and [[La Bottine Souriante]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe ACC hosted the Invictus Games Toronto 2017 Closing Ceremony on September 20, 2017. The event featured an arrangement of international headline music artists, coming together to celebrate and recognize the Invictus Games competitors. The closing ceremony featured headline musical guests [[Bachman & Turner]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[C\u0153ur de pirate|Coeur de Pirate]], [[Bruce Springsteen]], and [[Kelly Clarkson]]. This celebration also included words from world dignitaries as the Games are passed to the host nation of the [[2018 Invictus Games|Invictus Games 2018]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe venue hosted its first championship series when the Raptors played the [[Golden State Warriors]] in Games 1, 2, and 5 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]]. The Raptors won the NBA championship, albeit in the Warriors' home arena of [[Oracle Arena]] in [[Oakland]] in Game 6.\n\nThe arena has also played host to five [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC) events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmajunkie.com/news/2013/05/ufc-165-heads-to-air-canada-centre-in-toronto-on-sept-21|title=UFC 165 heads to Air Canada Centre in Toronto on Sept. 21|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=May 14, 2013|accessdate=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"UFC206\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/8/19/12562718/ufc-releases-schedule-for-rest-of-2016-including-ufc-206-in-toronto|title=UFC releases schedule for rest of 2016 including UFC 206 in Toronto|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Marc Raimondi|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 19, 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! Date\n|-\n| [[UFC 140]]\n| Saturday, December 10, 2011\n|-\n| [[UFC 152]]\n| Saturday, September 22, 2012\n|-\n| [[UFC 165]]\n| Saturday, September 21, 2013\n|-\n| [[UFC 206]]\n|Saturday, December 10, 2016\n|-\n| [[UFC 231]]\n|Saturday, December 8, 2018\n|}\n<!--Please don't add WWE events per consensus-->\n\n===Video game competitions===\nOn August 27 and 28, 2016, Air Canada Centre hosted the [[2016 Summer North American League of Legends Championship Series|sixth season of the Summer North American Championship Series]] of ''[[League of Legends]]'' (LoL), marking the first [[League of Legends Championship Series|professional ''League of Legends'' competition]] in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lolesports.com/en_US/articles/na-summer-finals-coming-toronto|title=LoL Esports|website=www.lolesports.com}}</ref> ''League of Legends'' is a popular [[multiplayer online battle arena]] (MOBA) [[PC game|computer game]] by American video game developer [[Riot Games]]; ''League of Legends'' competitions are among the most viewed among professional video game competitions worldwide. During the final round, [[Team SoloMid]] (TSM) defeated [[Cloud9]] (C9) three matches to one in a best-of-five format. The Summer North American Championship Series serve as the qualifiers for the annual [[League of Legends World Championship]] for North American teams.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- Per [[WP:ELMINOFFICIAL]], choose one official website only -->\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.scotiabankarena.com/}}\n* [http://torontoplaques.com/Pages/Toronto_Postal_Delivery_Building.html Toronto's Historical Plaques; Toronto Postal Delivery Building]\n{{Portal bar|Sports|Ice hockey|Canada|Ontario}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list1=\n&nbsp;\n{{S-start-collapsible|header={{S-sta|et}}}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Raptors]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Rogers Centre|SkyDome]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Maple Leafs]]\n | years = 1999\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Rock]]\n | years = 2000\u2013present\n | before = [[Maple Leaf Gardens]]\n | after = current\n}}\n{{Succession box\n | title = Home of the<br />[[Toronto Phantoms]]\n | years = 2001\u201320